{"title_page": "Paul Martin (illustrator)", "text_new": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Paul Martin\n| image = Paul_Martin_(illustrator),_studio_portrait.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = photo <!-- by Campbell Studio, New York --> taken between 1911 & 1913\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|6|6|mf =y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf =yes|1932|3|19|1883|6|6}}\n| death_place = [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining, New York]]\n| education = [[National Academy of Design]]\n| occupation = [[Illustrator]]\n| spouse = Lauretta Willey (1880-1972)\n}}\n\n'''Paul Martin''' (June 6, 1883, New York City, New York \u2013 March 19, 1932, Ossining, New York)<ref>Register of Deaths for the Village of Ossining, N.Y. His then home address was in the nearby hamlet of Millwood. ''U.S. Census of 1930''. Backup source.</ref> was a [[graphic designer|graphic artist]] and [[illustrator]]. His artwork appeared on nine different magazine covers from 1923 to 1932. Martin designed the then-world's largest ever electrical display in 1917. He reshaped the then-iconic Fisk Tire Boy in late 1929. He played in [[tennis]] tournaments around the [[New York metropolitan area|Greater New York area]] from 1909 to 1931. Also in the [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] of 1920-[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]], 24 (all after age 35).<ref>Men's Singles was held at the [[Germantown Cricket Club]] in Philadelphia from 1921-23. It then returned to [[Forest Hills, Queens|Forest Hills]].</ref> The annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament is named after him.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of illustration began in the 1880s.<ref>[https://www.rafoxsociety.com/what-was-the-golden-age-of-illustration/ \"Golden Age\"]. Path: R. Atkinson Fox Society's homepage>Links>See More. Its key source was ''[[The Artist's Magazine|American Artist]]'' magazine (1937-2012), June 2006.</ref> Major advancements in printing techniques were then taking place. This included breakthroughs in the [[halftone]] process. It made the printing of images for commercial usage more economical, feasible, and realistic. The reproduction of art from [[wood engraving]]s (time consuming and strenuous), was largely replaced with [[photoengraving|photo-mechanical engravings]] (higher accuracy level).<ref>''Scribner's Magazine''. \"American Illustration and the Reproductive  Arts\" by Carrington, July 1922 pp. 123-28. (Viewable online at www.unz.com.)</ref> These and other methods were utilized by artist, writer, teacher, innovator\u2013[[Howard Pyle]], who is generally regarded as \"The Father of American Illustration.\"<ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 10, 1911 p. 11. Obit column. Excerpt: \"He was almost [or like] the father of American magazine illustration, as it is known to-day.\"</ref> Others who gained fame in this field included [[Howard Chandler Christy]], [[Harrison Fisher]], [[James Montgomery Flagg]], [[Charles Dana Gibson]], [[John Held Jr.]], [[J. C. Leyendecker]], [[Maxfield Parrish]], [[Coles Phillips]], [[Frederic Remington]], [[Norman Rockwell]], [[Jessie Willcox Smith]] and [[N. C. Wyeth]].\n\nHowever, the vast majority of illustrators received little recognition, compared to the [[fine art]]ists. This was basically due to their artwork being viewed as more commercially, than creatively inspired. Nonetheless, these unheralded illustrators played a powerful role, in communicating the people's aspirations, concerns, customs, humor, labor, morals and social interests.<ref name=\"historical\">''Cover Story: The Art of American Magazine Covers 1900-1950'' by Heller & Fili, 1996.</ref> One of them was Paul Martin, whose work appeared on the covers of ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]'', ''[[Farm & Fireside]]'', ''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' and ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' from 1923-31. These seven magazines were once ranked among the most widely circulated. They all went out of business long ago, except for ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''. Their eventual downfall was caused by the changing times (or taste), emergence of radio and television (more attractive medium for advertisers), and economics (increased cost / decreased revenue). The more specialized ones that targeted specific audiences, tended to fare better. Another point is that major advancements in photographic equipment and technology took place during the 1930s. This brought about the gradual changeover (twenty-five+ year process) from illustrated to photographic covers.<ref name=\"historical\"/> The former still lingered on, for its innovative and enchanting qualities, until succumbing to digital media (especially [[Adobe Photoshop|Photoshop]]).\n\n==Collier's==\n[[File:Collier's10-25-24.jpg|thumb|117px|(Calling the play) ''Collier's'' 10-25-1924]]\nGeneral interest magazines (mixture of entertainment, pictures, politics, serials, short stories and sports) were once very popular and appealed to diverse audiences. One of them was the historically significant ''[[Collier's]]'' (founded 1888), which had a revival under new editor [[Collier's#Editors|William L. Chenery]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Collier's\">''A Cavalcade of Collier's'', edited by McArdle (''Collier's'' last editor), 1959 pp. xii-xiii.</ref><ref>''Magazines in the Twentieth Century'', Peterson, 1956 p. 188; ''The New York Times'', August 20, 1974 p. 38.</ref> Martin drew many of its covers during the mid-[[Roaring Twenties]], including seven in 1925 (twenty 1923\u201327). Some artists created a niche and then stuck with it, such as in drawing comical situations, domestic follies, political satire, pretty women or simple pleasures. His recurring theme was of a youthful boy engaged in various lighthearted activities. This included the following:<ref>These seventeen described activities, each appeared on a ''Collier's'' cover between Feb. 2, 1924 and Aug. 27, 1927. Their exact dates are collectively listed in this article, under the heading \"Magazine cover illustrator.\"</ref> catching a baseball, loading up on desserts ''(pictured below)'', playing the flute,<ref name=\"flute\">[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200182868/ \"Collier's\" (6-24)]. Library of Congress at loc.gov. Select: \"Photos, Prints, Drawings.\" Enter: \"Correct Position for the Fingers.\" A beginning flutist wearing a sailor suit and red bow.</ref> decked out in a straw hat, shooting marbles, shoveling snow, carrying books on head, riding a sled, winding up a spinning top, eating turkey at Christmas, bobbing for apples, playing football ''(pictured)'',<ref>[https://fourthgarrideb.com/2014/11/09/colliers-magazine-cover-for-october-25-1925-the-three-garridebs/ \"Collier's\" (10-24)]. \"The Fourth Garrideb - Numismatics of Sherlock Holmes.\" Posted online by G. Ruby, Nov. 9, 2014.</ref> happily swimming, getting a shaved haircut, saying grace, working as a messenger, daydreaming about fishing<ref name=\"school\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-W_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=American+Education+in+Popular+Media:+From+the+Blackboard+to+the+Silver+Screen#v=snippet&q=%22refuge%22&f=false \"Collier's\" (9-25)]. ''American Education in Popular Media'', edited by Terzian & Ryan, 2015 p. 74.</ref> and going down a water slide.<ref name=\"slide\">[https://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Collier'sSlide.jpg \"Collier's\" (8-27)]. Commons. A joyful boy & apprehensive dog, going down a water slide together.</ref> He seldom veered from this subject matter. The most striking departure was for a self-portrait cover. He portrayed himself as a well-dressed, vocal spectator at the [[horse racing|horse races]].<ref name=\"races\">[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Collier's6-27-25.jpg \"Collier's\" (6-25)]. Head shot with add-on mustache. He's wearing a derby hat (amid red carnations).</ref>\n\nHis drawing style was simple yet bold. It captured the carefreeness and innocence of youth. There was a nostalgic element to them. Martin excluded the non-essential details (extra people, structures, trees, scenery etc.), which allowed viewers to make an instant connection. His paintings were often easy to recognize, since their theme and style remained fairly consistent. They sometimes gave the illusion of three-dimensional depth. This was through the use of various techniques, such as overlapping, color intensity or variation and [[perspective (graphical)|linear perspective]]. His cover art never corresponded to anything in particular, but rather had a holiday or seasonal theme or portrayed the magazine's overall image (common practice back then).<ref>''Collier's'' usually preferred cover art that conveyed plain and simple thoughts, unlike its main rival in the ''Post''.</ref> Martin mostly hired local boys for the [[photo shoot|photo sessions]].<ref name=\"hard\">''Hard Row to Hoe'' (literary newsletter), V-9 Fall 2005. \"Golden Era of the Illustrations\" pp. 1-3. Joe E. (Edwin) Armstrong in collaboration with Martin's niece Adele. Excerpts: \"[The] Fisk Tire advertisement, 'A Time to Retire,' with Adele's brother Walter as a model, was his best known work.\" The niece recalled visiting the artist on a particular occasion, with her brother and sister: \"We climbed the oak stairs to the second floor  ... [and] entered a huge bright room ... This was my uncle's studio. ... Although my uncle generally used local models, especially boys, some of our family posed for photographs which would later miraculously turn into paintings. My grandmother was depicted in a Thanksgiving scene basting a turkey ... My brother and I sat for ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls'' while Uncle Paul took our picture, as we sat on the kitchen table of our own house. My sister modeled for Junior Red Cross posters (only one confirmed). [S]he posed as well, taking a license number from a boy's homemade car, for hitting her carriage and doll.\" [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> His drawings were made directly from those photos, and not real life (which required long sittings). This gave him more options and flexibly, as the final version was based on multiple photos taken during the shoot (along with some improvising).<ref>[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._1.jpg|Photo Session #1]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared in the ''Saturday Evening Post'' of Nov. 22, 1930, p. 37. Artist signed. The boy, girls, and refrigerator were photographed separately.</ref><ref name=\"memorial\">[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._2.jpg|Photo Session #2]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared on the cover of ''Foreign Service'' in May 1932. Artist signed. The boy is holding a matchbox on a paintbrush stick, in lieu of a flower.</ref> It was also a more practical process, due to active children being involved. He would interact with them, until getting the desired natural or candid expression. His wife assisted in preparing the models for their scenes. ''[[Collier's]]'' couldn't keep up with the rapidly changing times following [[World War II|WWII]], and ceased publication in December 1956.<ref name=\"Collier's\"/> The main culprit was television, which dramatically affected its advertising and circulation revenue. ''Collier's'' top competitors (''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Post]]'') adapted somewhat better to the changing times, which helped them hold out longer.\n\n==Graphic artist==\n[[File:H-O_Oats.jpg|left|thumb|139px|H-O Oats, outdoor advertising sign, 1931]]\n[[File:BoyandPups.jpg|thumb|117px|Gerlach Barklow calendar, \"Singin' in the Rain,\" 1931]]\n[[File:Martin_gets_check.jpg|left|thumb|139px|Martin gets a $300 winner's check, 1931]]\nMartin designed [[Wrigley Company|Wrigley Gum's]] light bulb spectacular, which showcased six acrobatic \"[[Wrigley's Spearmint|spearmen]]\" on a [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] billboard in 1917. It was then the world's largest ever electrical display at 200' x 50'. It covered the entire city block between 43rd and 44th Streets.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', June 1917 p. 33; ''New York Tribune'', November 10, 1917 p. 1; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', April 29, 1920 p. 6. These [[primary source]]s give descriptions of Wrigley's gleaming sign, that was directed toward the masses. Its energetic mascots with green-pointed heads, promoted the chewy gum's healthy aspects.</ref><ref>[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/510d47e1-0689-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99 Simulated Movements]. New York Public Library. Digital Collections. This photo doesn't capture the entire rooftop sign. Another three sprightly \"spearmen\" are on the left side. The six of them are doing 'setting-up exercises.' ''The Evening Star'' (D.C.), July 17, 1923 p. 6; ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (NYC), Feb. 7, 1924 p. 18. It operated from 1917-24.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UK5FAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Wrigley's Gem]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', October 1920 pp. 25 (photograph), 26 (description). Scroll far downward. It was located atop the old Putnam Bldg. That site is now occupied by the [[1501 Broadway|Paramount Bldg.]] ''Illustrated World'', March 1920 pp. 689, 691. Another source with photo/desc.</ref><ref>[https://image.slidesharecdn.com/hist-display-121122214349-phpapp01/95/history-of-lighting-display-exhibit-16-638.jpg Animated Display]. \"History of lighting - display & exhibit\" - SlideShare. Posted online by J. Fonseca, Nov. 22, 2012. The anthropomorphic gymnasts, bubbling fountains and fluttering peacocks, are framed within a vine-like floral design. Also reachable via slideshare.net. Enter: \"History & Theory of Interior Illumination\">click icon>move arrow to pic #16.</ref><ref>''One Times Square'' by McKendry, 2012 p. 17. A watercolor of the fully animated, moving lights, attention-grabber.</ref> This [[Times Square]] light show, was a major tourist attraction for seven years. He drew a poster titled \"Serve Your Country,\" for the War Camp Community Service in 1918. It showed a fashionable young woman serving in tennis ([[wikt:play on words|play on words]]).<ref>[https://collectionscanada.gc.ca/pam_archives/index.php?fuseaction=genitem.displayItem&lang=eng&rec_nbr=3667979 \"Serve\" #1]. [[Library and Archives Canada]]. Path: LAC homepage>Search the Collection>Collection Search. Enter: \"Serve Your Country, Benefit of War Camp Activities.\" Size: 11 x 17\". Many artists lent their talents to the war effort. He registered for the draft later that year, when the cut-off age was upped from 31 to 45. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ServeCntyTennis.jpg \"Serve\" #2]. Commons.</ref> Women were encouraged to entertain off-duty soldiers, by participating in various social events (dancing, dining etc.).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/whatnewyorkdidfo00warc#page/n1/mode/2up \"General Summary\"]. ''What New York Did for Fighting Men: Through New York War Camp Community Service in the World-War of 1917-1919'', 1919 pp. 3-4.</ref> A silkscreen version of this poster, has been periodically on display at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>It was donated by Bessie Holden in 1965. This is stated within the frame. ''The Sun'', April 21, 1918 sec. 7 p. 8; July 16, 1918 p. 13. She helped organize the National Tennis Women's War Relief Association. ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 09, 1919 p. 15; June 2, 1920 p. 13; June 16, 1920 p. 13; July 26, 1921 p. 12; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 23, 1922 p. A2; Sept. 24, 1930 p. 25; ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', Feb. 27, 1923 p. 10. Holden and Mrs. Martin both played in these tourneys.</ref> Another two were for the [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]]. The first was titled \"The Flag of Service the World Around\" in 1929. It showed children in international costumes on top of a globe, with one holding a large Red Cross flag.<ref name=\"Red Cross\">''Newport (R.I.) Mercury and Weekly News'', Sept. 6, 1929 p. 5. Heading: \"New Junior Red Cross Poster Designed by Paul Martin, Beautiful and Inspiring.\"</ref> The second was titled \"Juniors Helping Everywhere\" (with twenty miniature scenes) in 1930.<ref name=\"poster\">[https://digicom.bpl.lib.me.us/wwII_posters_redcross/6/ \"American Junior Red Cross\"]. Bangor (Maine) Public Library, Digital Commons@bpl. His niece Edna is pictured second from top right. It's signed in the globe's lower right.</ref> Its purpose was to expand awareness of their various worldwide projects. He created three paintings for the Hecker H-O (Hornby's Oatmeal) Company of [[Buffalo, New York]] in 1931. One showed a confident young football player being patched up, who had oats for breakfast ''(pictured)''.<ref>Titled: \"I don't care, I'm strong.\" Girl cautions boy to be careful, who's wearing a leather football helmet. She's applying a bandage. The girl in real life was the boy's aunt Helen, an older teenager. They went together to this photo session, from their home to the Martins. She walked [[wikt:to and fro|to and fro]], while her young nephew rode a two-wheeled scooter. He traveled/pedaled alone, to all other shoots. [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48644655461_ddb5a9bf75_b.jpg Docs]. Flickr. (Backs up the year.)</ref> The other two emphasized its healthiness<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo2.jpg Weight Gain]. Boy standing on a weighing scale. He says to his real-life aunt, \"You can't call me Skinny now!\" They also posed for another painting for H-O Oats ''(pictured top left)'', during this shoot. [https://archive.org/stream/advertisingoutdo02outdrich#page/562/mode/2up Thumb Pointing]. ''Advertising Outdoors'', November 1931 p. 35. Excerpt: \"Overflowing pep and energy is expressed ... .\" These two images are identical, except that in the latter, McCandlish Litho removed the artist's signature.</ref> and goodness.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo3.jpg Early Riser]. Commons. Boy leaping out of bed, saying, \"Coming mother ... I'm hungry.\"</ref> These advertisements appeared on poster panels, to attract passing motorists and pedestrians. They also had a short run in food markets; on their walls, display windows or hanging from overhead wires.<ref>Their display period was short-lived, since company salesmen continually pushed for their products to be highlighted. This approach existed in the era before food brokers and paid contracts. Many store owners would not allow ads to hang from overhead wires. This was due to their cluttered appearance.</ref>\n\nHe painted three color advertisements for [[General Electric]]'s all-steel [[refrigerator#Domestic refrigerators|\"Monitor Top\" refrigerator]] in 1930. The first and most elaborate featured two boys running a lemonade stand. Their mother is shown looking on with approval, through the open kitchen window.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GE-Lemonade.jpg Ade #1]. ''Saturday Evening Post'', July 26, 1930 p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://nebraskahistory.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/A86A28F8-CE8A-44FD-B8D3-537250952019 Ade #2]. Nebraska State Historical Society. Select: \"Keyword Search.\" Enter: \"Silent Hostess.\"</ref> It appeared as a full-page ad in many different magazines at around the same time.<ref>Mags, 1930: ''Silent Hostess'', vol. 2 no. 5, p. inside cover; ''Post'', July 26 p. 43; ''The American Magazine'', Aug. p. 124; ''Arts & Decoration'', Aug. p. 15; ''Collier's'', Aug. 16 p. 27; ''Country Life'' (pub. in Garden City, N.Y.), Aug. p. 75; ''Ladies' Home Journal'', Aug. p. 70. New York dailies, 1930: ''Auburn Citizen'', July 31 p. 8; ''Friendship Register'', July 24 p. 7; ''Herald Mail'' (Fairport), July 24 p. 10; ''Orleans Republican'', July 23 p. 3; ''Standard Holley'', July 24 p. 5; ''St. Lawrence Plaindealer'', July 15 p. 2.</ref>'' [[Printers' Ink]]'' review from 1930. Excerpt: \"'Electric Lemonaide, 5 cents per glass', reads the sign of the youthful shopkeepers. [They] are soliciting trade in a strenuous manner, as a friendly dog enters into the spirit of the event with challenging barks. ... It is a picture filled with action and story-telling strength. But because the advertised product has been worked in so [[wikt:adroitly|adroitly]], the illustration seems doubly effective and relevant.\"<ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Sept. 18, 1930 pp. 130-32. \"What Constitutes a Story Illustration?\" by W. Livingston Larned.</ref> His other \"Monitor Top\" credits were of a girl playing with blocks (that spell out the company's initials),<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', October 25, 1930 p. 34 (blocks).</ref> and two dressed-up girls listening to an enthusiastic sales boy.<ref>Mags: ''Silent Hostess'', 1930 vol. 2 no. 7, p. inside cover; ''Saturday Evening Post'', Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. Book: ''Advertising the American Dream: Making Way for Modernity, 1920-1940'' by Marchand, 1985 p. 271. Newspapers, 1930: ''Alexandria Times-Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Canyon News'' (Tex.), Nov. 13 p. 16; ''Coshocton Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Evening Journal'' (Del.), Nov. 26 p. 4; ''Friendship Register'', Nov. 20 p. 4; ''Hanover Evening Sun'', Nov. 30 p. 3; ''Independent and Times'' (New Paltz, N.Y.), Nov. 21; ''Indiana Gazette'', Nov. 20 p. 13; ''Jamestown Evening News'' (N.Y.), Nov. 13 p. 15; ''Ludington Daily News'', Aug. 13 p. 7; ''Morning Herald'' (Uniontown, Pa.), Nov. 20 p. 16; ''Patriot and Free Press'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Republican Watchman'', Nov. 14 p. 3; ''Silver Creek News'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Salamanca Republican Press'', Nov. 20-21 p. 3; ''Van Wert Times Bulletin'', Nov. 20 p. 8; ''Wilmington News-Journal'' (Ohio), Nov. 27, 1930 p. 2. Kids playing grown-ups.</ref> It was proclaimed as the first reliable and affordable model for residential use (though at a hefty price). He also drew a cheerful boy eating beans for [[Heinz 57]].<ref>''[[Ladies' Home Journal|Ladies' Home Journal]]'', May 1927 p. 71. \"I Know Beans.\"</ref>\n\nHe designed a contest-winning poster for the [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scouts]] in 1931. It was titled \"Usefulness \u2022 Beauty \u2022 Health \u2022 Truth \u2022 Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"winning\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Excerpts: \"An art enthusiast from his boyhood ... He studied commercial art at the Academy of Design ... Mr. Martin gained a national reputation when he designed the automobile tire advertisement, 'Time to Re-tire' ... He has won several art prizes, including an award last year for drawing the best poster symbolizing the Girl Scout movement. ... Member of the Artists' Guild. He was also a member of the County [Tennis] Club of Westchester and of the Scarsdale Badminton Club.\" The Martins enjoyed playing together, in those two racket sports.</ref><ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (contest-winning). Sizes = 17 x 22\" & 7 x 9.25\".</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200137.pdf \"Prize\"] (PDF). ''The Pelham Sun'', March 13, 1931 p. 7.</ref> This contest was conducted by the Art Alliance of America,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w18oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Art+Alliance+of+America#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Alliance\"]. ''[[American Art Directory|American Art Annual]]'' by the [[American Federation of Arts]], 1921 vol. 17 p. 174. They often held competitions, demonstrations and exhibitions.</ref> an organization that brought together craft workers and manufacturers. The six-judge panel consisted of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw T. Benda|W. T. Benda]] (who replaced [[Charles Dana Gibson]]),<ref name=\"contest\">[https://nyshistoricnewspapers.org/lccn/sn84031094/1931-01-21/ed-1/seq-7/ \"Poster Campaign of Girl Scouts\"]. ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', Jan. 21, 1931 p. 7. Gibson was on the original (not final) judging panel.</ref> Ray Greenleaf, [[Rockwell Kent]], [[John La Gatta]], [[Neysa McMein]] and Edward A. Wilson.<ref name=\"scouting\">[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200110.pdf \"Girl Scout Notes\"] (PDF). [[Fultonhistory.com]]. ''The Pelham Sun'', Feb. 27, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Martin's model for the poster was Barbara Smith, a 14-year-old from Darien, Connecticut (who previously lived in Yonkers, N.Y.).<ref name=\"scouting\"/><ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Nov. 6, 1931 p. 20; ''Citizen Sentinel'', Nov. 9, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Her parents and Martin were lifelong friends. He even served as [[wikt:best man|best man]] at their wedding back in 1904.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 1, 1929 p. 6 (best man). It was held at the bride's family home, on Riverside Ave. (then more commonly known as Dr.) in Manhattan, NYC.</ref> His winning entree earned him a first-place check, from the Girl Scouts' National Director [[Minnesota Woman Suffrage Memorial#Josephine Schain|Josephine Schain]] ''(pictured)''. This exchange took place at their old national headquarters on [[Lexington Avenue]] in [[New York City]]. Also, right after the first, second and third place winners were announced.<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'', Feb. 19, 1931 p. 8; ''Dobbs Ferry Register'', March 13, 1931 p. 11; ''The Daily Plainsman'', March 14, 1931 p. 7 (PM\u2013Schain pic, exchange). The first is a slightly different & fuller pose, which was taken within seconds of the other two.</ref> National President [[James Otis (New York)#Personal life|Mrs. Frederick (Birdsall Otis) Edey]] was one of three consultants, along with executives [[Anne Hyde Choate]] and [[Genevieve Garvan Brady]].<ref name=\"contest\"/> This poster ''(inserted in pictured)'' later appeared with three raised fingers instead of a salute, on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Girl_Scouts_Competition_Letter.jpg The Sign]. A change request is initiated by Gilchriese.</ref> It captured the spirit of their character-building movement, and was in popular usage until 1937.<ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (popular usage). The two catalog dates were verified, by viewing the actual covers. The dates given to them in this book, are slightly off.</ref> Martin said at the award ceremony, \"Barbara seems [to be] the personification of all that [[Girl Guides|Girl Scouting]] means. She is the very spirit of radiant, happy and wholesome young girlhood, and my mind naturally turned to her immediately when I learned of the competition.\"<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), Feb. 17, 1931 p. 6; ''Lockport Union-Sun and Journal'', Feb. 21, 1931 p. 4 (quote).</ref>\n\nHis drawings also ended up on [[Gerlach Barklow Co.|Gerlach Barklow]] calendars, ink blotter cards and prints for business advertising, such as one titled \"Singin' in the Rain\" from 1931. It showed a boy sheltering several pups from the rain with an umbrella, while sitting down ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1932 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first showed up on its calendars, ink blotter cards (3.5 x 6\" with pink backs) and prints in 1931.</ref> Another showed a boy reading about scientific theories with some difficulty.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1933 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first appeared on the cover of ''Parents'' magazine in October 1930. ''Parents'' sold the rights to Gerlach Barklow. One of their artists changed the lettering, and also titled it \"Oh Yeah.\"</ref> Martin's paintings often included a cute and friendly pup (or even several). He drew covers for such [[trade magazine|trade publications]] as ''Advertising & Selling'',<ref name=\"spearmen\">''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. Excerpt: \"It is interesting to note that this [cover] drawing was made by Paul Martin, who while he was with the O. J. Gude Co., designed the famous Wrigley electric sign showing the dancing 'spear-men', still on display in New York. Mr. Martin was for seven years art manager of the ''New York Tribune''.\" This write-up gives him credit for the cover, which otherwise would have gone solely to Gotham Studios. (Gotham's insignia is on it.)</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRwYAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Photo to Sketch]. ''Advertising & Selling'', January 24, 1920 (cover). Scroll upward. Pencil sketch of an executive with [[John Deere|Deere & Company]]. Magazine's lifespan: 1891-1924. It was known as ''Profitable Advertising'' through May 1909.</ref> ''Good Hardware'',<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GoodHardware.jpg Repair]. ''Good Hardware'', Oct. 1930 (man fixing clock). Published by Strevell-Paterson Hardware Co., Salt Lake City.</ref> ''Progressive Grocer'' (voice of the industry for food retailers)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2f08AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Cover Design\"]. ''Progressive Grocer'', Sept. 1922 vol. 1 no. 9 (talking on the phone) & Nov. 1922 vol. 1 no. 11 (weighing a turkey). Credits for them are on pp. 5 & 5. The covers are visible by scrolling nearly all the way down to pp. 113 & 117.</ref> and ''Silent Hostess'' (recipes and tips for homemakers)<ref>''Silent Hostess'' by General Electric, 1930 vol. 2 no. 4 (eating an apple); 1931 vol. 3 no. 4 (flexing muscles); 1931 vol. 3 no. 7 (blowing up a football). Mag's lifespan: 1930-32. Its key purpose was to promote the innovative \"Monitor Top\" refrigerator.</ref> between 1920 & 1931. Coincidentally, the helmet-wearing boy for H-O Oats ''(pictured)'', later served as ''Progressive Grocer's'' associate editor from 1956-62.<ref>''The Daily Bulletin'' (Endicott, N.Y.), Oct. 12, 1956 p. 5. The appointment took effect on Nov. 1.</ref> Martin's first two ''signed'' covers were for this food-oriented magazine.<ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920. Those two are only predated by this ''A&S'' unsigned cover. Its credit is instead, given on p. 12. ''Progressive Grocer'' (1922\u2013). It's dedicated to helping the independent operators.</ref> His work appeared in many different types of print media (including outdoor advertising).<ref>Martin's signature is within every artwork mentioned, in this article. However, there are others unsigned by him, which would be difficult or impossible to prove as credits. A neighbor kid, William Everett [[Millwood, New York#Fire department|Orser]] (1919-2016), posed for him as the [[Dutch Boy Paint|Dutch Boy]]. But no in-print proof. His paintings turned into outdoor signs were not salvageable. Their scaled-down counterparts in grocery markets were largely discarded. Hence, even pictures of them likely don't exist, unless featured in a trade mag.</ref><ref>''The Daily Argus'', Dec. 3, 1921, [[wikt:gravure|gravure]] section. He signed a contract earlier in year, to design greeting cards for [[William Edwin Rudge]]. Its printing plant was located in Mount Vernon, N.Y. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Christmas_card_with_boy,_girl,_dog,_cat.jpg \"Bide-A-Wee\"]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Dec. 11, 1921 p. D23 (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 20, 1921 p. B5; Dec. 17, 1922 p. last; Dec. 16, 1923 p. 33-resorts (\"Skating. Coasting\"); ''New York Tribune'',  Jan. 22, 1922 p. 6; Dec. 03, 1922 p. 5 (\"Skating. Coasting\"); Jan. 29, 1922 p. 6 (\"Snowshoe Trail\"); ''The New York Times'', Feb. 4, 1923 p. 12-resorts (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 9, 1923 p. 7-resorts; Jan. 25, 1925 p. 14-R; Dec. 6, 1925 p. 19-R (\"Skating. Coasting\"). He drew three different pencil sketches, for the [[New York, Ontario and Western Railway|New York, Ontario & Western Railway Co]]. Artist signed.</ref>\n\nAnother credit is mentioned in a publication by the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] in 1932. As follows: \"The cover design on this issue of ''Foreign Service''<ref name=\"memorial\"/> is a two-color reproduction of the official 1932 Buddy Poppy poster.<ref>''Altoona (Pa.) Tribune'', May 21, 1932 p. 5; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; ''Brownsville (Tex.) Herald'', May 17, 1933 p. 2; ''Medford Mail Tribune'', May 21, 1933 p. 4; ''San Bernardino Daily Sun'', May 22, 1933 p. 3; ''Bakersfield Californian'', May 23, 1933 p. 7; ''Boys' Life'', May 1934 p. 44. These are examples of its appearance in print.</ref> (It was so named because former soldiers would use that word, in describing their comrades who perished in [[World War I|WWI]].) The original was painted in oil by the late Paul Martin, noted New York poster artist, who died suddenly on March 19th following a serious operation. The poster has been pronounced as one of the most striking and appropriate designs ever used, to depict the symbolism of the [[remembrance poppy|Buddy Poppy]]. (A bright red artificial flower, which was worn in honor of the fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied soldiers]].) It was completed shortly before the artist's death and is believed to have been his last important assignment [''sic''].<ref>For clarity: The original was painted and sold to ''Parents'' in March 1930. This is based on Mrs. Martin's notes. Also, the model only posed for him from 1930-31. It went unused, and so was sold by ''Parents'' to American Lithographic, and from there to the Veterans of Foreign Wars. They turned this artwork into a poster, and then magazine cover in spring 1932.</ref><ref>''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52 (poster). ''Foreign Service'', May 1932 (cover). Their first known appearances in print. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. His last involvement was with the poster.</ref><ref name=\"reading\">''Parents'', Oct. 1930. A youngster reading their mag with some difficulty. This image later appeared on Gerlach Barklow calendars with altered lettering. Young Donald also posed for Martin's: 1. ''Saturday Evening Post'' ad, Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. 2. Outdoor posters for H-O Oats (three different scenes). Their mini versions were displayed in grocery stores. 3. Bond Bread, Rollfast Bicycles, Wilson Bats ads (though unknown if any of them, made it to print). 4. ''Foreign Service'' cover, May 1932. However, its photo shoots took place two years earlier. More: They lived on opposite ends of a very long street in Millwood, N.Y. They first met at a short-lived (victim of the [[Great Depression]]) coffee shop in Millwood, operated by the boy's parents. It was called \"Rose and Carl's Restaurant,\" and located across from the railroad depot on Station Road. Martin was a regular customer, who often ordered stuffed cabbage with apple pie. He coupled trips to the post office, with getting a home-baked meal (same bldg.). Their photo sessions took place from 1930-31. (Salary: 15\u00a2/still or $5+/half-day, with free snacks.) The cover model went on to graduate from [[Chappaqua, New York#Education|Horace Greeley (High) School]] (1941) ... take part in the [[Invasion of Normandy]] ([[ADSEC]] unit; landed on June 21, 1944) ... become a sportswriter for ''The Daily Item'' of Port Chester, N.Y. (1948-50), & associate editor for ''Progressive Grocer'' (1956-62).</ref> Those familiar with Paul Martin's career as an artist, declare the 1932 Buddy Poppy poster to be one of his best creations.\"<ref>''Foreign Service'', May 1932 pp. 10, 26 (quote).</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jHibnoOKgZoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22golden%20rule%22&f=false \"Wear a Buddy Poppy\"]. ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52. A black and white version of the poster. Artist signed. The silky flowers were made by disabled and needy veterans. Proceeds from its sales, provided relief to veterans and their dependents.</ref>\n\n==Fisk Tire Boy==\n[[File:Fisk_Tire_Boy_(1930-34).jpg|left|thumb|117px|Jigsaw Puzzle - Design No. One, 1933. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:The_Kid.jpg|thumb|117px|'''Martin's Most Notable Artwork''', 1930. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:FiskEnvelope.jpg|thumb|150px|Envelope postmarked 1932. Artist signed. His credits include all of (and only) the version with the two-piece pajamas.]]\nPrelude: The [[Fisk Tire Company|Fisk Rubber Company]] (as officially known; founded 1898) was producing automobile, bicycle and carriage tires by 1901.<ref>Fisk Tires brochure, 1901. Size: 4.5 x 6.5\". 12 pp. This handout gives the details, prices, sizes and weights; on its automobile, bicycle and carriage tires.</ref><ref>''Our County and its People: A History of Hampden County, Massachusetts.\" Copeland, lead editor, 1902 vol. 3 p. 504.</ref> Its factory was located along the riverfront in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls, Massachusetts]]. It pumped out 230,000 tires in August 1921.<ref>''Automobile Topics'' (trade magazine), September 24, 1921 p. 443. That total was a record monthly output for 1921.</ref> Fisk struggled financially during most of the 1930s.<ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 278. Excerpt: \"As the [[Great Depression|depression]] deepened, net sales of the company plummeted.\" It forced them to severely cut back on advertising.</ref> They were bought out by [[United States Rubber Company|U.S. Rubber]], [[wikt:AKA|aka]] U.S. Royal (1940).<ref>''The New York Sun'', January 19, 1940 p. 31. Heading: \"Transfer Fisk Assets to U.S.\"</ref> Their international branch acquired a majority stake in [[Englebert (tyre manufacturer)|Englebert]] (1958). Their worldwide names were condensed/simplified into [[United States Rubber Company|Uniroyal]] (1966).<ref>See Babcock book, 1966 pp. 97 (aka), xv, 410-11 (names).</ref> They merged with Goodrich, and became known as [[Goodrich Corporation|Uniroyal Goodrich]] (1986). Its tire division was sold to [[Michelin]] (1990).<ref>The deal was struck 1989. Finalized 1990.</ref> The Fisk Tire brand had a dormant period after 1977.<ref>''The Tennessean'', Sept. 15, 1966 p. 69; ''Nevada State Journal'', Dec. 8, 1966 p. 25; ''Poughkeepsie Journal'', Aug. 30, 1977 p. 17; ''Circleville (Ohio) Herald'', Sept. 20, 1977 p. 10; ''Beckley (W.Va.) Post-Herald'', Nov. 17, 1977 p. 21. [[Kmart]] sold the Fisk brand from 1966-77.</ref> This brand was revitalized by [[Michelin]], and produced exclusively for [[Discount Tire]] (1996-2014).<ref>''Tire Business'' (trade magazine), July 6, 1998. \"Time to Un-Retire: Discount Tire Revives Fisk, Escort.\" Editor Dave Zielasko in collaboration with Al Olsen.</ref>\n\nHe completely reshaped one of the most famous characters in the history of American advertising. It was the Fisk Rubber Company's [[wikt:bedtime|bedtime]] boy, who shouldered an oversized tire while dangling a lighted candle.<ref>''America A to Z'' by ''Reader's Digest'', 1997 pp. 364-65. It's listed as one of the eleven, most famous trademarks ever.</ref><ref>''The 100 Greatest Advertisements: Who Wrote Them and What They Did'' by Watkins, 1959 pp. 16-17. Retitled and republished in 2012.</ref><ref>''Logo, Font & Lettering Bible'' by Cabarga, 2004 p. 16. The boy's hair got lighter, as the years went on.</ref> It came with the catchphrase \"Time To Re-tire\" (debuted 1910).<ref name=\"debut\">''[[The San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call]]'', April 30, 1911 p. 44; ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', August 17, 1911; ''[[Country Life in America]]'', April 15, 1912 p. 86; ''[[Collier's]]'', April 20, 1912 p. 30; ''[[Motor (American magazine)|Motor]]'', April 1912 p. 26. These are among the earliest appearances of the advertising character. However, it first showed up on merchandise in 1910.</ref><ref name=\"year\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ALUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA11-PA78&lpg=RA11-PA78&dq Early History]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78. \"Development of 'Fisk Boy' as Trade Figure.\" The sleepy-eyed character was created in 1910. It showed up that year on lithographs, posters and then one-cent postcards. The latter have periodically showed up on the collector's market. They were postmarked in either late-1910, 11 or 12. ''The Poster'', Nov. 1913 p. 55. \"Why the Fisk Rubber Company Uses Posters,\" by their advertising manager M. G. (Mabel Garetta) Webber. Excerpt: \"He appeared first in 1910.\" (Viewable online at booksgoogle.com.)</ref> This slogan had a simple double meaning. The boy's yawn became a smile in early 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Jan. 12, 1929 p. 78 (print debut).</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317. Mgmt. decided on the facial alteration in 1928.</ref> Martin was then commissioned to come up with a slightly more aged, modern-day figure in late 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8, 1930 p. 106 (print debut).</ref><ref name=\"modern\">''Editor & Publisher'' (mag), March 22, 1947 p. 36. Martin's contributions to \"Master PJs\" are indirectly mentioned. Excerpt: \"At one time, they put him in a modern suit of pajamas, made him a little older.\" This source states the boy was created CIRCA 1907. It's very unlikely the trademark was created three years before debuting. A more likely estimate would be 1909 or 10. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78; ''The Poster'' (mag), Nov. 1913 p. 55. These very early sources claim the boy was created in 1910.</ref> The objective was to update the heavily publicized trademark, while still maintaining its charm and familiarity. The young lad's one-piece sleeper became a two-piece pajama set, during the changeover process. The slippers were also added. His four-year-old nephew was used as the model (neck down only).<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), July 11, 1927 p. 1. Subheading: \"Mr. and Mrs. Jacob Willey Celebrate [50th Wedding] Anniversary.\" This article mentions the Martins, their nieces Adele and Edna, and nephew Walter.</ref> Still, the pose and all-important props remained basically intact (though with the current tire design and a more fashionable\u2014less tilted\u2014candle holder). This new look was described by the publicity manager at Fisk, to a national magazine writer in early 1930. As follows: \"A happy, smiling, 100-percent American boy in his little two-piece pajama, radiating good cheer, ruddy-cheeked and tousle-headed, snappy and wide awake, standing in the old-time pose.\"<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\">''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 27, 1930 pp. 10, 12 (R. G. Bath's quote). \"Don't Be Afraid to Improve Your Trade-Mark: Even the Long-Famous Time to Re-tire Boy Has Been Modernized.\" The boy's three stages are pictured and reviewed. This is a rare [[primary source]] on the third and final stage.</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company: A Case Study in Corporation Management'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317 (quote).</ref><ref>''[[Smile, Darn Ya, Smile!]]'' Cartoon short, Sept. 1931. [[Foxy (Merrie Melodies)|Foxy]] notices the new look, after the 3:15 mark.</ref>\n\nThe now-updated version was first used by Fisk Tires, to showcase its newly introduced \"Air-Flights\" in advertisements. This included twelve times in ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', between Feb. 8 and Aug. 23, 1930 ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8 p. 106; March 8 p. 76; April 5 p. 107; May 3 p. 69;  May 10 p. 128; May 24 p. 61; June 7 p. 67; June 21 p. 89; June 28 p. 87; July 5 p. 69; July 26 p. 91; Aug. 23 p. 38. All twelve issues are from 1930.</ref><ref>His signature appears with the trade character in three of these twelve issues. As follows: March 8, 1930 p. 76 (plain backdrop); July 26, 1930 p. 91 (purple backdrop); Aug. 23, 1930 p. 38 (blue backdrop).</ref> It was offered to the public as an 11x14\" colorful art print, that could be framed.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Mar. 8, 1930 p. 77 (free coupon).</ref> The cheerful mascot went on to appear in many different formats. These were either with or without a facial touch-up.<ref>His credits include all images of the boy, wearing two-piece pajamas. This was the company's logo from 1930-34.</ref> For instance, on the front cover and endpapers of children's books in 1931. Subjects (8): Candy Land, Jack and the Bean Stalk, Little Black Sambo, Peter Rabbit, Pied Piper, Three Bears, Three Little Kittens and Three Little Pigs.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskBooks.jpg Books]. Commons. Softcovers. Size: 5.75 x 7.25\".</ref> They were all subtitled, \"Time to Re-tire / A Bedtime Story.\" It also showed up on ashtrays,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskAshtray.jpg Ashtray]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. Diameter 6.75\". Height 1.25\".</ref> bridge score pads,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskScorePad.jpg Score Pad]. Commons. A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington is on the cover. Size: 4 x 6.5\".</ref> cigarette cases,<ref>They came with elastic holding straps on both inside ends.</ref> electrical clocks,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskTelechron.jpg Clock]. Commons. They were circular in shape, with a rubber tire around the rim. Made by [[Telechron]]. Diameter 5.5\".</ref> jigsaw puzzles (''#1 pictured''),<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskPuzzle.jpg Puzzle]. Commons. Die-cut cardboard. Size: 8.625 x 11\". Set of five.</ref><ref>Design No. 1 - The Fisk Trade Mark Boy. (Martin's signature is next to the boy's left heel.) Design No. 2 - Elephant and Mouse. Design No. 3 - Checker Players. Design No. 4 - The Shadow. Design No. 5 - Baseball. The last four feature an old Reginald Bolles, Kernan or Thrasher painting. Also, a large sign of the new corporate figurehead, in the background.</ref> matchbooks,<ref>It showed up on Diamond Quality, Pull Quick, & Universal Match Corporation covers. The first two were made by the Diamond Match Co. of N.Y. The Pull Quicks had ten wooden sticks, which were ignited by quickly pulling them out.</ref> posters<ref>Titled: \"Coming and Going,\" with an Army/Navy theme and NRA ([[National Recovery Administration]]) logo. That helps date it to 1933 or 34. Size: 28 x 39\".</ref> and rubber heel replacements for shoes.<ref>The mascot with words \"Air Cushion\" & \"Fisk.\" This was a self-repair product. It came in various sizes, incl. a 10-11\".</ref> These were giveaway items, with an automotive purchase.<ref>''New Oxford (Pa.) Item'', April 13, 1933 p. 3; April 20, 1933 p. 14. Ad: \"During this tire sale, we will give absolutely free, one Fisk jig saw puzzle with every tire sold.\"</ref> Martin's version was used by Fisk retailers on their data books,<ref>''Super-Service Data Book'', 1933. Size: 6.25 x 3.75\". 32 pp. It gives the specs on rims and tires, for various car models.</ref> display windows,<ref>These were circular [[decal]]s that stuck onto the inside of glass windows.</ref> letterheads and mailing envelopes ''(pictured)''.<ref>Other variations: 1. Trademark character on both sides, with phrase on back \"Time to Retire / Get a Fisk.\" 2. Character on the front, with phrase \"Air-Flight Principle Tires by Fisk.\"</ref> It appeared in a scaled-down form, in ''[[Boys' Life]]'' and other magazines<ref>''National Petroleum News'', Feb. 19, 1930 p. 120; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 43; June 1932 p. 53; July 1932 p. 45; Sept. 1933 p. 28; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zbtu_glJDyAC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=fisk+tire+boy+created+1910&source=bl&ots=GGMI39sMhI&sig=pLDn3b09BV89R62Tp-z8KsTueFY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=k3OoU47MJsfhoATUv4LwDQ&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=fisk%20tires&f=false \"All the World\"]. Dec. 1933 p. 42; April 1934 p. 28; May 1934 p. 30; June 1934 p. 42; Dec. 1934 p. 55; ''The American Boy'', Dec. 1933. These tire ads are for bicycles.</ref> (along with hundreds of newspapers)<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%20Disk3/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20&%20Farmer/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale.pdf/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200156.pdf \"Air-Flight Principle\"] (PDF). ''Gazette & Farmers' Journal'', April 17, 1930 p. 3; ''The Cayuga Chief'', April 4, 1930 p. 3; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 10, 1930 p. 10; April 17, 1930 p. 15; ''The New York Sun'', May 8, 1930 p. 47; ''Waterville Times'' May 8, 1930 p. 6; ''The Newark (N.Y.) Courier'', June 12, 1930 p. 6; ''San Jose Evening News'', July 11, 1930 p. 13; ''Skaneateles Free Press'', July 17, 1930 p. 6; ''Binghamton Press'', April 23, 1931 p. 19; ''Van Nuys News'', Aug. 6, 1931 p. 21; ''Dansville Breeze'', Jan. 21 & 23, 1932 p. 3; ''Buffalo Courier-Express'', Jan. 4, 1932 p. 6; ''Medina Daily Journal'', May 11 & June 29, 1933 p. 5; ''The Evening News'', July 19, 1933 p. 16; ''Schenectady Gazette'', May 25, 1934 p. 32; ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', July 6, 1934 p. 8; July 7 & 19, 1934 p. 5; Aug. 14, 1934 p. 8. Fisk dramatically cut back on advertising after 1930. This was due to the deepening Great Depression, which forced most of their franchise dealers out of business.</ref> from 1930-34. Fisk Tires then went back to the original sleepy boy in 1935.<ref>''The Hogan Handbook'', Fisk-Federal-Badger Tire Catalog, Thomas E. Hogan Inc., 1935 pp. 35-36. The original \"Fisk Boy\" did not appear in mag ads from 1930-36. However, it started showing up on various advertising materials in 1935.</ref> Incidentally, [[Norman Rockwell]] drew many paintings featuring the trade character, which were published in 1917-20, 24-25.<ref>''Norman Rockwell Encyclopedia'' by Moline, 1979 pp. 144-46, 149, 156-57, 161, 167-68, 172, 183-84 (credit listings).</ref> Likewise, J. F. Kernan and [[Leslie Thrasher]] between 1924 & 1927.<ref>Kernan: 1926-27. Thrasher: 1924-27.</ref>\n\nTimetable.<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\"/> Three stages of the pajama-clad boy (based on its appearance in print or on advertising material): a. 1910-28, 35-onward<ref name=\"debut\"/><ref name=\"year\"/><ref>\"Master Pajamas\" lost its luster over time. Nonetheless, the trade character continued to show up on boxes and cans of auto parts into the 1970s. For instance: air filters, antifreeze, brake fluid, headlamps, motor tune-ups, oil filters, shock absorbers, spark plugs and tire cleaners. It has since then appeared on Franklin Mint collectibles, Lionel boxcars, and the label stickers for Fisk Classic tires.</ref> (created by Burr Giffin, an agency art director). b. 1929-30 (change of a yawn into a smile\u2014uncredited). c. 1930-34 (modern redesign by Paul Martin).<ref name=\"modern\"/>\n\n''[[Printers' Ink]]'' article from 1912. Excerpt: \"It was in 1910 that the 'Time to Re-Tire' boy was created, appeared first in a lithographed wall hanger in four colors, and later all over the country for poster display. This is the now familiar picture of the little boy ready for bed, lugging a large Fisk tire on his arm. His reception was sufficiently enthusiastic to cause the advertiser to distribute postcards and reprints in which the boy was the central figure.\"<ref name=\"year\"/>\n\n==Personal life and tennis==\nHe was born to Hannah A. (n\u00e9e Morrow) and Robert C. Martin (a brick merchant) in [[New York City]] on June 6, 1883.<ref>''[[New York Press (historical)|New York Press]]'', December 13, 1890 p. 2. His father was an associate with \"Peck, Martin & Co.\" They dealt in building materials (especially bricks). Excerpt: \"Mr. Martin, who had been employed as a bookkeeper by the firm for twelve years, was admitted as a partner February 1, 1882.\"</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AevFLAEluDAC&pg=PA23-IA3&lpg=PA23-IA3&dq=%22Peck,+Martin+%26+Co.%22&source=bl&ots=qPSdWJCKg_&sig=ACfU3U2R-HVGcHRS2xH6HJLJgfXCf1BBMw&hl#v=onepage&q=%22Peck%2C%20Martin%20%26%20Co.%22&f=false \"Materials\"]. ''Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide'', Jan. 5, 1884 p. 24-Vi; Feb. 7, 1891 p. 199 (\"Martin & Co.\").</ref> He was the youngest of nine children (three of whom did not reach adulthood).<ref>''Census of 1880''. Search under \"Robt. C.\" ''Census of 1900 & 1910''. They had nine children (six still living). ''New York Herald'', Nov. 5, 1864 p. 3. His parents were married in 1864. ''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4; ''New York Tribune'', July 30, 1917 p. 7. Robert's obit notices. He was survived by Hannah, five sons and one daughter. The funeral service was held at Calvary M. E. Church in Manhattan, at 129th St. and 7th Ave. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1919 p. 22. Hannah's obit.</ref><ref>''[[The Sun (New York City)|The Sun]]'', July 17, 1891 p. 5. His sister Theresa, died at thirteen months. ''The Evening World'', June 20, 1893 p. 7. His sister Hannah Louisa, died at 16. Their funeral services were held, at the family home on Edgecombe Ave. Keywords at [[Chronicling America]]: \"Hannah A. Martin.\"</ref> The family home was on [[Manhattan]]'s 31st St., between 8th and 9th Aves. throughout the 1880s.<ref>''Census of 1880'' (under abbreviated name \"Robt. C.\"); ''New York & New Jersey Telephone Company'' (Directory), 1888 sec. NYC p. 81; ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1890 p. 835. They lived near the future site of [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]].</ref> The Martin clan moved way up to [[Harlem|Central Harlem]] on Edgecombe Ave. in 1890.<ref>''The Sun'', Dec. 13, 1890 p. 8. \"Real Estate Transfers.\" Locale: east side (of street), N of 138th. ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1891 p. 912; 1892 p. 948; 1893 p. 931; 1894 p. 931; 1896 p. 966; 1897 p. 863. Home: Edgecombe Ave. Their address is listed under Robert F (son of Robert C) for 1896 & 97.</ref> They relocated within Central Harlem, to 129th and 5th in 1898.<ref>''Census of 1880''. The family lived on 31st St. ''Census of 1900''. They lived on 129th St.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1899 p. 846. They lived on 129th St.</ref> They belonged to the 24th Street [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1890)<ref>''Minutes of the New York Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church'', edited by Adams & Strobridge, 1884 p. 74. The father is listed as a church official.</ref><ref>''Comprehensive Church Record of the Twenty-Fourth Street Methodist Episcopal Church'', 1877. This book was viewed by an archivist with the New York Conference, United Methodist Church (White Plains, N.Y.). Department: Archives and History. The Martins and their two oldest sons are listed as members.</ref> and Calvary [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1908). Paul's father Robert was the superintendent of their [[Sunday school]]s.<ref>''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4 (superintendent). The family switched churches, due to their residential relocation ([[list of Manhattan neighborhoods|Chelsea to Harlem neighborhoods]]). Calvary moved to the West Bronx in 1923. Its [[:File:CALVARY METHODIST EPISCOPAL CHURCH, NEW YORK CITY ABOVE 110TH ST. NY.jpg|original church]] (built 1887) was designated as a historic landmark in 2016.</ref> Martin immensely enjoyed drawing as a boy.<ref name=\"winning\"/> He studied [[commercial art]] at the [[National Academy of Design]] in [[New York City]] from 1902-06.<ref>Summer only 1906. He took classes in Antique (drawing from plaster casts), Illustration (taught by Charles Louis Hinton), and Life (drawing live models). The Academy's archive department supplied these dates and details. ''American Art Annual 1903\u20131904'', edited by [[Florence Nightingale Levy|Levy]], p. 288; ''1905\u20131906'' p. 304 (backup sources). Hinton was then their only instructor in Illustration.</ref><ref>The school was then located at West 109th St. and Amsterdam Ave. in NYC. He continued to live at home, during that time. This was with immediate & extended family, on 129th St. His residency was verified by the school's archive dept.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpt: \"He studied at the National Academy of Design.\"</ref> He worked as the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'s'' art manager from 1906-13.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. \"Manager. Art Dept. Daily Paper.\" ''Directory of the Oranges'' (N.J.), Price & Lee Co., 1910 p. 400 \"Mgr. NY\"; 1912 p. 429 \"Mgr. NY.\"</ref><ref>''Census of 1900''. He previously worked as a brokerage clerk.</ref> Martin and family members moved from [[Upper Manhattan]] to [[Maplewood, New Jersey]], 1908.<ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. His household, occupation and residence are listed. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. He played in inter-club tennis tourneys (both singles and doubles), as a member of the Maplewood Field Club.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1907 vol. CXXI p. 1063 (home: 129th St.); 1908 vol. CXXII p. 928 (home: Orange, N.J.). Maplewood was then a section of Orange.</ref><ref>''Trow Directory, Printing and Bookbinding Company'', 1909 p. 937. Robert Martin's occupation (building materials) and residence (Maplewood) are listed.</ref> He started competing in sanctioned tennis tournaments, 1909.<ref name=\"competing\">It's verified through the name-pairing, in the following sources as a whole. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 8; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 pp. 98-99. He played singles and doubles (with H. N. Balch), in the New Jersey State Championship at Morristown. ''Spalding's'', 1910 p. 181. They also played in the Nyack Country Club tournament. ''Spalding's'', 1913 p. 64. Harry Balch and Martin played doubles in South Orange, N.J. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. They were clubmates and doubles partners at the Maplewood Field Club. ''Census of 1910''. The two were also neighbors, who lived a few houses apart.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1910-05-17/ed-1/seq-9/#date1=1907&sort=relevance&rows=20&words \"Many Players Put Out\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1910 p. 9; May 20 & 29, 1910 p. 8; June 2, 1910 p. 9; June 21, 1910 p. 9; June 28 & July 1, 1910 p. 9; ''The Sun'', May 29, 1911 p. 4; May 31, 1911 p. 9; Aug. 12, 1911 p. 7; Aug. 14, 1911 p. 9. He participated in many tourneys from 1910-11. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1914 pt. 2 p. 6; July 6, 1915 p. 15; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4. Martin's lean years on the circuit were from 1912-14. His game was elevated a notch by 1915. ''New York Tribune'', Dec. 22, 1918 pt. 2 p. 7; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 pp. 177, 181. He was nationally ranked for the first time in 1918 (at No. 91). There were no rankings in the war year of 1917.</ref> Martin married Lauretta Willey in 1912.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:MarriageAnnouncementNewYork1912.jpg Card]. Their wedding announcement card gave the date and location as Sept. 27, 1912 in New York. ''Census of 1930''. Their ages at marriage are stated, though PM's is off by one year.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1900''. The Willeys lived in [[Upper Manhattan]], as the century turned. Her parents were Mary Immler (1854-1937) and Jacob Willey (1849-1939). ''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), Aug. 2, 1937 p. 2; ''The New York Times'', July 27, 1939 p. 19. Their obituaries. Lauretta was raised Methodist. The Martins and Willeys both attended the then-named Calvary M. E. Church.</ref> (Her brother would own the Willey Book Co.)<ref>Their specialty was in reprinting old books. Her brother worked for and later took over the company, from someone who by chance had the same surname. ''U.S. Census of 1910''; ''New York State Census of 1915''; ''New York State Census of 1925''. He's listed sequentially, as an accountant for a publishing company ... office clerk ... publisher from [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].</ref> Their first rented home was in the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] section of the [[The Bronx|Bronx]], 1912.<ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1913 p. 812; 1915 p. 1258. They lived on Loring Pl.</ref> They relocated a block away in 1915.<ref>''New York State Census of 1915''; ''U.S. Census of 1920''; Westchester County New York Property Records, Aug. 1925. Their home address was on Andrews Ave. They were renters according to the ''U.S. Census''.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1916 p. 1140. They lived on Andrews Ave.</ref> He was employed with the O. J. Gude Company 1913-19 & Gotham Studios 1919-20.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. Martin, as a Gude employee, writes to the Mrs. in 1914. His artistic credits, nearly always went to the company.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1920''. He was living in the West Bronx and working in outdoor advertising. ''Trow General Directory of New York City, embracing the Boroughs of Manhattan and the Bronx'', April 1916 p. 1140 (occupation: artist).</ref><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. His employment with the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'' and O. J. Gude Co. are mentioned, in a special write-up. It also gives him credit (via Gotham Studios) for the cover. FamilySearch.org. Search>Records. Draft Registration Card, September 1918. He was then employed with Gude.</ref><ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 11, 1920 p. 72. He gets credit for a drawing of the [[ancient Greek]] philosopher Empedocles, while working for Gotham Studios.</ref> Those two were giants in the advertising industry. Martin joined the Artists' Guild<ref name=\"winning\"/> and went freelance in January 1921.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y1U2AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=guide&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Guild\"]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', Dec. 1920 p. 97; Jan. 1921 p. 97. He's first listed as a member, in the latter.</ref> Paul and Lauretta moved from the [[The Bronx|Bronx]] to a rural area of [[Millwood, New York]], August 1925.<ref>Office of the Westchester County Clerk. They provided the property records, on the Martins' two-story home in Millwood.</ref> Their first owned home doubled as a working studio (upper floor) from 1925-32.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Martins%27_home,_Ossining,_N.Y.jpg \"Cottage Tor\"]. Commons. Martin's painting of their home.</ref> Its centerpiece was a long flat-top table that held the canvases, drawing pads, paint brushes and tubes. Also nearby were art books, easels and props for photo shoots.<ref>The props included caps, jackets, jerseys, neckties, pajamas, shirts, sports equipment and sweaters. They sometimes appeared in multiple illustrations. Martin's niece, Adele, recalled the studio's materials and layout in a typed essay. It was for an article in ''Hard Row to Hole'', Fall 2005 pp. 1-3 (but didn't make it into print). [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> He occasionally used family members as models. Uncle Paul's niece Edna is shown, writing down the license number of a boy's wagon (for knocking over her doll carriage),<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'' cover of September 12, 1925. She's also highlighted on an [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]] poster.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref name=\"poster\"/> His mother-in-law is shown [[basting (cooking)|basting]] a turkey for [[Thanksgiving dinner|Thanksgiving]],<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' cover of November 1928.\n\n[[File:TrophyWCTL.jpg|left|thumb|69px|Paul Martin Memorial Trophy]]\nHe was ranked among the top thirty tennis players in the [[New York metropolitan area]], from 1920-25 (top twenty 1923\u201324).<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1924 p. 97 (top twenty for '23); 1925 p. 92 (top twenty for '24). He was ranked in the teens from 1923-24.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 13, 1920 p. 12. Metro players were first officially ranked in 1920. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1921 pp. 29 (USA ranking), 109 (NY metropolitan area).</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1920 sec. 9 p. 2 (ranked between 18 & 31); Jan. 8, 1922 sec. 9 p. 1 (top 30); Jan. 14, 1923 sec. 1 pt. 2 p. 1 (top 30); Dec. 11, 1923 p. 24 (top 20); Jan. 25, 1925 p. 4S (top 20); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Jan. 25, 1925 p. 6D (top 20); Dec. 27, 1925 p. C3 (top 25).</ref> His strength was in making accurate shots.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11; ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3.</ref> Martin won numerous trophies (or awards) in singles, doubles and mixed doubles (with Lauretta) between 1919 & 1931.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-09-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1919&index=1&rows/ \"Woodmere\"]. ''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16. He won the runner-up trophy. That's assuming they were (as normally) awarded to the top two finishers. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 p. 225. The prize that year in particular, could have been a certificate or medal.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. His first tournament win (excl. consolation singles). ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1918 p. 33. This sanctioned husbands-and-wives event began in 1918. The unique idea was proposed by future HOFer [[Marie Wagner]].</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19311016.2.21 \"Club Title\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1. His last tournament win, which came at age 48. Victor in doubles. (Also runner-up in singles.) These events were open only to members of their club. However, he also won a sanctioned tourney that year, at Lake George, N.Y. (See Ref #232.)</ref> This included, for example, one for capturing the inaugural championship at Sunningdale Country Club in 1920.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/07/11/112662657.pdf \"Martin Tennis Winner\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17. It was held on the Sunningdale Courts in Scarsdale, N.Y.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l-c9AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Second Annual Tournament\"]. ''American Lawn Tennis'', June 15, 1921 p. 135. Scroll downward. Excerpt: \"The first leg on this cup was won in 1920 by Paul Martin.\"</ref> Others were for the Lake George<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles title); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 2, 1925 p. 2F (alternate source). The latter states that Martin was the Lake George champion of 1924.</ref> and Lake Mohonk<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20Freeman/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale%20-%200870.pdf \"Ulster County Tennis Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles).</ref> Championships of 1924. Martin's opponents included future Hall of Famers [[Fred Alexander]],<ref>''The Sun'', June 22, 1910 p. 9. It was headlined by [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]], [[William Larned]].</ref> [[Jean Borotra]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 2, 1925 p. 2A [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|(National Indoor Doubles]]). Their match was played on the drill floor, of Manhattan's [[Seventh Regiment Armory]].</ref> [[Francis Hunter]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1919-07-07/ed-1/seq-12/ \"Hunter Gains Place in Round Before Semi-Finals\"] (subheading). ''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12.</ref> [[Gerald Patterson]],<ref name=\"Patterson\">''Schenectady Gazette'', August 28, 1924 p. 9. \"Patterson, after encountering some difficulty and losing a set to Paul Martin of New York ...\" ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 27, 1924 p. 2. \"Gerald Patterson, Australian Davis Cup captain, quickly finished off his opponent, Paul Martin of New York, by taking the fourth and deciding set of their postponed match without the loss of a game. The Anzac had dropped a long deuce set to Martin [on] Monday but he was invincible today.\" ''The New York Times'', Aug. 28, 1924 p. 12. This was the National Championship at Forest Hills. Patterson went on to reach the semi-finals.</ref> [[Vincent Richards]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-05-18/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Close Finishes\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 18, 1918 p. 14. Excerpt: \"In the second round, there was a keenly fought struggle between Richards\u2013Fischer and Paul Martin\u2013[[United States Tennis Association#Presidents|Jones W. Mersereau]].\" ''The Sun'', Aug. 21, 1918 p. 11; ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13; March 17, 1919 p. 17 (Hawthorne column); May 8, 1919 p. 22. The schoolboy prodigy and seasoned veteran were clubmates at Univ. Hts. ''The New York Times'', April 4, 1919 p. 12. Richards simultaneously belonged to the New York TC. ''The Sun'', July 6, 1919 sec. 2 p. 3. Martin over Richards by default. ''The Sun'', Oct. 6, 1919 p. 20; ''The New York Times'', Oct. 19, 1919 p. 6S. They were no longer clubmates by now. ''New York Tribune'', June 24, 1922 p. 11. They met in a 4th round match.</ref> [[Bill Tilden]],<ref name=\"Tilden\">''The New York Times'', June 28, 1925 p. 6S. They faced off at the [[New York Athletic Club]]'s country home, on Travers Island in New Rochelle. \"Big Bill\" went on to win the singles (over Vincent Richards) & doubles titles.</ref> [[John Van Ryn]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 3, 1924 p. 2A. [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoors]]. It was hosted by the 7th Regt. Armory. ''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476. Martin d. Van Ryn 6-4, 2-6, 6-4.</ref> [[Marie Wagner]]<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-10-15/ed-1/seq-21 \"Kynaston is Victor\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21. A mixed doubles match at West Orange, N.J. ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 52. The Martins over Wagner\u2013Calder at Lake George 3-6, 11-9, 2-0 default. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19. His wife faced Wagner in the second round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref> & [[Watson Washburn]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 20, 1919 p. 13. An inter-club tourney (unlike the rest). Heylman\u2013Washburn d. PM\u2013Robinson 6-3, 7-5.</ref><ref>''New York Tribune'', June 7, 1910 p. 8. [[Karl Behr]] over Martin by default at Englewood, N.J.</ref> Other standouts were [[Herbert Bowman]],<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15 (4R-West Bronx); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19 (5R-Hoboken, N.J.); ''The New York Times'', June 2, 1923 p. S8. Martin won after losing the first set 0-6. ''The New York Times'', June 12, 1925 p. 17 (5R-Montclair, N.J.); ''Buffalo Courier'', July 10, 1925 p. 10 (4R-Syracuse); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 9, 1928 p. 12. They were clubmates at Hartsdale. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 22, 1930 p. C3. They met in the semi-finals of the Eastern Clay Court Championship, at Travers Island.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', April 12, 1925 p. 16. Bowman and Martin came back from near defeat, to win an exhibition doubles match at the Briarcliff Lodge TC.</ref> [[Wylie Grant]],<ref>''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 p. 181; 1912 p. 160. Sequentially: Grant\u2013Rosenbaum over Balch\u2013Martin 6-1, 6-2 and Friedman\u2013Grant over Balch\u2013Martin 7-5, 6-2.</ref> [[Walter Merrill Hall]],<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/07/23/109816164.pdf \"Net Stars Advance\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', last (final) edition, July 1, 1922 p. 7; May 17, 1925 p. 2D.</ref> [[Robert Kinsey]],<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale%20-%200716.pdf \"Kinsey Brothers Score\"] (PDF). ''New York Tribune'', July 24, 1922 p. 11.</ref> Percy Kynaston,<ref>''New York Tribune'', March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1923 p. 17; June 15, 1923 p. 17 (semifinals match\u2013Montclair, N.J.); Aug. 22, 1923 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D; ''Long Island News and the Owl'', July 24, 1924 p. 1.</ref> [[Nathaniel Niles (figure skater)|Nathaniel Niles]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5 (Westchester Biltmore CC in Rye).</ref> Dr. William Rosenbaum,<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1919/09/15/118159201.pdf \"Rosenbaum Wins at Net\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 13. Martin eliminated Fred Anderson (older brother of Frank), earlier in the tournament. Anderson and Rosenbaum were both finalist, at different times, in the [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Singles]].</ref> [[S. Howard Voshell|Howard Voshell]]<ref>''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1910 p. 9; June 25, 1920 p. 15; June 24, 1922 p. 11. Voshell won back-to-back [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Tennis Championships]].</ref> & Charles Wood.<ref>''The New York Times'', May 29, 1923 p. 12. Heading: \"Martin conquers Wood at Yonkers.\" ''The New York Times'', June 20, 1924 p. 22. Wood played in every [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927\u20131945|National Professional Tennis Championship]] from 1927-36.</ref> A doubles partner and longtime clubmate was newspaper columnist [[Franklin P. Adams]], who wrote \"[[Baseball's Sad Lexicon]].\"<ref name=\"fellow\">''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1916-08-13/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Semi-Finals Reached\"]. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2; Sept. 17, 1917 p. 11; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-05-28/ed-1/seq-10/ \"Heights Team Wins\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', May 28, 1920 p. 10; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Martin belonged to the University Heights TC (as stated in all of the above). ''New York Tribune'', May 10, 1915 p. 15. A fellow clubmate was [[Franklin P. Adams]]. ''The Sun'', July 30 & Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 4, 1915 pt. 2 p. 4; July 1, 1917 pt. 2 p. 3 & July 2, 1917 p. 11; June 30, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 22, 1922 p. 9; ''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7; May 4, 1924 sec. 10 p. 6. They both played in these tourneys, put on by University Heights. ''New York Tribune'', July 2, 1919 pp. 10, 12. Columnist Adams mentions that event volunteer Mrs. Martin; served him cake, sandwiches and tea for refreshments. Her husband and Adams formed a tandem.</ref> A teammate was the reigning national boy champion, 14-year-old [[Vincent Richards]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13. Seven-member team: Behr, Clapp, Fischer, Martin, Mersereau, Richards, Whyte (not White). ''The Sun'', Aug. 26, 1917 sec. 2 p. 2. Boy's title.</ref>\n\nMartin competed with [[Bill Tilden]] in well over a dozen tournaments,<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-06-03/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Reach Fourth Round\"]. ''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1918 p. 13; May 18, 1918 p. 14; March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; July 14, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun'', May 14, 1919 p. 16; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 15, 1925 p. 2A; June 24, 1925 p. 2A; Feb. 17, 1926 p. 2A; May 16, 1926 p. 2C; Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5; ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Aug. 13, 1928 p. 13; ''Syracuse American'', Aug. 11, 1929 p. 8.</ref> including the [[US Open (tennis)|National/US Open Championships]] of 1920, [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]] & 24.<ref name=\"nationals\">Men's Singles: ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 31, 1920 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 1, 1921 p. 2; ''The Sun'', Aug. 20, 1924 p. 26. Tilden won every National from 1920-25.</ref><ref>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921 Nationals]]. Sec. 8. 2R: Rogers vs. Martin. His wife Lauretta, played in the women's division.</ref> The latter was played at newly built [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills Stadium]], and on its outlying courts. He faced off against two-time [[list of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon champion]], [[Gerald Patterson]] of [[Australia]]. 41-year-old Martin won a set, though lost the match 4-6, 4-6, 9-7, 0-6.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/tennis/US_Open/Men_1924.html \"Round of 64\"]. Complete results. Compiled by T. Krastev.</ref> (There was a one-day [[rainout (sports)|rain delay]] after the third set.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 486. Excerpt: \"Upon resuming, Patterson won six games in a row, despite Martin's steady play.\"</ref> He also competed on these same Forest Hills courts, in four straight [[US Open (tennis)|National Championships]] for veterans (ages 45+) from 1928-31.<ref name=\"veterans\">''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1929 p. 51. Excerpt: \"[[Philip B. Hawk|Dr. Hawk]] went into the semi-final against Bassford with a victory over PM of New York.\" ''Spalding's'', 1930 p. 31. Excerpt: \"[[Jean Baptiste Adoue|{{bracket|Jean Adoue}}]] engaged PM of New York in the longest and closest match of the tournament, which required forty-eight games.\" ''Spalding's'', 1931 p. 27. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1932 p. 13. He lasted twice until both the third and fourth rounds. (Age REQ later lowered.)</ref> Martin was a standout singles and doubles player, for both the University Heights (Bronx, N.Y.)<ref name=\"fellow\"/> and County (Scarsdale, N.Y.)<ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 23, 1928 sec. 11 p. 8; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22; Aug. 15, 1930 p. 1; June 26, 1931 p. 2. It was also called the County TC of Hartsdale or Westchester. He joined this club, after moving from the Bronx to Millwood in August 1925.</ref> Tennis Clubs. He was unwittingly caught up in the famous player-writer dispute of 1924 (overview in reference<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 pp. 1-2D. The [[United States Tennis Association|USLTA]] adopted the player-writer rule on Feb. 2, 1924. It stated that any active player who received payment for writing on tennis, would be stripped of their amateur status starting Jan. 1, 1925. This resolution was easily approved by its members, who voted in blocks (47,196 to 6,250). It would have most deeply affected Bill Tilden, followed distantly by Vincent Richards. Strong opposition came from the influential [[Stephen Wallis Merrihew|S. Wallis Merrihew]], fans and writers.  A petition was signed by, among others, 12 [not 18] of the top 25 ranked racketmen from the [[New York metropolitan area|NY Metro Area]]. It rebuked the new rule that redefined amateurism. [[Walter Merrill Hall]] (#11) and Martin (#18) did not sign on with the pro-Tilden forces. They instead wrote a separate letter (full text printed, p. 2D), urging its reconsideration. A special committee of seven was formed, to further study the troubling matter on Nov. 2, 1924. (This was after a months-long selection process, to fill the final three critical spots.) It consisted of Arthur Hellen, Merrihew, Jones Mersereau, [[Devereux Milburn]], Senator [[George W. Pepper|George Pepper]], [[Grantland Rice]] and Tilden. Their report was released on Dec. 13. The USLTA accepted its recommendations, to greatly modify the anti-writing resolution. The alternative was to face continued backlash.</ref>). The distinction between amateurism and professionalism was hotly contested from Feb.-Dec. 1924. He often acted as the women's [[official (tennis)#Off-court officials|referee]].<ref>''The New York Times'', June 12, 1923 p. 17. Heading: \"Women to Meet at Nets.\" ''American Lawn Tennis'', July 15, 1924 p. 249. ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9. Chairwoman Helen Simpson supervised the event. ''New York Evening Post'', June 9, 1925 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', June 7, 1925 p. 8S. Martin was the tournament referee, and in charge of accepting entries. His wife served on its committee. ''New York Evening Post'', June 19, 1925 p. 14. Former [[U.S. Women's Indoor Championships|national indoor champion]], Helene Pollak Falk, nearly collapsed during a semi-finals match. Referee Paul assisted her off the court. ''The Post-Star'', July 21, 1925 p. 11; ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1930 p. 166.</ref> He organized tournaments for youngsters, as a committee member of the [[Briarcliff Lodge]] Sports Club.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19260820.2.12 \"Younger Tennis Players\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 20, 1926 pp. 1, 10; Aug. 15, 1925 p. 9.</ref> The [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] Tennis League is the oldest continuously running of its kind, in the United States (est. 1924). They hold the annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament.<ref>[http://www.wctl.net/tennis/about.shtml \"Westchester County Tennis League\"]. The WCTL has hosted the event every year since 1932 (excluding 1942-45). This was last verified via email with a league rep in 2019. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 15, 1964 p. E3 (event's host).</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale%20-%201075.pdf \"Annual County Net Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 21, 1932 p. 14. Club managers decide to honor Martin. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 4; June 29, 1934 p. 14; July 10, 1936 p. 1. The person most responsible for its establishment was Fenimore Cady, of the Mount Pleasant Tennis Club in Pleasantville.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19320819.2.3 \"Memorial Tourney to Start\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 19, 1932 p. 1.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale%20-%202925.pdf \"Paul Martin Memorial Play\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 28, 1935 p. 19. It was originally called the Paul Martin Memorial Tennis Tournament, and included singles and doubles competition.</ref> The winners of this event have their names engraved, on one of his prized cups ''(pictured)''.<ref>A second-place trophy in the third annual Essex County Championship (W. Orange, N.J.). It ran from Oct. 8-14, 1922.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (names engraved).</ref><ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1 (column's end); Sept. 9, 1932 p. 1; Oct. 7, 1932 p. 14; Sept. 22, 1933 p. 11. The singles winner of the annual County TC tournament (for members only), started having their names engraved on another PM memorial cup in 1932. It was Martin's trophy for finishing second at Harlem in 1923. The cup's future history\u2013unknown.</ref>\n\nMartin died of ulcers at age 48, following a major operation at Ossining Hospital in 1932.<ref name=\"hospital\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Subheading: \"Originator of 'Time to Re-Tire' series succumbs after operation.\" Excerpt: \"Funeral services will be Tuesday night at 7 o'clock, at the Highland Avenue M. E. Church.\"</ref><ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', April 20, 1932 p. 64. Excerpts: \"Paul Martin, well known in New York tennis circles and a [former] member of the University Heights Tennis Club, died suddenly ... For some time Martin had been troubled with pains in the stomach.\" His passing was also noted in the Table of Contents on p. 3. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, 1932 vol. 158:2 p. 80.</ref> The funeral service was held at [[Downtown Ossining Historic District#Zoning and regulation|Highland (now United) Methodist Church]] in [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining]].<ref name=\"hospital\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpts: \"An artist specializing in advertising ... studied at the National Academy of Design. ... Funeral services will be held Tuesday in the Highland Methodist Church.\"</ref> Survivors included three brothers and one sister. His wife Lauretta \"Lolly\" (1880-1972) outlived him by forty years.<ref>Lifespan: July 7, 1880, New York City, N.Y. - Aug. 14, 1972, Mount Vernon, N.Y. She was predeceased by her brother and sister. ''Social Security Death Index'' (SSDI). Her birth year is listed as 1880.</ref> They both played in the singles draw of the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]<ref name=\"nets\">[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-08-14/ed-1/seq-19 \"First Round Schedule ... 2pm\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 14, 1921 pt. 1 p. 19. She competed in the [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Women's National Championship]] (US Open) of 1921. The final was between Molla Mallory and Mary K. Browne. This Forest Hills tournament featured the heavily publicized, American debut of [[Suzanne Lenglen]]. Both Martins played in the singles draw of the 1921 Nationals. It's a trivial, though rare, occurrence for a married couple (in the same year). Others: Clarence Hobart\u2013Augusta Schultz (1905), Nathaniel Niles\u2013Martha Pitkin (1920-21), Marjorie Gladman\u2013John Van Ryn (1931-37), Nell Hall\u2013Harry Hopman (1938), Frank Kovacs\u2013Virginia Wolfenden (1941), Edwin Cooke\u2013Sarah Palfrey (1945), Lew Hoad\u2013Jenny Staley (1956), Carole Caldwell\u2013Clark Graebner (1964-65), Bill Bowrey\u2013Lesley Turner (1969), Chris Evert\u2013John Lloyd (1979, 81, 83-85).</ref> and were regular mixed doubles partners.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. Subheading: \"Earn Husband and Wife Metropolitan Tennis Championship.\" ''The Sun and New York Herald'', Sept. 24, 1920 p. 9. They lasted until the fourth round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Their names are listed near the column's end.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19291025.2.41 \"County Club is Victorious\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3. Their mixed doubles win was credited to the team. [https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19310717.2.14# \"County Tennis Club\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', July 17, 1931 p. 1. Their victory was in a club tournament.</ref> She donated the tournament trophy named after her husband.<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (donated trophy).</ref> His painting \"Serve Your Country\" was once prominently displayed, in the main room of the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]].<ref>A silkscreen print (serigraph) made from the original painting. It was first on display at that location in 1965. It has since then been periodically exhibited in various areas. This was verified by the museum's research center, and a letter in its files by Sec-Treas. Heffernan (dated Dec. 3, 1965).</ref> Its gift shop periodically offered a coffee mug<ref>Dimensions: Height 3.75\". Width 3.25\" (w/o handle). The Hall of Fame's logo is on the image's opposite side.</ref> and postcard version ''(pictured)''. He was known for his athletic ability, active participation, friendliness and sportsmanship.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19340622.2.26 \"Paul Martin Tennis Tourney\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 1 (attributes).</ref> ''Bronxville Press'' column from 1932. Excerpt: \"His presence was always felt by topnotchers, as well as by those who could play only an average game. Paul Martin was a synonym for all that was clean and wholesome in the game.\"<ref>''[[Bronxville, New York| Bronxville]] Press'', Aug. 16, 1932 p. 4. \"The Village Vagabond.\" (Viewable online at news.hrvh.org. Select: \"Browse by title.\")</ref>\n\n==Total finals and more==\n[[File:ServeYourCountry.jpg|thumb|117px|(Serving in style) WWI poster, 1918]]\nThis list only includes open or invitational tournaments, which were sanctioned by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]]. Their results largely determined the player rankings, and who qualified for the [[US Open (tennis)|Nationals]]. These [[wikt:semimajor|semi-majors]] are categorized by the event's host.<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1923 pp. 306, 311-14. These clubs are all listed as [[United States Tennis Association|association members]], except for South Yonkers. That's due to its courts not being dedicated until May 25, 1924. The Oritani FC credit was added at a later date, hence not verified. Nonetheless, it's clearly listed in the next year's edition on p. 281.</ref> '''Total finals (30)'''\u2013that are known. Breakdown follows. '''Wins (11).''' SINGLES: 1920-Sunningdale CC (Scarsdale, N.Y.).<ref>''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17 (singles title). Heading: \"Martin Tennis Winner.\"</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk Tennis Clubs ([[list of counties in New York|Warren & Ulster Counties]]). CONSOLATION SINGLES: 1915-Merriewold TC ([[List of counties in New York|Sullivan Co.]]).<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4; ''The New York Times'', Aug. 16, 1915 p. 6. These sources give the winners in singles, doubles and consolation singles. Martin was staying at the Mamakating Inn in Wurtsboro, during the tourney. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1916 pp. 119, 313. Full results and definition of consolation. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 3, 1916 sec. 3 (social news) p. 6. This source states that \"Martin of the University Heights Tennis Club\" was \"picked to win the tournament\" at Merriewold Park in 1916. (Lost in semis instead.) He had, after all, won a title there in 1915. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>Non-championship final (unlike the other twenty-nine). Nonetheless, a trophy was awarded to the winner.</ref> DOUBLES: 1922-New York Athletic Club.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-07-12/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Hammett\u2013Martin Team Wins\"]. ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1922 p. 13. ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8 (singles semi-finalist); June 28, 1925 p. 6S (doubles semi-finalist); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 24, 1928 p. C3 (doubles quarter-finalist); June 22, 1930 p. C3 (singles semi-finalist). These events were held at the athletic club's [[wikt:home away from home|home away from home]], on [[Travers Island, New York|Travers Island]] (now a peninsula) along the [[Long Island Sound|L. I. Sound]].</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1925-Lake George & West Side Tennis Club (for veterans).<ref>''The New York Times'', May 20, 1925 p. 19 (at Forest Hills); June 3, 1925 p. 21. Heading: \"Martin and Bassford Win.\" Subheading: \"Beat Anderson and Hartmann in 'Over 39ers' Tennis Final.\"</ref> 1931-Lake George. MIXED DOUBLES: 1920-New York TC (for married couples).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 396 (husbands & wives quarter-finalist); ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 25, 1920 p. 10 (singles quarter-finalist); June 29, 1920 p. 11 (husbands & wives title); ''New York Herald'', June 25, 1922 sec. 4 p. 4 (doubles quarter-finalist).</ref> '''Runners-up (19).''' SINGLES: 1919-Woodmere Club (L.I., N.Y.).<ref>''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16 (singles runner-up). ''New York Tribune'', July 17, 1920 p. 9 (singles semi-finalist); July 15, 1921 p. 11 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1922-Essex County (N.J.) CC<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Feb. 15, 1922 p. 631 (doubles semi-finalist); ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 15 (singles runner-up); Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21 (doubles & mixed doubles quarter-finalists).</ref> & Powelton Club (Newburgh, N.Y.).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Nov. 15, 1922 p. 491 (singles runner-up & doubles semi-finalist). The Mrs. reached the singles semis.</ref> 1923-Amackassin Club (Yonkers)<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D & ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1923 p. 4S (singles runner-up); ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', May 29, 1924 p. 8 (singles quarter-finalist). These events were for the Eastern New York State Championship. It was hosted by Amackassin from 1920-24.</ref> & Harlem (Manhattan) TC.<ref>''New York Tribune'', May 16, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21 (singles & doubles quarter-finalists); ''The Evening Telegram'', May 20, 1923 p. 10. Excerpt on Martin: \"The University Heights veteran.\" This corrects misinformation given in a competing paper on 5/20. ''The New York Times'', May 21, 1923 p. 19 (singles runner-up).</ref> 1924-Oritani Field Club (Hackensack, N.J.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476; ''Long Island News'', July 24, 1924 p. 1. It ran from July 5-20. Final: Kynaston over PM 8-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2.</ref> & Stamford (Conn.) Yacht Club.<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 3, 1924 p. D3 (\"Martin Beats Japanese Star\") & Aug. 18, 1924 p. 2A (singles runner-up); ''The New York Times'', Aug. 2, 1925 p. S5 (singles semi-finalist).</ref> 1925-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1930-Lake George. DOUBLES: 1921-Greenwich (Conn.) CC<ref>''The New York Times'', Oct. 17, 1921 p. 12 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up).</ref> & Milford (Pa.) Field Club. 1925-Lake Mohonk. 1926-South Yonkers TC.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2 (doubles runner-up). Final: Franklin & Warren Osgood vs. Martin\u2013C. R. Watkins. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Aug. 8, 1929 p. 13 (singles quarter-finalist); Aug. 8, 1930 p. 16 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1930-Lake George. 1931-Lake Mohonk.<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1923 p. 404 (singles quarter-finalist & mixed doubles semi-finalist); Aug. 15, 1924 p. 370 (mixed doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles); ''The New York Times'', July 18, 1925 p. 11 (singles & doubles runners-up); ''Long Island News'', July 18, 1929 p. 1 (doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 13, 1931 p. 12 & ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 48 (doubles runner-up).</ref> MIXED DOUBLES: 1921-Milford (Pa.).<ref>''The Evening Gazette'' (Port Jervis, N.Y.), Aug. 26, 1921 p. 8 (mixed doubles runner-up); ''American Lawn Tennis'', Oct. 15, 1921 p. 463 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up). It ran from Aug. 16-20. His mixed doubles partner was not Lauretta. A rarity due to a scheduling conflict. She had a first-round singles match, at the Nationals on Aug. 15. ''The New York Times'', June 29, 1924 sec. 1 p. 27. Another rare instance. He paired here with a close acquaintance in Helen Simpson.</ref> 1925-Lake George (with Lauretta). 1930-Lake George (with Lauretta).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles & doubles titles); ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9 (singles & doubles titles); Aug. 15, 1925 p. 7 (doubles title, singles & mixed doubles runners-up); July 12, 1930 p. 3 (singles, doubles & mixed doubles runners-up); ''Citizen Sentinel'', July 16, 1931 p. 12 (singles quarter-finalist); ''The New York Times'', July 19, 1931 sec. 10 p. 7 (doubles title); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', July 20, 1931 p. 14. Heading: \"Bassford, Martin Win Doubles Title.\" The Mrs. was a finalist in consolation singles.</ref> '''Misc.''' He also won many tournaments, which were open only to members of the County Tennis Club in [[Hartsdale, New York|Hartsdale]].<ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 5, 1928 p. 5 (reached the singles semi-finals, with no further results printed); Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22 (singles title); July 17, 1931 p. 1 (mixed doubles title); Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1 (singles runner-up & second straight doubles title); Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1. Excerpt: \"He was a ranking high player of the CC, having won the doubles championship there for several years with various partners, and always appeared in the finals.\" The results of club tourneys usually went unreported. Hence, most of them are lost to history.</ref>\n{{Quote box|width=128px|align=left|quote=<center>[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] singles<br>1920 (1R)<br>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]] (2R)<br>1924 (2R)</center>}}\n'''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] (majors).''' This list is based solely on appearances. He lasted until the stated rounds. National Singles (3): 1920-1R. [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]]-2R. 1924-2R.<ref name=\"nationals\"/> [Lauretta: 1921-1R.]<ref name=\"nets\"/> National Veterans' Singles for ages 45+ (4): 1928-4R. 1929-4R. 1930-3R. 1931-3R.<ref name=\"veterans\"/> It was renamed the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1968.\n\n'''[[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] TC.''' A longtime committee and playing member, who lived in the immediate area. He competed in their annual North Side tournaments between 1913 & 1929 (consecutively 1915\u201325). These open events typically drew a large entry. Singles (12): 1915-5R. 1916-3R. 1917-2R. 1918-4R. 1919-5R. 1920-3R. 1922-3R. 1923-4R. 1924-SF. 1925-3R. 1928-SF. 1929-2R.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15; July 2, 1917 p. 11; July 4, 1918 p. 12; July 3, 1919 p. 10; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 23, 1922 p. 13; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post''; April 5, 1922 p. 15 (cmte.); April 25, 1924 (cmte.); April 22, 1926 p. 15 (cmte.); June 9, 1928 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1923 p. 19 (cmte.); May 9, 1923 p. 16; May 13, 1925 p. 19; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 p. 2D; Sept. 25, 1929 p. 28. SF = semifinals.</ref> Doubles (6): 1913-SF. 1915-3R. 1916-3R. 1919-1R. 1920-3R. 1921-1R. 1922-discontinued.<ref>''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1915 p. 13; July 2, 1919 p. 12; May 3, 1920 p. 11; May 2, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post'', April 5, 1922 p. 15 (D/C). He nearly reached the trophy round in 1913. Lost in semis 3-6, 7-5, 2-6.</ref> Mixed Doubles: 1923-1R.<ref>''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7. This division replaced regular doubles, which was no longer on the agenda.</ref>\n\n'''Memberships.''' These spans were compiled from annuals and newspaper accounts. Maplewood (N.J.) FC 1909-12.<ref name=\"competing\"/> University Heights (Bronx) TC 1913-26.<ref>The Martins moved to the Bronx, after their marriage on Sept. 27, 1912. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9. He first entered a University Heights tourney in 1913. ''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1925 p. 24. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print. ''New York Evening Post'', April 22, 1926 p. 15. Non-playing committee member.</ref><ref>He could have joined the club btw. Oct. & Dec. 1912. It can't be verified, since the tennis season was nearly over by then.</ref> County (Hartsdale) TC 1926-32.<ref>He joined the County TC of Hartsdale / in Scarsdale, sometime after moving to Millwood in Aug. 1925. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; June 26, 1931 p. 2. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print.</ref>\n\n'''Featured Match.''' Eastern New York State Championship of 1925. A first-hand account by ''New York Times'' sportswriter, [[Allison Danzig]]. Excerpts: \"This afternoon [[Bill Tilden|[Bill] Tilden]] and Strachan advanced from the semi-finals of the doubles, by putting out Alfred D. Hammett and Paul Martin at 6-4, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ... It required some of the best tennis that Tilden has played here all week, before the Philadelphians were able to overcome the New York pair. Hammett and Martin were always contenders, except in the third set when they slumped badly; and in order to hold them off, Tilden constantly found it necessary to invade his partner's territory and play the opposing pair single-handed. ... There was nothing to choose between the two teams in the first and second sets. In the third set, Hammett and Martin went to pieces as Tilden became rampant and raked their court with placement drives and volleys. After the Phlladelphians had gained a commanding lead [in that one], the New York pair allowed the set to go without making much effort, preferring to save their strength for the next chapter. But after the rest period, Tilden returned to the courts to play perhaps his best tennis of the match. Both Martin and Hammett fought with everything they had and their team work was splendidly coordinated, but all counted for nought against the individual brilliance of Tilden\" [then ranked [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]]].<ref name=\"Tilden\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 30, 1921 p. 12. Hammett and Martin were clubmates at University Heights. ''Big Bill Tilden'' by Deford, 1976 p. 221. Donald Strachan was one of Tilden's Philadelphia prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.</ref>\n\n==Magazine cover illustrator==\nMost of them are artist signed. The rest are imprinted with the words \"Cover by Paul Martin.\" His signature remained fairly consistent; with a curvature P & M, slanted crossing of the T, and underline mark. Also with the placement of given name above surname.\n[[File:People's Home Journal, May 1928.jpg|left|thumb|115px|(Runner slides home) ''PHJ'', 5-1928]]\n[[File:Collier's2-2-1924.jpg|thumb|117px| \"Business Men's Lunch\": cream pie, chocolate cake, rice pudding and an ice cream sundae. ''Collier's'' 2-2-1924]]\nHis artwork featured on ''Foreign Service'' was initially sold to ''Parents'' in 1930. It went unused and so was dealt to [[American Lithographic Co. v. Werkmeister|American Lithographic]]. They then sold it to the Veterans of Foreign Wars for their publication, in early 1932.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. A letter from Barney Yanofsky to Mrs. Martin.</ref> Martin's artwork featured on ''Die Hausfrau'' (published in Wisconsin) of a boy with five pups ''(pictured above)'', was initially used by the Gerlach Barklow Calendar Company. ''Farm & Fireside'''s  name changed to ''Country Home'' in February 1930.\n\n''Parents''' 25th anniversary issue came out in October 1951. Its unique cover featured twenty-five of their former covers, reproduced in miniature form (one for each year from 1926-50). Three of Martin's made it onto this [[wikt:silver jubilee|silver jubilee]] edition. Their issued dates were Oct. 1928, Aug. 1929 and Oct. 1930. He therefore, [[wikt:in a way|in a way]], won their coveted [[Person of the Year|\"Cover of the Year\"]] award for 1928, 29 & 30.\n\nThe following list contains thirty-seven known credits, from consumer (not trade) magazines. It includes three from September 1925.\n\n\u25cf '''''[[Girl Scouts of the USA#The American Girl|The American Girl]]''''' (1917\u20131979): 10-1931.<ref>It was called ''The Rally'' from 1917-20. This image later appeared on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs, for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Collier's]]''''' (1888\u2013Jan.1957): 5-26-1923, 2-2-1924 ''(pictured right)'', 6-28-1924,<ref name=\"flute\"/> 10-25-1924 ''(pictured above)'', 11-22-1924, 12-27-1924, 5-2-1925, 5-30-1925, 6-27-1925 ''(self-portrait)'',<ref name=\"races\"/> 7-4-1925, 7-25-1925, 9-19-1925,<ref name=\"school\"/> 10-31-1925,<ref>Joe Winkworth paraphrases [[Babe Ruth]] on p. 15. [[wikiquote:Babe Ruth#Quotes|Excerpts]].</ref> 1-16-1926, 2-13-1926, 5-22-1926, 12-25-1926, 2-26-1927, 8-13-1927, 8-27-1927.<ref name=\"slide\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]''''' (1899\u20131929): 9-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t2970.htm#A63781 \"Everybody's\"]. The FictionMags Index. A young swimmer and his rascally dog, Sept. 1925. Alternative path: scroll up, and then click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\">search by name.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Farm & Fireside|Farm & Fireside / Country Home]]''''' (1878\u20131939): 11-1923, 8-1930.<br />\n\u25cf '''''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]''''' (1897\u20131970): 1-1931.<ref>It was known as ''Farm Journal and Farmer's Wife'' (upon their merger), from May 1939 to July 1945. It was then retitled ''Farm Journal'', with a back section titled Farmer's Wife.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[VFW magazine|Foreign Service]]''''' (1914\u2013To Date): 5-1932.<ref>Memorial Day cover. A poster version is shown in ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; May 1934 p. 44. The mag was renamed ''VFW'' (Veterans of Foreign Wars) in 1951.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Das Fenster|Die Hausfrau]]''''' (1904\u2013To Date): 4-1936.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DieHausfrau193604 \"Die Hausfrau\" (The Housewife)]. Internet Archive, San Francisco. The mag had three titles: ''Die Deutsche Hausfrau'' 1904-18. ''Die Hausfrau'' 1919-92. ''Das Fenster'' 1992\u2013. This cover image originally appeared on calendars, ink blotter cards and prints in 1931.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]''''' (1924\u20131950): 9-12-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4083.htm#A88949 \"Liberty\"]. The FictionMags Index. A doll carriage & wagon collide, Sept. 12, 1925. The girl's dark locks were added on. (ALT: scroll up>click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist.\")</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''''' (Oct.1926\u2013To Date): 10-1928,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Magazine for Parents'' from Oct. 1926 to Jan. 1929.</ref> 2-1929, 5-1929,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Parents' Magazine'' from February to July 1929.</ref> 8-1929, 10-1929, 2-1930, 10-1930.<ref name=\"reading\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[People's Home Journal]]''''' (1885\u20131929): 5-1928 ''(pictured)'', 11-1928.\n\n==Book illustrator==\n[[File:BaseballDetective.jpg|left|thumb|69px|''The Baseball Detective'', 1928]]\nHis artistic contributions to [[short story|short stories]], include the following: 1. ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]''. ''Short Turns and Encore'' by various writers, July 29, 1922 p.&nbsp;16.<ref>''Short Turns and Encore''. A boy and girl listening to a Civil War veteran, who's reminiscing about General Sherman. (Viewable online at books.google.com.)</ref> 2. ''[[Collier's]]''. ''The Blanket'' by [[Floyd Dell]], October 16, 1926 p.&nbsp;18.<ref>''The Blanket''. Trio of son (with scissors), dad and granddad.</ref> 3. ''Collier's''. ''The Unfairway'' by Burford Lorimer, December 25, 1926 pp.&nbsp;22-23.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1926dec25-00022 \"The Unfairway\"]. Unz.com. A man, woman and caddie, p. 22. A father and son reading the headline news, p. 23.</ref> 4. ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]''. ''Tragedy'' by Eve Bernstein, April 1928 p.&nbsp;479.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928apr-00477 \"Tragedy\"]. Unz.com. \"The Unz Review.\" A school teacher consoling her grieving student.</ref> 5. ''Scribner's Magazine''. ''On the Dark Trail'' by Franklin Holt, July 1928 p.&nbsp;71.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928jul-00061 \"On the Dark Trail\"]. Unz.com. Young Henry holding a flashlight and hatchet.</ref>\n\nThe first six listed below, are fictional or semi-fictional books for boys and or girls.\n\n\u25cf ''Philus, the Stable Boy of Bethlehem; and Other Children's Story-Sermons for Christmas ... ''. Edmund J. Cleveland, with foreword by the [[The Right Reverend|Rt. Rev.]]  [[Charles Lewis Slattery|Charles L. Slattery]], Sept. 1927. (Credits: [[dust jacket]], [[book frontispiece|frontispiece]] and facing pp.&nbsp;52, 66, 124.)<ref>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11810/pg11810.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1954 (listed under the author). ''[[The Herald News|Herald News]]'' (Fall River, Mass.), Oct. 22, 1927. The following words are atop a Martin illustration: \"Local Clergyman Writes Book.\"</ref> It includes eleven short stories covering the church year. The opener is about a stable boy, who was present at the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]]. These are [[wikt:pseudonarrative|pseudo-narratives]] with a moral message.<br />\n\u25cf ''Puck Chasers Incorporated''. Charles G. Muller, Sept. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and inside pages.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=%22Puck%20chasers%2C%20incorporated%22&f=false#v=snippet&q=%22Muller%2C%20Charles%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927. The book's illustrator was not recorded.</ref> This is one of the earliest books with an [[ice hockey]] theme. Its predecessors tended to be on a combination of [[winter sports]], instead of solely on ice hockey.<br />\n\u25cf ''Araminta''. Helen Cady Forbes, Nov. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;134, 212.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=Araminta.+Helen+Cady#v=onepage&q=Araminta&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927.</ref> Araminta turns eleven years old and finds a kidnapped baby.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Prince and the Pig's Gate, and Other Sermons in Story''. Robert Hugh Morris, May 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;48, 134, 166.)<ref name=gut>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11812/pg11812.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1955 (listed under the author).</ref><br />\n\u25cf ''The Baseball Detective''. Charles G. Muller, Aug. 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;22, 132, 250-''pictured''.)<ref name=gut/> It's a story of [[baseball]], competition, friendship and intrigue at the Fisk School for Boys.<br />\n\u25cf ''Chad of Knob Hill: The Tale of a Lone Scout''. [[Howard R. Garis]], Sept. 1929. Republished in 2013. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and pp.&nbsp;14, 60, 85, 97, 163, 187, 213, 281.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jJ8hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1645&lpg=PA1645&dq=Paul+Martin#v=onepage&q=Paul%20Martin&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1929.</ref> This book has a [[Scouts BSA|Boy Scouting]] theme. Garis created stories about [[Uncle Wiggily]], a gentlemanly [[wikt:rheumatism|rheumatism]]-stricken rabbit.<br />\n\u25cf ''Stories of To-day and Yesterday; Thirty Selected Short Stories, Nine Imitative Stories by Students ... ''. [[Frederick Houk Law|Frederick H. Law]], editor, Feb. 1930. (Credit: frontispiece.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&q=Frederick+H.+Law#v=snippet&q=%22edited%20by%20frederick%20Houk%20Law%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1930.</ref> An instructional guide on how to appreciate and write short stories.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls''. [[Clara Whitehill Hunt]], lead editor, 1930\u201331 and 1931\u201332 editions. (Credits: dust jackets.)<ref>Published annually by [[R.R. Bowker|R.R. Bowker Co.]], 45th St., NYC. They sold the dust jackets in bulk to bookstores. Bowker's would also imprint on them, the retailer's business name and address. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._1.jpg Readers #1]. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._2.jpg Readers #2]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref> The best books for children are carefully selected. Catalog format with descriptive notes. An authoritative guide for parents.\n\n==References and notes==\nContinuity Guidelines. Notes come after the sources. They are directly related or give additional details. This pattern can be harder to follow, when the same source is cited more than once. Keywords are sometimes placed after the page number, in parenthesis.\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Paul_Martin_(illustrator)|Paul Martin (illustrator)|position=left}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin (illustrator), Paul}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:New York Tribune personnel]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male tennis players]]\n", "text_old": "{{Infobox person\n| name = Paul Martin\n| image = Paul_Martin_(illustrator),_studio_portrait.jpg\n| image_size = 200px\n| caption = photo <!-- by Campbell Studio, New York --> taken between 1911 & 1913\n| birth_date = {{birth date|1883|6|6|mf =y}}\n| birth_place = [[New York City|New York City, New York]]\n| death_date = {{death date and age|mf =yes|1932|3|19|1883|6|6}}\n| death_place = [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining, New York]]\n| education = [[National Academy of Design]]\n| occupation = [[Illustrator]]\n| spouse = Lauretta Willey (1880-1972)\n}}\n\n'''Paul Martin''' (June 6, 1883, New York City, New York \u2013 March 19, 1932, Ossining, New York)<ref>Register of Deaths for the Village of Ossining, N.Y. His then home address was in the nearby hamlet of Millwood. ''U.S. Census of 1930''. Backup source.</ref> was a [[graphic designer|graphic artist]] and [[illustrator]]. His artwork appeared on nine different magazine covers from 1923 to 1932. Martin designed the then-world's largest ever electrical display in 1917. He reshaped the then-iconic Fisk Tire Boy in late 1929. He played in [[tennis]] tournaments around the [[New York metropolitan area|Greater New York area]] from 1909 to 1931. Also in the [[US Open (tennis)|U.S. National Championships]] of 1920-[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]], 24 (all after age 35).<ref>Men's Singles was held at the [[Germantown Cricket Club]] in Philadelphia from 1921-23. It then returned to [[Forest Hills, Queens|Forest Hills]].</ref> The annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament is named after him.\n\n==Background==\nThe [[Golden age (metaphor)|golden age]] of illustration began in the 1880s.<ref>[https://www.rafoxsociety.com/what-was-the-golden-age-of-illustration/ \"Golden Age\"]. Path: R. Atkinson Fox Society's homepage>Links>See More. Its key source was ''[[The Artist's Magazine|American Artist]]'' magazine (1937-2012), June 2006.</ref> Major advancements in printing techniques were then taking place. This included breakthroughs in the [[halftone]] process. It made the printing of images for commercial usage more economical, feasible, and realistic. The reproduction of art from [[wood engraving]]s (time consuming and strenuous), was largely replaced with [[photoengraving|photo-mechanical engravings]] (higher accuracy level).<ref>''Scribner's Magazine''. \"American Illustration and the Reproductive  Arts\" by Carrington, July 1922 pp. 123-28. (Viewable online at www.unz.com.)</ref> These and other methods were utilized by artist, writer, teacher, innovator\u2013[[Howard Pyle]], who is generally regarded as \"The Father of American Illustration.\"<ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 10, 1911 p. 11. Obit column. Excerpt: \"He was almost [or like] the father of American magazine illustration, as it is known to-day.\"</ref> Others who gained fame in this field included [[Howard Chandler Christy]], [[Harrison Fisher]], [[James Montgomery Flagg]], [[Charles Dana Gibson]], [[John Held Jr.]], [[J. C. Leyendecker]], [[Maxfield Parrish]], [[Coles Phillips]], [[Frederic Remington]], [[Norman Rockwell]], [[Jessie Willcox Smith]] and [[N. C. Wyeth]].\n\nHowever, the vast majority of illustrators received little recognition, compared to the [[fine art]]ists. This was basically due to their artwork being viewed as more commercially, than creatively inspired. Nonetheless, these unheralded illustrators played a powerful role, in communicating the people's aspirations, concerns, customs, humor, labor, morals and social interests.<ref name=\"historical\">''Cover Story: The Art of American Magazine Covers 1900-1950'' by Heller & Fili, 1996.</ref> One of them was Paul Martin, whose work appeared on the covers of ''[[Collier's]]'', ''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]'', ''[[Farm & Fireside]]'', ''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]'', ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'', ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]'' and ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' from 1923-31. These seven magazines were once ranked among the most widely circulated. They all went out of business long ago, except for ''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''. Their eventual downfall was caused by the changing times (or taste), emergence of radio and television (more attractive medium for advertisers), and economics (increased cost / decreased revenue). The more specialized ones that targeted specific audiences, tended to fare better. Another point is that major advancements in photographic equipment and technology took place during the 1930s. This brought about the gradual changeover (twenty-five+ year process) from illustrated to photographic covers.<ref name=\"historical\"/> The former still lingered on, for its innovative and enchanting qualities, until succumbing to digital media (especially [[Adobe Photoshop|Photoshop]]).\n\n==Collier's==\n[[File:Collier's10-25-24.jpg|thumb|117px|(Calling the play) ''Collier's'' 10-25-1924]]\nGeneral interest magazines (mixture of entertainment, pictures, politics, serials, short stories and sports) were once very popular and appealed to diverse audiences. One of them was the historically significant ''[[Collier's]]'' (founded 1888), which had a revival under new editor [[Collier's#Editors|William L. Chenery]] in 1925.<ref name=\"Collier's\">''A Cavalcade of Collier's'', edited by McArdle (''Collier's'' last editor), 1959 pp. xii-xiii.</ref><ref>''Magazines in the Twentieth Century'', Peterson, 1956 p. 188; ''The New York Times'', August 20, 1974 p. 38.</ref> Martin drew many of its covers during the mid-[[Roaring Twenties]], including seven in 1925 (twenty 1923\u201327). Some artists created a niche and then stuck with it, such as in drawing comical situations, domestic follies, political satire, pretty women or simple pleasures. His recurring theme was of a youthful boy engaged in various lighthearted activities. This included the following:<ref>These seventeen described activities, each appeared on a ''Collier's'' cover between Feb. 2, 1924 and Aug. 27, 1927. Their exact dates are collectively listed in this article, under the heading \"Magazine cover illustrator.\"</ref> catching a baseball, loading up on desserts ''(pictured below)'', playing the flute,<ref name=\"flute\">[https://www.loc.gov/item/ihas.200182868/ \"Collier's\" (6-24)]. Library of Congress at loc.gov. Select: \"Photos, Prints, Drawings.\" Enter: \"Correct Position for the Fingers.\" A beginning flutist wearing a sailor suit and red bow.</ref> decked out in a straw hat, shooting marbles, shoveling snow, carrying books on head, riding a sled, winding up a spinning top, eating turkey at Christmas, bobbing for apples, playing football ''(pictured)'',<ref>[https://fourthgarrideb.com/2014/11/09/colliers-magazine-cover-for-october-25-1925-the-three-garridebs/ \"Collier's\" (10-24)]. \"The Fourth Garrideb - Numismatics of Sherlock Holmes.\" Posted online by G. Ruby, Nov. 9, 2014.</ref> happily swimming, getting a shaved haircut, saying grace, working as a messenger, daydreaming about fishing<ref name=\"school\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=0-W_CQAAQBAJ&pg=PA74&dq=American+Education+in+Popular+Media:+From+the+Blackboard+to+the+Silver+Screen#v=snippet&q=%22refuge%22&f=false \"Collier's\" (9-25)]. ''American Education in Popular Media'', edited by Terzian & Ryan, 2015 p. 74.</ref> and going down a water slide.<ref name=\"slide\">[https://commons.wikipedia.org/wiki/File:Collier'sSlide.jpg \"Collier's\" (8-27)]. Commons. A joyful boy & apprehensive dog, going down a water slide together.</ref> He seldom veered from this subject matter. The most striking departure was for a self-portrait cover. He portrayed himself as a well-dressed, vocal spectator at the [[horse racing|horse races]].<ref name=\"races\">[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Collier's6-27-25.jpg \"Collier's\" (6-25)]. Head shot with add-on mustache. He's wearing a derby hat (amid red carnations).</ref>\n\nHis drawing style was simple yet bold. It captured the carefreeness and innocence of youth. There was a nostalgic element to them. Martin excluded the non-essential details (extra people, structures, trees, scenery etc.), which allowed viewers to make an instant connection. His paintings were often easy to recognize, since their theme and style remained fairly consistent. They sometimes gave the illusion of three-dimensional depth. This was through the use of various techniques, such as overlapping, color intensity or variation and [[perspective (graphical)|linear perspective]]. His cover art never corresponded to anything in particular, but rather had a holiday or seasonal theme or portrayed the magazine's overall image (common practice back then).<ref>''Collier's'' usually preferred cover art that conveyed plain and simple thoughts, unlike its main rival in the ''Post''.</ref> Martin mostly hired local boys for the [[photo shoot|photo sessions]].<ref name=\"hard\">''Hard Row to Hoe'' (literary newsletter), V-9 Fall 2005. \"Golden Era of the Illustrations\" pp. 1-3. Joe E. (Edwin) Armstrong in collaboration with Martin's niece Adele. Excerpts: \"[The] Fisk Tire advertisement, 'A Time to Retire,' with Adele's brother Walter as a model, was his best known work.\" The niece recalled visiting the artist on a particular occasion, with her brother and sister: \"We climbed the oak stairs to the second floor  ... [and] entered a huge bright room ... This was my uncle's studio. ... Although my uncle generally used local models, especially boys, some of our family posed for photographs which would later miraculously turn into paintings. My grandmother was depicted in a Thanksgiving scene basting a turkey ... My brother and I sat for ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls'' while Uncle Paul took our picture, as we sat on the kitchen table of our own house. My sister modeled for Junior Red Cross posters (only one confirmed). [S]he posed as well, taking a license number from a boy's homemade car, for hitting her carriage and doll.\" [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> His drawings were made directly from those photos, and not real life (which required long sittings). This gave him more options and flexibly, as the final version was based on multiple photos taken during the shoot (along with some improvising).<ref>[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._1.jpg|Photo Session #1]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared in the ''Saturday Evening Post'' of Nov. 22, 1930, p. 37. Artist signed. The boy, girls, and refrigerator were photographed separately.</ref><ref name=\"memorial\">[[:File:Composite_illustration_no._2.jpg|Photo Session #2]]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. A model posing for the artist, and its final product. This [[wikt:composite|composite]] appeared on the cover of ''Foreign Service'' in May 1932. Artist signed. The boy is holding a matchbox on a paintbrush stick, in lieu of a flower.</ref> It was also a more practical process, due to active children being involved. He would interact with them, until getting the desired natural or candid expression. His wife assisted in preparing the models for their scenes. ''[[Collier's]]'' couldn't keep up with the rapidly changing times following [[World War II|WWII]], and ceased publication in December 1956.<ref name=\"Collier's\"/> The main culprit was television, which dramatically affected its advertising and circulation revenue. ''Collier's'' top competitors (''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', ''[[Look (American magazine)|Look]]'' and ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Post]]'') adapted somewhat better to the changing times, which helped them hold out longer.\n\n==Graphic artist==\n[[File:H-O_Oats.jpg|left|thumb|139px|H-O Oats, outdoor advertising sign, 1931]]\n[[File:BoyandPups.jpg|thumb|117px|Gerlach Barklow calendar, \"Singin' in the Rain,\" 1931]]\n[[File:Martin_gets_check.jpg|left|thumb|139px|Martin gets a $300 winner's check, 1931]]\nMartin designed [[Wrigley Company|Wrigley Gum's]] light bulb spectacular, which showcased six acrobatic \"[[Wrigley's Spearmint|spearmen]]\" on a [[Broadway (Manhattan)|Broadway]] billboard in 1917. It was then the world's largest ever electrical display at 200' x 50'. It covered the entire city block between 43rd and 44th Streets.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', June 1917 p. 33; ''New York Tribune'', November 10, 1917 p. 1; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', April 29, 1920 p. 6. These [[primary source]]s give descriptions of Wrigley's gleaming sign, that was directed toward the masses. Its energetic mascots with green-pointed heads, promoted the chewy gum's healthy aspects.</ref><ref>[https://digitalcollections.nypl.org/items/510d47e1-0689-a3d9-e040-e00a18064a99 Simulated Movements]. New York Public Library. Digital Collections. This photo doesn't capture the entire rooftop sign. Another three sprightly \"spearmen\" are on the left side. The six of them are doing 'setting-up exercises.' ''The Evening Star'' (D.C.), July 17, 1923 p. 6; ''[[Variety (magazine)|Variety]]'' (NYC), Feb. 7, 1924 p. 18. It operated from 1917-24.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=UK5FAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Wrigley's Gem]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', October 1920 pp. 25 (photograph), 26 (description). Scroll far downward. It was located atop the old Putnam Bldg. That site is now occupied by the [[1501 Broadway|Paramount Bldg.]] ''Illustrated World'', March 1920 pp. 689, 691. Another source with photo/desc.</ref><ref>[https://image.slidesharecdn.com/hist-display-121122214349-phpapp01/95/history-of-lighting-display-exhibit-16-638.jpg Animated Display]. \"History of lighting - display & exhibit\" - SlideShare. Posted online by J. Fonseca, Nov. 22, 2012. The anthropomorphic gymnasts, bubbling fountains and fluttering peacocks, are framed within a vine-like floral design. Also reachable via slideshare.net. Enter: \"History & Theory of Interior Illumination\">click icon>move arrow to pic #16.</ref><ref>''One Times Square'' by McKendry, 2012 p. 17. A watercolor of the fully animated, moving lights, attention-grabber.</ref> This [[Times Square]] light show, was a major tourist attraction for seven years. He drew a poster titled \"Serve Your Country,\" for the War Camp Community Service in 1918. It showed a fashionable young woman serving in tennis ([[wikt:play on words|play on words]]).<ref>[https://collectionscanada.gc.ca/pam_archives/index.php?fuseaction=genitem.displayItem&lang=eng&rec_nbr=3667979 \"Serve\" #1]. [[Library and Archives Canada]]. Path: LAC homepage>Search the Collection>Collection Search. Enter: \"Serve Your Country, Benefit of War Camp Activities.\" Size: 11 x 17\". Many artists lent their talents to the war effort. He registered for the draft later that year, when the cut-off age was upped from 31 to 45. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:ServeCntyTennis.jpg \"Serve\" #2]. Commons.</ref> Women were encouraged to entertain off-duty soldiers, by participating in various social events (dancing, dining etc.).<ref>[https://archive.org/stream/whatnewyorkdidfo00warc#page/n1/mode/2up \"General Summary\"]. ''What New York Did for Fighting Men: Through New York War Camp Community Service in the World-War of 1917-1919'', 1919 pp. 3-4.</ref> A silkscreen version of this poster, has been periodically on display at the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]] in [[Newport, Rhode Island]].<ref>It was donated by Bessie Holden in 1965. This is stated within the frame. ''The Sun'', April 21, 1918 sec. 7 p. 8; July 16, 1918 p. 13. She helped organize the National Tennis Women's War Relief Association. ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 09, 1919 p. 15; June 2, 1920 p. 13; June 16, 1920 p. 13; July 26, 1921 p. 12; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 23, 1922 p. A2; Sept. 24, 1930 p. 25; ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', Feb. 27, 1923 p. 10. Holden and Mrs. Martin both played in these tourneys.</ref> Another two were for the [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]]. The first was titled \"The Flag of Service the World Around\" in 1929. It showed children in international costumes on top of a globe, with one holding a large Red Cross flag.<ref name=\"Red Cross\">''Newport (R.I.) Mercury and Weekly News'', Sept. 6, 1929 p. 5. Heading: \"New Junior Red Cross Poster Designed by Paul Martin, Beautiful and Inspiring.\"</ref> The second was titled \"Juniors Helping Everywhere\" (with twenty miniature scenes) in 1930.<ref name=\"poster\">[https://digicom.bpl.lib.me.us/wwII_posters_redcross/6/ \"American Junior Red Cross\"]. Bangor (Maine) Public Library, Digital Commons@bpl. His niece Edna is pictured second from top right. It's signed in the globe's lower right.</ref> Its purpose was to expand awareness of their various worldwide projects. He created three paintings for the Hecker H-O (Hornby's Oatmeal) Company of [[Buffalo, New York]] in 1931. One showed a confident young football player being patched up, who had oats for breakfast ''(pictured)''.<ref>Titled: \"I don't care, I'm strong.\" Girl cautions boy to be careful, who's wearing a leather football helmet. She's applying a bandage. The girl in real life was the boy's aunt Helen, an older teenager. They went together to this photo session, from their home to the Martins. She walked [[wikt:to and fro|to and fro]], while her young nephew rode a two-wheeled scooter. He traveled/pedaled alone, to all other shoots. [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48644655461_ddb5a9bf75_b.jpg Docs]. Flickr. (Backs up the year.)</ref> The other two emphasized its healthiness<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo2.jpg Weight Gain]. Boy standing on a weighing scale. He says to his real-life aunt, \"You can't call me Skinny now!\" They also posed for another painting for H-O Oats ''(pictured top left)'', during this shoot. [https://archive.org/stream/advertisingoutdo02outdrich#page/562/mode/2up Thumb Pointing]. ''Advertising Outdoors'', November 1931 p. 35. Excerpt: \"Overflowing pep and energy is expressed ... .\" These two images are identical, except that in the latter, McCandlish Litho removed the artist's signature.</ref> and goodness.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:H-O_OatsNo3.jpg Early Riser]. Commons. Boy leaping out of bed, saying, \"Coming mother ... I'm hungry.\"</ref> These advertisements appeared on poster panels, to attract passing motorists and pedestrians. They also had a short run in food markets; on their walls, display windows or hanging from overhead wires.<ref>Their display period was short-lived, since company salesmen continually pushed for their products to be highlighted. This approach existed in the era before food brokers and paid contracts. Many store owners would not allow ads to hang from overhead wires. This was due to their cluttered appearance.</ref>\n\nHe painted three color advertisements for [[General Electric]]'s all-steel [[refrigerator#Domestic refrigerators|\"Monitor Top\" refrigerator]] in 1930. The first and most elaborate featured two boys running a lemonade stand. Their mother is shown looking on with approval, through the open kitchen window.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GE-Lemonade.jpg Ade #1]. ''Saturday Evening Post'', July 26, 1930 p. 43.</ref><ref>[https://nebraskahistory.pastperfectonline.com/webobject/A86A28F8-CE8A-44FD-B8D3-537250952019 Ade #2]. Nebraska State Historical Society. Select: \"Keyword Search.\" Enter: \"Silent Hostess.\"</ref> It appeared as a full-page ad in many different magazines at around the same time.<ref>Mags, 1930: ''Silent Hostess'', vol. 2 no. 5, p. inside cover; ''Post'', July 26 p. 43; ''The American Magazine'', Aug. p. 124; ''Arts & Decoration'', Aug. p. 15; ''Collier's'', Aug. 16 p. 27; ''Country Life'' (pub. in Garden City, N.Y.), Aug. p. 75; ''Ladies' Home Journal'', Aug. p. 70. New York dailies, 1930: ''Auburn Citizen'', July 31 p. 8; ''Friendship Register'', July 24 p. 7; ''Herald Mail'' (Fairport), July 24 p. 10; ''Orleans Republican'', July 23 p. 3; ''Standard Holley'', July 24 p. 5; ''St. Lawrence Plaindealer'', July 15 p. 2.</ref>'' [[Printers' Ink]]'' review from 1930. Excerpt: \"'Electric Lemonaide, 5 cents per glass', reads the sign of the youthful shopkeepers. [They] are soliciting trade in a strenuous manner, as a friendly dog enters into the spirit of the event with challenging barks. ... It is a picture filled with action and story-telling strength. But because the advertised product has been worked in so [[wikt:adroitly|adroitly]], the illustration seems doubly effective and relevant.\"<ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Sept. 18, 1930 pp. 130-32. \"What Constitutes a Story Illustration?\" by W. Livingston Larned.</ref> His other \"Monitor Top\" credits were of a girl playing with blocks (that spell out the company's initials),<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', October 25, 1930 p. 34 (blocks).</ref> and two dressed-up girls listening to an enthusiastic sales boy.<ref>Mags: ''Silent Hostess'', 1930 vol. 2 no. 7, p. inside cover; ''Saturday Evening Post'', Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. Book: ''Advertising the American Dream: Making Way for Modernity, 1920-1940'' by Marchand, 1985 p. 271. Newspapers, 1930: ''Alexandria Times-Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Canyon News'' (Tex.), Nov. 13 p. 16; ''Coshocton Tribune'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Evening Journal'' (Del.), Nov. 26 p. 4; ''Friendship Register'', Nov. 20 p. 4; ''Hanover Evening Sun'', Nov. 30 p. 3; ''Independent and Times'' (New Paltz, N.Y.), Nov. 21; ''Indiana Gazette'', Nov. 20 p. 13; ''Jamestown Evening News'' (N.Y.), Nov. 13 p. 15; ''Ludington Daily News'', Aug. 13 p. 7; ''Morning Herald'' (Uniontown, Pa.), Nov. 20 p. 16; ''Patriot and Free Press'', Nov. 20 p. 9; ''Republican Watchman'', Nov. 14 p. 3; ''Silver Creek News'', Nov. 20 p. 6; ''Salamanca Republican Press'', Nov. 20-21 p. 3; ''Van Wert Times Bulletin'', Nov. 20 p. 8; ''Wilmington News-Journal'' (Ohio), Nov. 27, 1930 p. 2. Kids playing grown-ups.</ref> It was proclaimed as the first reliable and affordable model for residential use (though at a hefty price). He also drew a cheerful boy eating beans for [[Heinz 57]].<ref>''[[Ladies' Home Journal|Ladies' Home Journal]]'', May 1927 p. 71. \"I Know Beans.\"</ref>\n\nHe designed a contest-winning poster for the [[Girl Scouts of the USA|Girl Scouts]] in 1931. It was titled \"Usefulness \u2022 Beauty \u2022 Health \u2022 Truth \u2022 Knowledge.\"<ref name=\"winning\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Excerpts: \"An art enthusiast from his boyhood ... He studied commercial art at the Academy of Design ... Mr. Martin gained a national reputation when he designed the automobile tire advertisement, 'Time to Re-tire' ... He has won several art prizes, including an award last year for drawing the best poster symbolizing the Girl Scout movement. ... Member of the Artists' Guild. He was also a member of the County [Tennis] Club of Westchester and of the Scarsdale Badminton Club.\" The Martins enjoyed playing together, in those two racket sports.</ref><ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (contest-winning). Sizes = 17 x 22\" & 7 x 9.25\".</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200137.pdf \"Prize\"] (PDF). ''The Pelham Sun'', March 13, 1931 p. 7.</ref> This contest was conducted by the Art Alliance of America,<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=w18oAAAAYAAJ&pg=PA174&lpg=PA174&dq=Art+Alliance+of+America#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Alliance\"]. ''[[American Art Directory|American Art Annual]]'' by the [[American Federation of Arts]], 1921 vol. 17 p. 174. They often held competitions, demonstrations and exhibitions.</ref> an organization that brought together craft workers and manufacturers. The six-judge panel consisted of [[W\u0142adys\u0142aw T. Benda|W. T. Benda]] (who replaced [[Charles Dana Gibson]]),<ref name=\"contest\">[https://nyshistoricnewspapers.org/lccn/sn84031094/1931-01-21/ed-1/seq-7/ \"Poster Campaign of Girl Scouts\"]. ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', Jan. 21, 1931 p. 7. Gibson was on the original (not final) judging panel.</ref> Ray Greenleaf, [[Rockwell Kent]], [[John La Gatta]], [[Neysa McMein]] and Edward A. Wilson.<ref name=\"scouting\">[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspaper%2018/Pelham%20NY%20Sun/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931/Pelham%20NY%20Sun%201931%20-%200110.pdf \"Girl Scout Notes\"] (PDF). [[Fultonhistory.com]]. ''The Pelham Sun'', Feb. 27, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Martin's model for the poster was Barbara Smith, a 14-year-old from Darien, Connecticut (who previously lived in Yonkers, N.Y.).<ref name=\"scouting\"/><ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Nov. 6, 1931 p. 20; ''Citizen Sentinel'', Nov. 9, 1931 p. 9.</ref> Her parents and Martin were lifelong friends. He even served as [[wikt:best man|best man]] at their wedding back in 1904.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 1, 1929 p. 6 (best man). It was held at the bride's family home, on Riverside Ave. (then more commonly known as Dr.) in Manhattan, NYC.</ref> His winning entree earned him a first-place check, from the Girl Scouts' National Director [[Minnesota Woman Suffrage Memorial#Josephine Schain|Josephine Schain]] ''(pictured)''. This exchange took place at their old national headquarters on [[Lexington Avenue]] in [[New York City]]. Also, right after the first, second and third place winners were announced.<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'', Feb. 19, 1931 p. 8; ''Dobbs Ferry Register'', March 13, 1931 p. 11; ''The Daily Plainsman'', March 14, 1931 p. 7 (PM\u2013Schain pic, exchange). The first is a slightly different & fuller pose, which was taken within seconds of the other two.</ref> National President [[James Otis (New York)#Personal life|Mrs. Frederick (Birdsall Otis) Edey]] was one of three consultants, along with executives [[Anne Hyde Choate]] and [[Genevieve Garvan Brady]].<ref name=\"contest\"/> This poster ''(inserted in pictured)'' later appeared with three raised fingers instead of a salute, on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Girl_Scouts_Competition_Letter.jpg The Sign]. A change request is initiated by Gilchriese.</ref> It captured the spirit of their character-building movement, and was in popular usage until 1937.<ref>''Girl Scout Collector's Guide'' by Degenhardt & Kirsch, 1987 pp. 163 (color poster), 215 (popular usage). The two catalog dates were verified, by viewing the actual covers. The dates given to them in this book, are slightly off.</ref> Martin said at the award ceremony, \"Barbara seems [to be] the personification of all that [[Girl Guides|Girl Scouting]] means. She is the very spirit of radiant, happy and wholesome young girlhood, and my mind naturally turned to her immediately when I learned of the competition.\"<ref>''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), Feb. 17, 1931 p. 6; ''Lockport Union-Sun and Journal'', Feb. 21, 1931 p. 4 (quote).</ref>\n\nHis drawings also ended up on [[Gerlach Barklow Co.|Gerlach Barklow]] calendars, ink blotter cards and prints for business advertising, such as one titled \"Singin' in the Rain\" from 1931. It showed a boy sheltering several pups from the rain with an umbrella, while sitting down ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1932 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first showed up on its calendars, ink blotter cards (3.5 x 6\" with pink backs) and prints in 1931.</ref> Another showed a boy reading about scientific theories with some difficulty.<ref>''Title Leaves for 1933 Line'' (salesman's catalog). This image first appeared on the cover of ''Parents'' magazine in October 1930. ''Parents'' sold the rights to Gerlach Barklow. One of their artists changed the lettering, and also titled it \"Oh Yeah.\"</ref> Martin's paintings often included a cute and friendly pup (or even several). He drew covers for such [[trade magazine|trade publications]] as ''Advertising & Selling'',<ref name=\"spearmen\">''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. Excerpt: \"It is interesting to note that this [cover] drawing was made by Paul Martin, who while he was with the O. J. Gude Co., designed the famous Wrigley electric sign showing the dancing 'spear-men', still on display in New York. Mr. Martin was for seven years art manager of the ''New York Tribune''.\" This write-up gives him credit for the cover, which otherwise would have gone solely to Gotham Studios. (Gotham's insignia is on it.)</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=kRwYAQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false Photo to Sketch]. ''Advertising & Selling'', January 24, 1920 (cover). Scroll upward. Pencil sketch of an executive with [[John Deere|Deere & Company]]. Magazine's lifespan: 1891-1924. It was known as ''Profitable Advertising'' through May 1909.</ref> ''Good Hardware'',<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:GoodHardware.jpg Repair]. ''Good Hardware'', Oct. 1930 (man fixing clock). Published by Strevell-Paterson Hardware Co., Salt Lake City.</ref> ''Progressive Grocer'' (voice of the industry for food retailers)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=2f08AAAAYAAJ&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Cover Design\"]. ''Progressive Grocer'', Sept. 1922 vol. 1 no. 9 (talking on the phone) & Nov. 1922 vol. 1 no. 11 (weighing a turkey). Credits for them are on pp. 5 & 5. The covers are visible by scrolling nearly all the way down to pp. 113 & 117.</ref> and ''Silent Hostess'' (recipes and tips for homemakers)<ref>''Silent Hostess'' by General Electric, 1930 vol. 2 no. 4 (eating an apple); 1931 vol. 3 no. 4 (flexing muscles); 1931 vol. 3 no. 7 (blowing up a football). Mag's lifespan: 1930-32. Its key purpose was to promote the innovative \"Monitor Top\" refrigerator.</ref> between 1920 & 1931. Coincidentally, the helmet-wearing boy for H-O Oats ''(pictured)'', later served as ''Progressive Grocer's'' associate editor from 1956-62.<ref>''The Daily Bulletin'' (Endicott, N.Y.), Oct. 12, 1956 p. 5. The appointment took effect on Nov. 1.</ref> Martin's first two ''signed'' covers were for this food-oriented magazine.<ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920. Those two are only predated by this ''A&S'' unsigned cover. Its credit is instead, given on p. 12. ''Progressive Grocer'' (1922\u2013). It's dedicated to helping the independent operators.</ref> His work appeared in many different types of print media (including outdoor advertising).<ref>Martin's signature is within every artwork mentioned, in this article. However, there are others unsigned by him, which would be difficult or impossible to prove as credits. A neighbor kid, William Everett [[Millwood, New York#Fire department|Orser]] (1919-2016), posed for him as the [[Dutch Boy Paint|Dutch Boy]]. But no in-print proof. His paintings turned into outdoor signs were not salvageable. Their scaled-down counterparts in grocery markets were largely discarded. Hence, even pictures of them likely don't exist, unless featured in a trade mag.</ref><ref>''The Daily Argus'', Dec. 3, 1921, [[wikt:gravure|gravure]] section. He signed a contract earlier in year, to design greeting cards for [[William Edwin Rudge]]. Its printing plant was located in Mount Vernon, N.Y. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Christmas_card_with_boy,_girl,_dog,_cat.jpg \"Bide-A-Wee\"]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Dec. 11, 1921 p. D23 (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 20, 1921 p. B5; Dec. 17, 1922 p. last; Dec. 16, 1923 p. 33-resorts (\"Skating. Coasting\"); ''New York Tribune'',  Jan. 22, 1922 p. 6; Dec. 03, 1922 p. 5 (\"Skating. Coasting\"); Jan. 29, 1922 p. 6 (\"Snowshoe Trail\"); ''The New York Times'', Feb. 4, 1923 p. 12-resorts (\"They're Off\"); Dec. 9, 1923 p. 7-resorts; Jan. 25, 1925 p. 14-R; Dec. 6, 1925 p. 19-R (\"Skating. Coasting\"). He drew three different pencil sketches, for the [[New York, Ontario and Western Railway|New York, Ontario & Western Railway Co]]. Artist signed.</ref>\n\nAnother credit is mentioned in a publication by the [[Veterans of Foreign Wars]] in 1932. As follows: \"The cover design on this issue of ''Foreign Service''<ref name=\"memorial\"/> is a two-color reproduction of the official 1932 Buddy Poppy poster.<ref>''Altoona (Pa.) Tribune'', May 21, 1932 p. 5; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; ''Brownsville (Tex.) Herald'', May 17, 1933 p. 2; ''Medford Mail Tribune'', May 21, 1933 p. 4; ''San Bernardino Daily Sun'', May 22, 1933 p. 3; ''Bakersfield Californian'', May 23, 1933 p. 7; ''Boys' Life'', May 1934 p. 44. These are examples of its appearance in print.</ref> (It was so named because former soldiers would use that word, in describing their comrades who perished in [[World War I|WWI]].) The original was painted in oil by the late Paul Martin, noted New York poster artist, who died suddenly on March 19th following a serious operation. The poster has been pronounced as one of the most striking and appropriate designs ever used, to depict the symbolism of the [[remembrance poppy|Buddy Poppy]]. (A bright red artificial flower, which was worn in honor of the fallen [[Allies of World War I|Allied soldiers]].) It was completed shortly before the artist's death and is believed to have been his last important assignment [''sic''].<ref>For clarity: The original was painted and sold to ''Parents'' in March 1930. This is based on Mrs. Martin's notes. Also, the model only posed for him from 1930-31. It went unused, and so was sold by ''Parents'' to American Lithographic, and from there to the Veterans of Foreign Wars. They turned this artwork into a poster, and then magazine cover in spring 1932.</ref><ref>''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52 (poster). ''Foreign Service'', May 1932 (cover). Their first known appearances in print. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. His last involvement was with the poster.</ref><ref name=\"reading\">''Parents'', Oct. 1930. A youngster reading their mag with some difficulty. This image later appeared on Gerlach Barklow calendars with altered lettering. Young Donald also posed for Martin's: 1. ''Saturday Evening Post'' ad, Nov. 22, 1930 p. 37. 2. Outdoor posters for H-O Oats (three different scenes). Their mini versions were displayed in grocery stores. 3. Bond Bread, Rollfast Bicycles, Wilson Bats ads (though unknown if any of them, made it to print). 4. ''Foreign Service'' cover, May 1932. However, its photo shoots took place two years earlier. More: They lived on opposite ends of a very long street in Millwood, N.Y. They first met at a short-lived (victim of the [[Great Depression]]) coffee shop in Millwood, operated by the boy's parents. It was called \"Rose and Carl's Restaurant,\" and located across from the railroad depot on Station Road. Martin was a regular customer, who often ordered stuffed cabbage with apple pie. He coupled trips to the post office, with getting a home-baked meal (same bldg.). Their photo sessions took place from 1930-31. (Salary: 15\u00a2/still or $5+/half-day, with free snacks.) The cover model went on to graduate from [[Chappaqua, New York#Education|Horace Greeley (High) School]] (1941) ... take part in the [[Invasion of Normandy]] ([[ADSEC]] unit; landed on June 21, 1944) ... become a sportswriter for ''The Daily Item'' of Port Chester, N.Y. (1948-50), & associate editor for ''Progressive Grocer'' (1956-62).</ref> Those familiar with Paul Martin's career as an artist, declare the 1932 Buddy Poppy poster to be one of his best creations.\"<ref>''Foreign Service'', May 1932 pp. 10, 26 (quote).</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jHibnoOKgZoC&printsec=frontcover#v=onepage&q=%22golden%20rule%22&f=false \"Wear a Buddy Poppy\"]. ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52. A black and white version of the poster. Artist signed. The silky flowers were made by disabled and needy veterans. Proceeds from its sales, provided relief to veterans and their dependents.</ref>\n\n==Fisk Tire Boy==\n[[File:Fisk_Tire_Boy_(1930-34).jpg|left|thumb|117px|Jigsaw Puzzle - Design No. One, 1933. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:The_Kid.jpg|thumb|117px|'''Martin's Most Notable Artwork''', 1930. Artist signed.]]\n[[File:FiskEnvelope.jpg|thumb|150px|Envelope postmarked 1932. Artist signed. His credits include all of (and only) the version with the two-piece pajamas.]]\nPrelude: The [[Fisk Tire Company|Fisk Rubber Company]] (as officially known; founded 1898) was producing automobile, bicycle and carriage tires by 1901.<ref>Fisk Tires brochure, 1901. Size: 4.5 x 6.5\". 12 pp. This handout gives the details, prices, sizes and weights; on its automobile, bicycle and carriage tires.</ref><ref>''Our County and its People: A History of Hampden County, Massachusetts.\" Copeland, lead editor, 1902 vol. 3 p. 504.</ref> Its factory was located along the riverfront in [[Chicopee, Massachusetts|Chicopee Falls, Massachusetts]]. It pumped out 230,000 tires in August 1921.<ref>''Automobile Topics'' (trade magazine), September 24, 1921 p. 443. That total was a record monthly output for 1921.</ref> Fisk struggled financially during most of the 1930s.<ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 278. Excerpt: \"As the [[Great Depression|depression]] deepened, net sales of the company plummeted.\" It forced them to severely cut back on advertising.</ref> They were bought out by [[United States Rubber Company|U.S. Rubber]], [[wikt:AKA|aka]] U.S. Royal (1940).<ref>''The New York Sun'', January 19, 1940 p. 31. Heading: \"Transfer Fisk Assets to U.S.\"</ref> Their international branch acquired a majority stake in [[Englebert (tyre manufacturer)|Englebert]] (1958). Their worldwide names were condensed/simplified into [[United States Rubber Company|Uniroyal]] (1966). They merged with Goodrich, and became known as [[Goodrich Corporation|Uniroyal Goodrich]] (1986). Its tire division was sold to [[Michelin]] (1990).<ref>The deal was struck 1989. Finalized 1990.</ref> The Fisk Tire brand had a dormant period after 1977.<ref>''The Tennessean'', Sept. 15, 1966 p. 69; ''Nevada State Journal'', Dec. 8, 1966 p. 25; ''Poughkeepsie Journal'', Aug. 30, 1977 p. 17; ''Circleville (Ohio) Herald'', Sept. 20, 1977 p. 10; ''Beckley (W.Va.) Post-Herald'', Nov. 17, 1977 p. 21. [[Kmart]] sold the Fisk brand from 1966-77.</ref> This brand was revitalized by [[Michelin]], and produced exclusively for [[Discount Tire]] (1996-2014).<ref>''Tire Business'' (trade magazine), July 6, 1998. \"Time to Un-Retire: Discount Tire Revives Fisk, Escort.\" Editor Dave Zielasko in collaboration with Al Olsen.</ref><ref>See Babcock book, 1966 pp. 97 (aka), xv, 410-11 (names).</ref>\n\nHe completely reshaped one of the most famous characters in the history of American advertising. It was the Fisk Rubber Company's [[wikt:bedtime|bedtime]] boy, who shouldered an oversized tire while dangling a lighted candle.<ref>''America A to Z'' by ''Reader's Digest'', 1997 pp. 364-65. It's listed as one of the eleven, most famous trademarks ever.</ref><ref>''The 100 Greatest Advertisements: Who Wrote Them and What They Did'' by Watkins, 1959 pp. 16-17. Retitled and republished in 2012.</ref><ref>''Logo, Font & Lettering Bible'' by Cabarga, 2004 p. 16. The boy's hair got lighter, as the years went on.</ref> It came with the catchphrase \"Time To Re-tire\" (debuted 1910).<ref name=\"debut\">''[[The San Francisco Call|San Francisco Call]]'', April 30, 1911 p. 44; ''[[Life (magazine)|Life]]'', August 17, 1911; ''[[Country Life in America]]'', April 15, 1912 p. 86; ''[[Collier's]]'', April 20, 1912 p. 30; ''[[Motor (American magazine)|Motor]]'', April 1912 p. 26. These are among the earliest appearances of the advertising character. However, it first showed up on merchandise in 1910.</ref><ref name=\"year\">[https://books.google.com/books?id=ALUpAAAAYAAJ&pg=RA11-PA78&lpg=RA11-PA78&dq Early History]. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78. \"Development of 'Fisk Boy' as Trade Figure.\" The sleepy-eyed character was created in 1910. It showed up that year on lithographs, posters and then one-cent postcards. The latter have periodically showed up on the collector's market. They were postmarked in either late-1910, 11 or 12. ''The Poster'', Nov. 1913 p. 55. \"Why the Fisk Rubber Company Uses Posters,\" by their advertising manager M. G. (Mabel Garetta) Webber. Excerpt: \"He appeared first in 1910.\" (Viewable online at booksgoogle.com.)</ref> This slogan had a simple double meaning. The boy's yawn became a smile in early 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Jan. 12, 1929 p. 78 (print debut).</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317. Mgmt. decided on the facial alteration in 1928.</ref> Martin was then commissioned to come up with a slightly more aged, modern-day figure in late 1929.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8, 1930 p. 106 (print debut).</ref><ref name=\"modern\">''Editor & Publisher'' (mag), March 22, 1947 p. 36. Martin's contributions to \"Master PJs\" are indirectly mentioned. Excerpt: \"At one time, they put him in a modern suit of pajamas, made him a little older.\" This source states the boy was created CIRCA 1907. It's very unlikely the trademark was created three years before debuting. A more likely estimate would be 1909 or 10. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, Dec. 26, 1912 p. 78; ''The Poster'' (mag), Nov. 1913 p. 55. These very early sources claim the boy was created in 1910.</ref> The objective was to update the heavily publicized trademark, while still maintaining its charm and familiarity. The young lad's one-piece sleeper became a two-piece pajama set, during the changeover process. The slippers were also added. His four-year-old nephew was used as the model (neck down only).<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), July 11, 1927 p. 1. Subheading: \"Mr. and Mrs. Jacob Willey Celebrate [50th Wedding] Anniversary.\" This article mentions the Martins, their nieces Adele and Edna, and nephew Walter.</ref> Still, the pose and all-important props remained basically intact (though with the current tire design and a more fashionable\u2014less tilted\u2014candle holder). This new look was described by the publicity manager at Fisk, to a national magazine writer in early 1930. As follows: \"A happy, smiling, 100-percent American boy in his little two-piece pajama, radiating good cheer, ruddy-cheeked and tousle-headed, snappy and wide awake, standing in the old-time pose.\"<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\">''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 27, 1930 pp. 10, 12 (R. G. Bath's quote). \"Don't Be Afraid to Improve Your Trade-Mark: Even the Long-Famous Time to Re-tire Boy Has Been Modernized.\" The boy's three stages are pictured and reviewed. This is a rare [[primary source]] on the third and final stage.</ref><ref>''History of the United States Rubber Company: A Case Study in Corporation Management'' by Babcock, 1966 p. 317 (quote).</ref><ref>''[[Smile, Darn Ya, Smile!]]'' Cartoon short, Sept. 1931. [[Foxy (Merrie Melodies)|Foxy]] notices the new look, after the 3:15 mark.</ref>\n\nThe now-updated version was first used by Fisk Tires, to showcase its newly introduced \"Air-Flights\" in advertisements. This included twelve times in ''[[The Saturday Evening Post]]'', between Feb. 8 and Aug. 23, 1930 ''(pictured)''.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Feb. 8 p. 106; March 8 p. 76; April 5 p. 107; May 3 p. 69;  May 10 p. 128; May 24 p. 61; June 7 p. 67; June 21 p. 89; June 28 p. 87; July 5 p. 69; July 26 p. 91; Aug. 23 p. 38. All twelve issues are from 1930.</ref><ref>His signature appears with the trade character in three of these twelve issues. As follows: March 8, 1930 p. 76 (plain backdrop); July 26, 1930 p. 91 (purple backdrop); Aug. 23, 1930 p. 38 (blue backdrop).</ref> It was offered to the public as an 11x14\" colorful art print, that could be framed.<ref>''Saturday Evening Post'', Mar. 8, 1930 p. 77 (free coupon).</ref> The cheerful mascot went on to appear in many different formats. These were either with or without a facial touch-up.<ref>His credits include all images of the boy, wearing two-piece pajamas. This was the company's logo from 1930-34.</ref> For instance, on the front cover and endpapers of children's books in 1931. Subjects (8): Candy Land, Jack and the Bean Stalk, Little Black Sambo, Peter Rabbit, Pied Piper, Three Bears, Three Little Kittens and Three Little Pigs.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskBooks.jpg Books]. Commons. Softcovers. Size: 5.75 x 7.25\".</ref> They were all subtitled, \"Time to Re-tire / A Bedtime Story.\" It also showed up on ashtrays,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskAshtray.jpg Ashtray]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]]. Diameter 6.75\". Height 1.25\".</ref> bridge score pads,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskScorePad.jpg Score Pad]. Commons. A Gilbert Stuart portrait of George Washington is on the cover. Size: 4 x 6.5\".</ref> cigarette cases,<ref>They came with elastic holding straps on both inside ends.</ref> electrical clocks,<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskTelechron.jpg Clock]. Commons. They were circular in shape, with a rubber tire around the rim. Made by [[Telechron]]. Diameter 5.5\".</ref> jigsaw puzzles (''#1 pictured''),<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:FiskPuzzle.jpg Puzzle]. Commons. Die-cut cardboard. Size: 8.625 x 11\". Set of five.</ref><ref>Design No. 1 - The Fisk Trade Mark Boy. (Martin's signature is next to the boy's left heel.) Design No. 2 - Elephant and Mouse. Design No. 3 - Checker Players. Design No. 4 - The Shadow. Design No. 5 - Baseball. The last four feature an old Reginald Bolles, Kernan or Thrasher painting. Also, a large sign of the new corporate figurehead, in the background.</ref> matchbooks,<ref>It showed up on Diamond Quality, Pull Quick, & Universal Match Corporation covers. The first two were made by the Diamond Match Co. of N.Y. The Pull Quicks had ten wooden sticks, which were ignited by quickly pulling them out.</ref> posters<ref>Titled: \"Coming and Going,\" with an Army/Navy theme and NRA ([[National Recovery Administration]]) logo. That helps date it to 1933 or 34. Size: 28 x 39\".</ref> and rubber heel replacements for shoes.<ref>The mascot with words \"Air Cushion\" & \"Fisk.\" This was a self-repair product. It came in various sizes, incl. a 10-11\".</ref> These were giveaway items, with an automotive purchase.<ref>''New Oxford (Pa.) Item'', April 13, 1933 p. 3; April 20, 1933 p. 14. Ad: \"During this tire sale, we will give absolutely free, one Fisk jig saw puzzle with every tire sold.\"</ref> Martin's version was used by Fisk retailers on their data books,<ref>''Super-Service Data Book'', 1933. Size: 6.25 x 3.75\". 32 pp. It gives the specs on rims and tires, for various car models.</ref> display windows,<ref>These were circular [[decal]]s that stuck onto the inside of glass windows.</ref> letterheads and mailing envelopes ''(pictured)''.<ref>Other variations: 1. Trademark character on both sides, with phrase on back \"Time to Retire / Get a Fisk.\" 2. Character on the front, with phrase \"Air-Flight Principle Tires by Fisk.\"</ref> It appeared in a scaled-down form, in ''[[Boys' Life]]'' and other magazines<ref>''National Petroleum News'', Feb. 19, 1930 p. 120; ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 43; June 1932 p. 53; July 1932 p. 45; Sept. 1933 p. 28; [https://books.google.com/books?id=Zbtu_glJDyAC&pg=PA42&lpg=PA42&dq=fisk+tire+boy+created+1910&source=bl&ots=GGMI39sMhI&sig=pLDn3b09BV89R62Tp-z8KsTueFY&hl=en&sa=X&ei=k3OoU47MJsfhoATUv4LwDQ&ved=0CCkQ6AEwAjgK#v=onepage&q=fisk%20tires&f=false \"All the World\"]. Dec. 1933 p. 42; April 1934 p. 28; May 1934 p. 30; June 1934 p. 42; Dec. 1934 p. 55; ''The American Boy'', Dec. 1933. These tire ads are for bicycles.</ref> (along with hundreds of newspapers)<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%20Disk3/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20&%20Farmer/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale.pdf/Baldwinsville%20NY%20Gazette%20Farmers%20Journal%201930%20Jan%20-%201931%20Dec%20Grayscale%20-%200156.pdf \"Air-Flight Principle\"] (PDF). ''Gazette & Farmers' Journal'', April 17, 1930 p. 3; ''The Cayuga Chief'', April 4, 1930 p. 3; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 10, 1930 p. 10; April 17, 1930 p. 15; ''The New York Sun'', May 8, 1930 p. 47; ''Waterville Times'' May 8, 1930 p. 6; ''The Newark (N.Y.) Courier'', June 12, 1930 p. 6; ''San Jose Evening News'', July 11, 1930 p. 13; ''Skaneateles Free Press'', July 17, 1930 p. 6; ''Binghamton Press'', April 23, 1931 p. 19; ''Van Nuys News'', Aug. 6, 1931 p. 21; ''Dansville Breeze'', Jan. 21 & 23, 1932 p. 3; ''Buffalo Courier-Express'', Jan. 4, 1932 p. 6; ''Medina Daily Journal'', May 11 & June 29, 1933 p. 5; ''The Evening News'', July 19, 1933 p. 16; ''Schenectady Gazette'', May 25, 1934 p. 32; ''Plattsburgh Daily Press'', July 6, 1934 p. 8; July 7 & 19, 1934 p. 5; Aug. 14, 1934 p. 8. Fisk dramatically cut back on advertising after 1930. This was due to the deepening Great Depression, which forced most of their franchise dealers out of business.</ref> from 1930-34. Fisk Tires then went back to the original sleepy boy in 1935.<ref>''The Hogan Handbook'', Fisk-Federal-Badger Tire Catalog, Thomas E. Hogan Inc., 1935 pp. 35-36. The original \"Fisk Boy\" did not appear in mag ads from 1930-36. However, it started showing up on various advertising materials in 1935.</ref> Incidentally, [[Norman Rockwell]] drew many paintings featuring the trade character, which were published in 1917-20, 24-25.<ref>''Norman Rockwell Encyclopedia'' by Moline, 1979 pp. 144-46, 149, 156-57, 161, 167-68, 172, 183-84 (credit listings).</ref> Likewise, J. F. Kernan and [[Leslie Thrasher]] between 1924 & 1927.<ref>Kernan: 1926-27. Thrasher: 1924-27.</ref>\n\nTimetable.<ref name=\"Trade-Mark\"/> Three stages of the pajama-clad boy (based on its appearance in print or on advertising material): a. 1910-28, 35-onward<ref name=\"debut\"/><ref name=\"year\"/><ref>\"Master Pajamas\" lost its luster over time. Nonetheless, the trade character continued to show up on boxes and cans of auto parts into the 1970s. For instance: air filters, antifreeze, brake fluid, headlamps, motor tune-ups, oil filters, shock absorbers, spark plugs and tire cleaners. It has since then appeared on Franklin Mint collectibles, Lionel boxcars, and the label stickers for Fisk Classic tires.</ref> (created by Burr Giffin, an agency art director). b. 1929-30 (change of a yawn into a smile\u2014uncredited). c. 1930-34 (modern redesign by Paul Martin).<ref name=\"modern\"/>\n\n''[[Printers' Ink]]'' article from 1912. Excerpt: \"It was in 1910 that the 'Time to Re-Tire' boy was created, appeared first in a lithographed wall hanger in four colors, and later all over the country for poster display. This is the now familiar picture of the little boy ready for bed, lugging a large Fisk tire on his arm. His reception was sufficiently enthusiastic to cause the advertiser to distribute postcards and reprints in which the boy was the central figure.\"<ref name=\"year\"/>\n\n==Personal life and tennis==\nHe was born to Hannah A. (n\u00e9e Morrow) and Robert C. Martin (a brick merchant) in [[New York City]] on June 6, 1883.<ref>''[[New York Press (historical)|New York Press]]'', December 13, 1890 p. 2. His father was an associate with \"Peck, Martin & Co.\" They dealt in building materials (especially bricks). Excerpt: \"Mr. Martin, who had been employed as a bookkeeper by the firm for twelve years, was admitted as a partner February 1, 1882.\"</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=AevFLAEluDAC&pg=PA23-IA3&lpg=PA23-IA3&dq=%22Peck,+Martin+%26+Co.%22&source=bl&ots=qPSdWJCKg_&sig=ACfU3U2R-HVGcHRS2xH6HJLJgfXCf1BBMw&hl#v=onepage&q=%22Peck%2C%20Martin%20%26%20Co.%22&f=false \"Materials\"]. ''Real Estate Record and Builders' Guide'', Jan. 5, 1884 p. 24-Vi; Feb. 7, 1891 p. 199 (\"Martin & Co.\").</ref> He was the youngest of nine children (three of whom did not reach adulthood).<ref>''Census of 1880''. Search under \"Robt. C.\" ''Census of 1900 & 1910''. They had nine children (six still living). ''New York Herald'', Nov. 5, 1864 p. 3. His parents were married in 1864. ''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4; ''New York Tribune'', July 30, 1917 p. 7. Robert's obit notices. He was survived by Hannah, five sons and one daughter. The funeral service was held at Calvary M. E. Church in Manhattan, at 129th St. and 7th Ave. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1919 p. 22. Hannah's obit.</ref><ref>''[[The Sun (New York City)|The Sun]]'', July 17, 1891 p. 5. His sister Theresa, died at thirteen months. ''The Evening World'', June 20, 1893 p. 7. His sister Hannah Louisa, died at 16. Their funeral services were held, at the family home on Edgecombe Ave. Keywords at [[Chronicling America]]: \"Hannah A. Martin.\"</ref> The family home was on [[Manhattan]]'s 31st St., between 8th and 9th Aves. throughout the 1880s.<ref>''Census of 1880'' (under abbreviated name \"Robt. C.\"); ''New York & New Jersey Telephone Company'' (Directory), 1888 sec. NYC p. 81; ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1890 p. 835. They lived near the future site of [[Pennsylvania Station (New York City)|Penn Station]].</ref> The Martin clan moved way up to [[Harlem|Central Harlem]] on Edgecombe Ave. in 1890.<ref>''The Sun'', Dec. 13, 1890 p. 8. \"Real Estate Transfers.\" Locale: east side (of street), N of 138th. ''Trow's New York City Directory'', 1891 p. 912; 1892 p. 948; 1893 p. 931; 1894 p. 931; 1896 p. 966; 1897 p. 863. Home: Edgecombe Ave. Their address is listed under Robert F (son of Robert C) for 1896 & 97.</ref> They relocated within Central Harlem, to 129th and 5th in 1898.<ref>''Census of 1880''. The family lived on 31st St. ''Census of 1900''. They lived on 129th St.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1899 p. 846. They lived on 129th St.</ref> They belonged to the 24th Street [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1890)<ref>''Minutes of the New York Conference of the Methodist Episcopal Church'', edited by Adams & Strobridge, 1884 p. 74. The father is listed as a church official.</ref><ref>''Comprehensive Church Record of the Twenty-Fourth Street Methodist Episcopal Church'', 1877. This book was viewed by an archivist with the New York Conference, United Methodist Church (White Plains, N.Y.). Department: Archives and History. The Martins and their two oldest sons are listed as members.</ref> and Calvary [[Methodist Episcopal Church|M. E. Church]] (till 1908). Paul's father Robert was the superintendent of their [[Sunday school]]s.<ref>''New York Herald'', July 30, 1917 p. 4 (superintendent). The family switched churches, due to their residential relocation ([[list of Manhattan neighborhoods|Chelsea to Harlem neighborhoods]]). Calvary moved to the West Bronx in 1923. Its [[:File:CALVARY METHODIST EPISCOPAL CHURCH, NEW YORK CITY ABOVE 110TH ST. NY.jpg|original church]] (built 1887) was designated as a historic landmark in 2016.</ref> Martin immensely enjoyed drawing as a boy.<ref name=\"winning\"/> He studied [[commercial art]] at the [[National Academy of Design]] in [[New York City]] from 1902-06.<ref>Summer only 1906. He took classes in Antique (drawing from plaster casts), Illustration (taught by Charles Louis Hinton), and Life (drawing live models). The Academy's archive department supplied these dates and details. ''American Art Annual 1903\u20131904'', edited by [[Florence Nightingale Levy|Levy]], p. 288; ''1905\u20131906'' p. 304 (backup sources). Hinton was then their only instructor in Illustration.</ref><ref>The school was then located at West 109th St. and Amsterdam Ave. in NYC. He continued to live at home, during that time. This was with immediate & extended family, on 129th St. His residency was verified by the school's archive dept.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpt: \"He studied at the National Academy of Design.\"</ref> He worked as the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'s'' art manager from 1906-13.<ref name=\"spearmen\"/><ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. \"Manager. Art Dept. Daily Paper.\" ''Directory of the Oranges'' (N.J.), Price & Lee Co., 1910 p. 400 \"Mgr. NY\"; 1912 p. 429 \"Mgr. NY.\"</ref><ref>''Census of 1900''. He previously worked as a brokerage clerk.</ref> Martin and family members moved from [[Upper Manhattan]] to [[Maplewood, New Jersey]], 1908.<ref>''U.S. Census of 1910''. His household, occupation and residence are listed. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. He played in inter-club tennis tourneys (both singles and doubles), as a member of the Maplewood Field Club.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1907 vol. CXXI p. 1063 (home: 129th St.); 1908 vol. CXXII p. 928 (home: Orange, N.J.). Maplewood was then a section of Orange.</ref><ref>''Trow Directory, Printing and Bookbinding Company'', 1909 p. 937. Robert Martin's occupation (building materials) and residence (Maplewood) are listed.</ref> He started competing in sanctioned tennis tournaments, 1909.<ref name=\"competing\">It's verified through the name-pairing, in the following sources as a whole. ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', Sept. 15, 1909 p. 8; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 pp. 98-99. He played singles and doubles (with H. N. Balch), in the New Jersey State Championship at Morristown. ''Spalding's'', 1910 p. 181. They also played in the Nyack Country Club tournament. ''Spalding's'', 1913 p. 64. Harry Balch and Martin played doubles in South Orange, N.J. ''New York Herald'', July 7 & 21, 1912 pp. 15 & 15. They were clubmates and doubles partners at the Maplewood Field Club. ''Census of 1910''. The two were also neighbors, who lived a few houses apart.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1910-05-17/ed-1/seq-9/#date1=1907&sort=relevance&rows=20&words \"Many Players Put Out\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1910 p. 9; May 20 & 29, 1910 p. 8; June 2, 1910 p. 9; June 21, 1910 p. 9; June 28 & July 1, 1910 p. 9; ''The Sun'', May 29, 1911 p. 4; May 31, 1911 p. 9; Aug. 12, 1911 p. 7; Aug. 14, 1911 p. 9. He participated in many tourneys from 1910-11. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', May 17, 1914 pt. 2 p. 6; July 6, 1915 p. 15; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4. Martin's lean years on the circuit were from 1912-14. His game was elevated a notch by 1915. ''New York Tribune'', Dec. 22, 1918 pt. 2 p. 7; ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 pp. 177, 181. He was nationally ranked for the first time in 1918 (at No. 91). There were no rankings in the war year of 1917.</ref> Martin married Lauretta Willey in 1912.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:MarriageAnnouncementNewYork1912.jpg Card]. Their wedding announcement card gave the date and location as Sept. 27, 1912 in New York. ''Census of 1930''. Their ages at marriage are stated, though PM's is off by one year.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1900''. The Willeys lived in [[Upper Manhattan]], as the century turned. Her parents were Mary Immler (1854-1937) and Jacob Willey (1849-1939). ''The Daily Argus'' (Mount Vernon, N.Y.), Aug. 2, 1937 p. 2; ''The New York Times'', July 27, 1939 p. 19. Their obituaries. Lauretta was raised Methodist. The Martins and Willeys both attended the then-named Calvary M. E. Church.</ref> (Her brother would own the Willey Book Co.)<ref>Their specialty was in reprinting old books. Her brother worked for and later took over the company, from someone who by chance had the same surname. ''U.S. Census of 1910''; ''New York State Census of 1915''; ''New York State Census of 1925''. He's listed sequentially, as an accountant for a publishing company ... office clerk ... publisher from [[New Rochelle, New York|New Rochelle]].</ref> Their first rented home was in the [[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] section of the [[The Bronx|Bronx]], 1912.<ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1913 p. 812; 1915 p. 1258. They lived on Loring Pl.</ref> They relocated a block away in 1915.<ref>''New York State Census of 1915''; ''U.S. Census of 1920''; Westchester County New York Property Records, Aug. 1925. Their home address was on Andrews Ave. They were renters according to the ''U.S. Census''.</ref><ref>''Trow's General Directory of the Boroughs of Manhattan and Bronx'', 1916 p. 1140. They lived on Andrews Ave.</ref> He was employed with the O. J. Gude Company 1913-19 & Gotham Studios 1919-20.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. Martin, as a Gude employee, writes to the Mrs. in 1914. His artistic credits, nearly always went to the company.</ref><ref>''U.S. Census of 1920''. He was living in the West Bronx and working in outdoor advertising. ''Trow General Directory of New York City, embracing the Boroughs of Manhattan and the Bronx'', April 1916 p. 1140 (occupation: artist).</ref><ref>''Advertising & Selling'', Jan. 24, 1920 p. 12. His employment with the ''[[New-York Tribune|New York Tribune]]'' and O. J. Gude Co. are mentioned, in a special write-up. It also gives him credit (via Gotham Studios) for the cover. FamilySearch.org. Search>Records. Draft Registration Card, September 1918. He was then employed with Gude.</ref><ref>''Printers' Ink'', weekly, March 11, 1920 p. 72. He gets credit for a drawing of the [[ancient Greek]] philosopher Empedocles, while working for Gotham Studios.</ref> Those two were giants in the advertising industry. Martin joined the Artists' Guild<ref name=\"winning\"/> and went freelance in January 1921.<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=y1U2AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&vq=guide&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q=%22paul%20martin%22&f=false \"Guild\"]. ''Printers' Ink Monthly'', Dec. 1920 p. 97; Jan. 1921 p. 97. He's first listed as a member, in the latter.</ref> Paul and Lauretta moved from the [[The Bronx|Bronx]] to a rural area of [[Millwood, New York]], August 1925.<ref>Office of the Westchester County Clerk. They provided the property records, on the Martins' two-story home in Millwood.</ref> Their first owned home doubled as a working studio (upper floor) from 1925-32.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:The_Martins%27_home,_Ossining,_N.Y.jpg \"Cottage Tor\"]. Commons. Martin's painting of their home.</ref> Its centerpiece was a long flat-top table that held the canvases, drawing pads, paint brushes and tubes. Also nearby were art books, easels and props for photo shoots.<ref>The props included caps, jackets, jerseys, neckties, pajamas, shirts, sports equipment and sweaters. They sometimes appeared in multiple illustrations. Martin's niece, Adele, recalled the studio's materials and layout in a typed essay. It was for an article in ''Hard Row to Hole'', Fall 2005 pp. 1-3 (but didn't make it into print). [https://live.staticflickr.com/65535/48627229401_c4c1c40896_b.jpg Article (pp. 2-3)]. Flickr.</ref> He occasionally used family members as models. Uncle Paul's niece Edna is shown, writing down the license number of a boy's wagon (for knocking over her doll carriage),<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]'' cover of September 12, 1925. She's also highlighted on an [[American Red Cross|American Junior Red Cross]] poster.<ref name=\"hard\"/><ref name=\"poster\"/> His mother-in-law is shown [[basting (cooking)|basting]] a turkey for [[Thanksgiving dinner|Thanksgiving]],<ref name=\"hard\"/> on the ''[[People's Home Journal]]'' cover of November 1928.\n\n[[File:TrophyWCTL.jpg|left|thumb|69px|Paul Martin Memorial Trophy]]\nHe was ranked among the top thirty tennis players in the [[New York metropolitan area]], from 1920-25 (top twenty 1923\u201324).<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1924 p. 97 (top twenty for '23); 1925 p. 92 (top twenty for '24). He was ranked in the teens from 1923-24.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Nov. 13, 1920 p. 12. Metro players were first officially ranked in 1920. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1921 pp. 29 (USA ranking), 109 (NY metropolitan area).</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', Dec. 5, 1920 sec. 9 p. 2 (ranked between 18 & 31); Jan. 8, 1922 sec. 9 p. 1 (top 30); Jan. 14, 1923 sec. 1 pt. 2 p. 1 (top 30); Dec. 11, 1923 p. 24 (top 20); Jan. 25, 1925 p. 4S (top 20); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Jan. 25, 1925 p. 6D (top 20); Dec. 27, 1925 p. C3 (top 25).</ref> His strength was in making accurate shots.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11; ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3.</ref> Martin won numerous trophies (or awards) in singles, doubles and mixed doubles (with Lauretta) between 1919 & 1931.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1919-09-08/ed-1/seq-16/#date1=1919&index=1&rows/ \"Woodmere\"]. ''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16. He won the runner-up trophy. That's assuming they were (as normally) awarded to the top two finishers. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1919 p. 225. The prize that year in particular, could have been a certificate or medal.</ref><ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. His first tournament win (excl. consolation singles). ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1918 p. 33. This sanctioned husbands-and-wives event began in 1918. The unique idea was proposed by future HOFer [[Marie Wagner]].</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19311016.2.21 \"Club Title\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1. His last tournament win, which came at age 48. Victor in doubles. (Also runner-up in singles.) These events were open only to members of their club. However, he also won a sanctioned tourney that year, at Lake George, N.Y. (See Ref #232.)</ref> This included, for example, one for capturing the inaugural championship at Sunningdale Country Club in 1920.<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1920/07/11/112662657.pdf \"Martin Tennis Winner\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17. It was held on the Sunningdale Courts in Scarsdale, N.Y.</ref><ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=l-c9AQAAMAAJ&printsec=frontcover&source=gbs_ge_summary_r&cad=0#v=onepage&q&f=false \"Second Annual Tournament\"]. ''American Lawn Tennis'', June 15, 1921 p. 135. Scroll downward. Excerpt: \"The first leg on this cup was won in 1920 by Paul Martin.\"</ref> Others were for the Lake George<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles title); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 2, 1925 p. 2F (alternate source). The latter states that Martin was the Lake George champion of 1924.</ref> and Lake Mohonk<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20Freeman/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale/Kingston%20NY%20Daily%20FreeMan%201924%20Grayscale%20-%200870.pdf \"Ulster County Tennis Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles).</ref> Championships of 1924. Martin's opponents included future Hall of Famers [[Fred Alexander]],<ref>''The Sun'', June 22, 1910 p. 9. It was headlined by [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]], [[William Larned]].</ref> [[Jean Borotra]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 2, 1925 p. 2A [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|(National Indoor Doubles]]). Their match was played on the drill floor, of Manhattan's [[Seventh Regiment Armory]].</ref> [[Francis Hunter]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1919-07-07/ed-1/seq-12/ \"Hunter Gains Place in Round Before Semi-Finals\"] (subheading). ''New York Tribune'', July 7, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12.</ref> [[Gerald Patterson]],<ref name=\"Patterson\">''Schenectady Gazette'', August 28, 1924 p. 9. \"Patterson, after encountering some difficulty and losing a set to Paul Martin of New York ...\" ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', August 27, 1924 p. 2. \"Gerald Patterson, Australian Davis Cup captain, quickly finished off his opponent, Paul Martin of New York, by taking the fourth and deciding set of their postponed match without the loss of a game. The Anzac had dropped a long deuce set to Martin [on] Monday but he was invincible today.\" ''The New York Times'', Aug. 28, 1924 p. 12. This was the National Championship at Forest Hills. Patterson went on to reach the semi-finals.</ref> [[Vincent Richards]],<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-05-18/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Close Finishes\"]. ''New York Tribune'', May 18, 1918 p. 14. Excerpt: \"In the second round, there was a keenly fought struggle between Richards\u2013Fischer and Paul Martin\u2013[[United States Tennis Association#Presidents|Jones W. Mersereau]].\" ''The Sun'', Aug. 21, 1918 p. 11; ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13; March 17, 1919 p. 17 (Hawthorne column); May 8, 1919 p. 22. The schoolboy prodigy and seasoned veteran were clubmates at Univ. Hts. ''The New York Times'', April 4, 1919 p. 12. Richards simultaneously belonged to the New York TC. ''The Sun'', July 6, 1919 sec. 2 p. 3. Martin over Richards by default. ''The Sun'', Oct. 6, 1919 p. 20; ''The New York Times'', Oct. 19, 1919 p. 6S. They were no longer clubmates by now. ''New York Tribune'', June 24, 1922 p. 11. They met in a 4th round match.</ref> [[Bill Tilden]],<ref name=\"Tilden\">''The New York Times'', June 28, 1925 p. 6S. They faced off at the [[New York Athletic Club]]'s country home, on Travers Island in New Rochelle. \"Big Bill\" went on to win the singles (over Vincent Richards) & doubles titles.</ref> [[John Van Ryn]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', April 3, 1924 p. 2A. [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoors]]. It was hosted by the 7th Regt. Armory. ''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476. Martin d. Van Ryn 6-4, 2-6, 6-4.</ref> [[Marie Wagner]]<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-10-15/ed-1/seq-21 \"Kynaston is Victor\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21. A mixed doubles match at West Orange, N.J. ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 52. The Martins over Wagner\u2013Calder at Lake George 3-6, 11-9, 2-0 default. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19. His wife faced Wagner in the second round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref> & [[Watson Washburn]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 20, 1919 p. 13. An inter-club tourney (unlike the rest). Heylman\u2013Washburn d. PM\u2013Robinson 6-3, 7-5.</ref><ref>''New York Tribune'', June 7, 1910 p. 8. [[Karl Behr]] over Martin by default at Englewood, N.J.</ref> Other standouts were [[Herbert Bowman]],<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15 (4R-West Bronx); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 23, 1921 p. 19 (5R-Hoboken, N.J.); ''The New York Times'', June 2, 1923 p. S8. Martin won after losing the first set 0-6. ''The New York Times'', June 12, 1925 p. 17 (5R-Montclair, N.J.); ''Buffalo Courier'', July 10, 1925 p. 10 (4R-Syracuse); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', June 9, 1928 p. 12. They were clubmates at Hartsdale. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 22, 1930 p. C3. They met in the semi-finals of the Eastern Clay Court Championship, at Travers Island.</ref><ref>''The New York Times'', April 12, 1925 p. 16. Bowman and Martin came back from near defeat, to win an exhibition doubles match at the Briarcliff Lodge TC.</ref> [[Wylie Grant]],<ref>''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1910 p. 181; 1912 p. 160. Sequentially: Grant\u2013Rosenbaum over Balch\u2013Martin 6-1, 6-2 and Friedman\u2013Grant over Balch\u2013Martin 7-5, 6-2.</ref> [[Walter Merrill Hall]],<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1921/07/23/109816164.pdf \"Net Stars Advance\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', last (final) edition, July 1, 1922 p. 7; May 17, 1925 p. 2D.</ref> [[Robert Kinsey]],<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/Newspapers%206/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale/New%20York%20NY%20Tribune%201922%20Jul%20Grayscale%20-%200716.pdf \"Kinsey Brothers Score\"] (PDF). ''New York Tribune'', July 24, 1922 p. 11.</ref> Percy Kynaston,<ref>''New York Tribune'', March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21; ''The New York Times'', May 15, 1923 p. 17; June 15, 1923 p. 17 (semifinals match\u2013Montclair, N.J.); Aug. 22, 1923 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D; ''Long Island News and the Owl'', July 24, 1924 p. 1.</ref> [[Nathaniel Niles (figure skater)|Nathaniel Niles]],<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5 (Westchester Biltmore CC in Rye).</ref> Dr. William Rosenbaum,<ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1919/09/15/118159201.pdf \"Rosenbaum Wins at Net\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 13. Martin eliminated Fred Anderson (older brother of Frank), earlier in the tournament. Anderson and Rosenbaum were both finalist, at different times, in the [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Singles]].</ref> [[S. Howard Voshell|Howard Voshell]]<ref>''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1910 p. 9; June 25, 1920 p. 15; June 24, 1922 p. 11. Voshell won back-to-back [[U.S. National Indoor Championships|National Indoor Tennis Championships]].</ref> & Charles Wood.<ref>''The New York Times'', May 29, 1923 p. 12. Heading: \"Martin conquers Wood at Yonkers.\" ''The New York Times'', June 20, 1924 p. 22. Wood played in every [[U.S. Pro Tennis Championships draws, 1927\u20131945|National Professional Tennis Championship]] from 1927-36.</ref> A doubles partner and longtime clubmate was newspaper columnist [[Franklin P. Adams]], who wrote \"[[Baseball's Sad Lexicon]].\"<ref name=\"fellow\">''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030431/1916-08-13/ed-1/seq-14/ \"Semi-Finals Reached\"]. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2; Sept. 17, 1917 p. 11; [https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-05-28/ed-1/seq-10/ \"Heights Team Wins\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', May 28, 1920 p. 10; [https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Martin belonged to the University Heights TC (as stated in all of the above). ''New York Tribune'', May 10, 1915 p. 15. A fellow clubmate was [[Franklin P. Adams]]. ''The Sun'', July 30 & Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 4, 1915 pt. 2 p. 4; July 1, 1917 pt. 2 p. 3 & July 2, 1917 p. 11; June 30, 1919 p. 12; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 22, 1922 p. 9; ''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7; May 4, 1924 sec. 10 p. 6. They both played in these tourneys, put on by University Heights. ''New York Tribune'', July 2, 1919 pp. 10, 12. Columnist Adams mentions that event volunteer Mrs. Martin; served him cake, sandwiches and tea for refreshments. Her husband and Adams formed a tandem.</ref> A teammate was the reigning national boy champion, 14-year-old [[Vincent Richards]].<ref>''New York Tribune'', Oct. 1, 1917 p. 13. Seven-member team: Behr, Clapp, Fischer, Martin, Mersereau, Richards, Whyte (not White). ''The Sun'', Aug. 26, 1917 sec. 2 p. 2. Boy's title.</ref>\n\nMartin competed with [[Bill Tilden]] in well over a dozen tournaments,<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1918-06-03/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Reach Fourth Round\"]. ''New York Tribune'', June 3, 1918 p. 13; May 18, 1918 p. 14; March 28, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21; July 14, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun'', May 14, 1919 p. 16; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 15, 1925 p. 2A; June 24, 1925 p. 2A; Feb. 17, 1926 p. 2A; May 16, 1926 p. 2C; Aug. 8, 1926 p. C5; ''Philadelphia Inquirer'', Aug. 13, 1928 p. 13; ''Syracuse American'', Aug. 11, 1929 p. 8.</ref> including the [[US Open (tennis)|National/US Open Championships]] of 1920, [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|21]] & 24.<ref name=\"nationals\">Men's Singles: ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 31, 1920 p. 11; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 1, 1921 p. 2; ''The Sun'', Aug. 20, 1924 p. 26. Tilden won every National from 1920-25.</ref><ref>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921 Nationals]]. Sec. 8. 2R: Rogers vs. Martin. His wife Lauretta, played in the women's division.</ref> The latter was played at newly built [[West Side Tennis Club|Forest Hills Stadium]], and on its outlying courts. He faced off against two-time [[list of Wimbledon gentlemen's singles champions|Wimbledon champion]], [[Gerald Patterson]] of [[Australia]]. 41-year-old Martin won a set, though lost the match 4-6, 4-6, 9-7, 0-6.<ref name=\"Patterson\"/><ref>[http://www.todor66.com/tennis/US_Open/Men_1924.html \"Round of 64\"]. Complete results. Compiled by T. Krastev.</ref> (There was a one-day [[rainout (sports)|rain delay]] after the third set.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 486. Excerpt: \"Upon resuming, Patterson won six games in a row, despite Martin's steady play.\"</ref> He also competed on these same Forest Hills courts, in four straight [[US Open (tennis)|National Championships]] for veterans (ages 45+) from 1928-31.<ref name=\"veterans\">''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1929 p. 51. Excerpt: \"[[Philip B. Hawk|Dr. Hawk]] went into the semi-final against Bassford with a victory over PM of New York.\" ''Spalding's'', 1930 p. 31. Excerpt: \"[[Jean Baptiste Adoue|{{bracket|Jean Adoue}}]] engaged PM of New York in the longest and closest match of the tournament, which required forty-eight games.\" ''Spalding's'', 1931 p. 27. ''Wright & Ditson Officially Adopted Lawn Tennis Guide'', 1932 p. 13. He lasted twice until both the third and fourth rounds. (Age REQ later lowered.)</ref> Martin was a standout singles and doubles player, for both the University Heights (Bronx, N.Y.)<ref name=\"fellow\"/> and County (Scarsdale, N.Y.)<ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 23, 1928 sec. 11 p. 8; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22; Aug. 15, 1930 p. 1; June 26, 1931 p. 2. It was also called the County TC of Hartsdale or Westchester. He joined this club, after moving from the Bronx to Millwood in August 1925.</ref> Tennis Clubs. He was unwittingly caught up in the famous player-writer dispute of 1924 (overview in reference<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 pp. 1-2D. The [[United States Tennis Association|USLTA]] adopted the player-writer rule on Feb. 2, 1924. It stated that any active player who received payment for writing on tennis, would be stripped of their amateur status starting Jan. 1, 1925. This resolution was easily approved by its members, who voted in blocks (47,196 to 6,250). It would have most deeply affected Bill Tilden, followed distantly by Vincent Richards. Strong opposition came from the influential [[Stephen Wallis Merrihew|S. Wallis Merrihew]], fans and writers.  A petition was signed by, among others, 12 [not 18] of the top 25 ranked racketmen from the [[New York metropolitan area|NY Metro Area]]. It rebuked the new rule that redefined amateurism. [[Walter Merrill Hall]] (#11) and Martin (#18) did not sign on with the pro-Tilden forces. They instead wrote a separate letter (full text printed, p. 2D), urging its reconsideration. A special committee of seven was formed, to further study the troubling matter on Nov. 2, 1924. (This was after a months-long selection process, to fill the final three critical spots.) It consisted of Arthur Hellen, Merrihew, Jones Mersereau, [[Devereux Milburn]], Senator [[George W. Pepper|George Pepper]], [[Grantland Rice]] and Tilden. Their report was released on Dec. 13. The USLTA accepted its recommendations, to greatly modify the anti-writing resolution. The alternative was to face continued backlash.</ref>). The distinction between amateurism and professionalism was hotly contested from Feb.-Dec. 1924. He often acted as the women's [[official (tennis)#Off-court officials|referee]].<ref>''The New York Times'', June 12, 1923 p. 17. Heading: \"Women to Meet at Nets.\" ''American Lawn Tennis'', July 15, 1924 p. 249. ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9. Chairwoman Helen Simpson supervised the event. ''New York Evening Post'', June 9, 1925 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', June 7, 1925 p. 8S. Martin was the tournament referee, and in charge of accepting entries. His wife served on its committee. ''New York Evening Post'', June 19, 1925 p. 14. Former [[U.S. Women's Indoor Championships|national indoor champion]], Helene Pollak Falk, nearly collapsed during a semi-finals match. Referee Paul assisted her off the court. ''The Post-Star'', July 21, 1925 p. 11; ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1930 p. 166.</ref> He organized tournaments for youngsters, as a committee member of the [[Briarcliff Lodge]] Sports Club.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19260820.2.12 \"Younger Tennis Players\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 20, 1926 pp. 1, 10; Aug. 15, 1925 p. 9.</ref> The [[Westchester County, New York|Westchester County]] Tennis League is the oldest continuously running of its kind, in the United States (est. 1924). They hold the annual Paul Martin Singles Tournament.<ref>[http://www.wctl.net/tennis/about.shtml \"Westchester County Tennis League\"]. The WCTL has hosted the event every year since 1932 (excluding 1942-45). This was last verified via email with a league rep in 2019. ''[[Sports Illustrated]]'', June 15, 1964 p. E3 (event's host).</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201932%20Grayscale%20-%201075.pdf \"Annual County Net Tourney\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 21, 1932 p. 14. Club managers decide to honor Martin. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 4; June 29, 1934 p. 14; July 10, 1936 p. 1. The person most responsible for its establishment was Fenimore Cady, of the Mount Pleasant Tennis Club in Pleasantville.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19320819.2.3 \"Memorial Tourney to Start\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 19, 1932 p. 1.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201935%20Grayscale%20-%202925.pdf \"Paul Martin Memorial Play\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 28, 1935 p. 19. It was originally called the Paul Martin Memorial Tennis Tournament, and included singles and doubles competition.</ref> The winners of this event have their names engraved, on one of his prized cups ''(pictured)''.<ref>A second-place trophy in the third annual Essex County Championship (W. Orange, N.J.). It ran from Oct. 8-14, 1922.</ref><ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (names engraved).</ref><ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1 (column's end); Sept. 9, 1932 p. 1; Oct. 7, 1932 p. 14; Sept. 22, 1933 p. 11. The singles winner of the annual County TC tournament (for members only), started having their names engraved on another PM memorial cup in 1932. It was Martin's trophy for finishing second at Harlem in 1923. The cup's future history\u2013unknown.</ref>\n\nMartin died of ulcers at age 48, following a major operation at Ossining Hospital in 1932.<ref name=\"hospital\">''Citizen Sentinel'' (Ossining, N.Y.), March 19, 1932 p. 1. Subheading: \"Originator of 'Time to Re-Tire' series succumbs after operation.\" Excerpt: \"Funeral services will be Tuesday night at 7 o'clock, at the Highland Avenue M. E. Church.\"</ref><ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', April 20, 1932 p. 64. Excerpts: \"Paul Martin, well known in New York tennis circles and a [former] member of the University Heights Tennis Club, died suddenly ... For some time Martin had been troubled with pains in the stomach.\" His passing was also noted in the Table of Contents on p. 3. ''Printers' Ink'', weekly, 1932 vol. 158:2 p. 80.</ref> The funeral service was held at [[Downtown Ossining Historic District#Zoning and regulation|Highland (now United) Methodist Church]] in [[Ossining, New York (town)|Ossining]].<ref name=\"hospital\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', March 20, 1932 sec. 2 p. 7. Excerpts: \"An artist specializing in advertising ... studied at the National Academy of Design. ... Funeral services will be held Tuesday in the Highland Methodist Church.\"</ref> Survivors included three brothers and one sister. His wife Lauretta \"Lolly\" (1880-1972) outlived him by forty years.<ref>Lifespan: July 7, 1880, New York City, N.Y. - Aug. 14, 1972, Mount Vernon, N.Y. She was predeceased by her brother and sister. ''Social Security Death Index'' (SSDI). Her birth year is listed as 1880.</ref> They both played in the singles draw of the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]]<ref name=\"nets\">[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1921-08-14/ed-1/seq-19 \"First Round Schedule ... 2pm\"]. ''New York Tribune'', Aug. 14, 1921 pt. 1 p. 19. She competed in the [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Women's Singles|Women's National Championship]] (US Open) of 1921. The final was between Molla Mallory and Mary K. Browne. This Forest Hills tournament featured the heavily publicized, American debut of [[Suzanne Lenglen]]. Both Martins played in the singles draw of the 1921 Nationals. It's a trivial, though rare, occurrence for a married couple (in the same year). Others: Clarence Hobart\u2013Augusta Schultz (1905), Nathaniel Niles\u2013Martha Pitkin (1920-21), Marjorie Gladman\u2013John Van Ryn (1931-37), Nell Hall\u2013Harry Hopman (1938), Frank Kovacs\u2013Virginia Wolfenden (1941), Edwin Cooke\u2013Sarah Palfrey (1945), Lew Hoad\u2013Jenny Staley (1956), Carole Caldwell\u2013Clark Graebner (1964-65), Bill Bowrey\u2013Lesley Turner (1969), Chris Evert\u2013John Lloyd (1979, 81, 83-85).</ref> and were regular mixed doubles partners.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030273/1920-06-29/ed-1/seq-11/ \"Mr. and Mrs. Martin Win\"]. ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 29, 1920 p. 11. Subheading: \"Earn Husband and Wife Metropolitan Tennis Championship.\" ''The Sun and New York Herald'', Sept. 24, 1920 p. 9. They lasted until the fourth round at Hoboken, N.J.</ref><ref>[https://timesmachine.nytimes.com/timesmachine/1922/10/13/107073908.pdf \"Finals Reached\"] (PDF). ''The New York Times'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 22. Their names are listed near the column's end.</ref><ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19291025.2.41 \"County Club is Victorious\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 25, 1929 p. 3. Their mixed doubles win was credited to the team. [https://news.hrvh.org/veridian/cgi-bin/senylrc?a=d&d=scarsdaleinquire19310717.2.14# \"County Tennis Club\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', July 17, 1931 p. 1. Their victory was in a club tournament.</ref> She donated the tournament trophy named after her husband.<ref>[https://fultonhistory.com/newspaper%2010/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale/Yonkers%20NY%20Herald%20Statesman%201934%20Grayscale%20-%201595.pdf \"County League Sets Draw\"] (PDF). ''The Herald Statesman'', June 29, 1934 p. 22 (donated trophy).</ref> His painting \"Serve Your Country\" was once prominently displayed, in the main room of the [[International Tennis Hall of Fame|International Tennis Hall of Fame Museum]].<ref>A silkscreen print (serigraph) made from the original painting. It was first on display at that location in 1965. It has since then been periodically exhibited in various areas. This was verified by the museum's research center, and a letter in its files by Sec-Treas. Heffernan (dated Dec. 3, 1965).</ref> Its gift shop periodically offered a coffee mug<ref>Dimensions: Height 3.75\". Width 3.25\" (w/o handle). The Hall of Fame's logo is on the image's opposite side.</ref> and postcard version ''(pictured)''. He was known for his athletic ability, active participation, friendliness and sportsmanship.<ref>[https://news.hrvh.org/cgi-bin/newshrvh?a=d&cl=search&d=scarsdaleinquire19340622.2.26 \"Paul Martin Tennis Tourney\"]. ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 22, 1934 p. 1 (attributes).</ref> ''Bronxville Press'' column from 1932. Excerpt: \"His presence was always felt by topnotchers, as well as by those who could play only an average game. Paul Martin was a synonym for all that was clean and wholesome in the game.\"<ref>''[[Bronxville, New York| Bronxville]] Press'', Aug. 16, 1932 p. 4. \"The Village Vagabond.\" (Viewable online at news.hrvh.org. Select: \"Browse by title.\")</ref>\n\n==Total finals and more==\n[[File:ServeYourCountry.jpg|thumb|117px|(Serving in style) WWI poster, 1918]]\nThis list only includes open or invitational tournaments, which were sanctioned by the [[United States Tennis Association|United States Lawn Tennis Association]]. Their results largely determined the player rankings, and who qualified for the [[US Open (tennis)|Nationals]]. These [[wikt:semimajor|semi-majors]] are categorized by the event's host.<ref>''Spalding's Tennis Annual'', 1923 pp. 306, 311-14. These clubs are all listed as [[United States Tennis Association|association members]], except for South Yonkers. That's due to its courts not being dedicated until May 25, 1924. The Oritani FC credit was added at a later date, hence not verified. Nonetheless, it's clearly listed in the next year's edition on p. 281.</ref> '''Total finals (30)'''\u2013that are known. Breakdown follows. '''Wins (11).''' SINGLES: 1920-Sunningdale CC (Scarsdale, N.Y.).<ref>''The New York Times'', July 11, 1920 sec. 1 p. 17 (singles title). Heading: \"Martin Tennis Winner.\"</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk Tennis Clubs ([[list of counties in New York|Warren & Ulster Counties]]). CONSOLATION SINGLES: 1915-Merriewold TC ([[List of counties in New York|Sullivan Co.]]).<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 16, 1915 sec. 2 p. 4; ''The New York Times'', Aug. 16, 1915 p. 6. These sources give the winners in singles, doubles and consolation singles. Martin was staying at the Mamakating Inn in Wurtsboro, during the tourney. ''Spalding's Lawn Tennis Annual'', 1916 pp. 119, 313. Full results and definition of consolation. ''The Sun'', Aug. 13, 1916 sec. 2 p. 2. ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Sept. 3, 1916 sec. 3 (social news) p. 6. This source states that \"Martin of the University Heights Tennis Club\" was \"picked to win the tournament\" at Merriewold Park in 1916. (Lost in semis instead.) He had, after all, won a title there in 1915. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:OJGude.jpg Cachet]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref><ref>Non-championship final (unlike the other twenty-nine). Nonetheless, a trophy was awarded to the winner.</ref> DOUBLES: 1922-New York Athletic Club.<ref>[https://chroniclingamerica.loc.gov/lccn/sn83030214/1922-07-12/ed-1/seq-13/ \"Hammett\u2013Martin Team Wins\"]. ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1922 p. 13. ''The New York Times'', July 23, 1921 p. 8 (singles semi-finalist); June 28, 1925 p. 6S (doubles semi-finalist); ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 24, 1928 p. C3 (doubles quarter-finalist); June 22, 1930 p. C3 (singles semi-finalist). These events were held at the athletic club's [[wikt:home away from home|home away from home]], on [[Travers Island, New York|Travers Island]] (now a peninsula) along the [[Long Island Sound|L. I. Sound]].</ref> 1924-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1925-Lake George & West Side Tennis Club (for veterans).<ref>''The New York Times'', May 20, 1925 p. 19 (at Forest Hills); June 3, 1925 p. 21. Heading: \"Martin and Bassford Win.\" Subheading: \"Beat Anderson and Hartmann in 'Over 39ers' Tennis Final.\"</ref> 1931-Lake George. MIXED DOUBLES: 1920-New York TC (for married couples).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1919 p. 396 (husbands & wives quarter-finalist); ''The Sun and New York Herald'', June 25, 1920 p. 10 (singles quarter-finalist); June 29, 1920 p. 11 (husbands & wives title); ''New York Herald'', June 25, 1922 sec. 4 p. 4 (doubles quarter-finalist).</ref> '''Runners-up (19).''' SINGLES: 1919-Woodmere Club (L.I., N.Y.).<ref>''The Sun'', Sept. 8, 1919 p. 16 (singles runner-up). ''New York Tribune'', July 17, 1920 p. 9 (singles semi-finalist); July 15, 1921 p. 11 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1922-Essex County (N.J.) CC<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Feb. 15, 1922 p. 631 (doubles semi-finalist); ''New York Tribune'', Oct. 13, 1922 p. 15 (singles runner-up); Oct. 15, 1922 pt. 1 p. 21 (doubles & mixed doubles quarter-finalists).</ref> & Powelton Club (Newburgh, N.Y.).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', edited by Merrihew, Nov. 15, 1922 p. 491 (singles runner-up & doubles semi-finalist). The Mrs. reached the singles semis.</ref> 1923-Amackassin Club (Yonkers)<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', June 3, 1923 p. 4D & ''The New York Times'', June 3, 1923 p. 4S (singles runner-up); ''The Yonkers Statesman and News'', May 29, 1924 p. 8 (singles quarter-finalist). These events were for the Eastern New York State Championship. It was hosted by Amackassin from 1920-24.</ref> & Harlem (Manhattan) TC.<ref>''New York Tribune'', May 16, 1920 pt. 1 p. 21 (singles & doubles quarter-finalists); ''The Evening Telegram'', May 20, 1923 p. 10. Excerpt on Martin: \"The University Heights veteran.\" This corrects misinformation given in a competing paper on 5/20. ''The New York Times'', May 21, 1923 p. 19 (singles runner-up).</ref> 1924-Oritani Field Club (Hackensack, N.J.)<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1924 p. 476; ''Long Island News'', July 24, 1924 p. 1. It ran from July 5-20. Final: Kynaston over PM 8-6, 6-4, 0-6, 6-2.</ref> & Stamford (Conn.) Yacht Club.<ref>''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', Aug. 3, 1924 p. D3 (\"Martin Beats Japanese Star\") & Aug. 18, 1924 p. 2A (singles runner-up); ''The New York Times'', Aug. 2, 1925 p. S5 (singles semi-finalist).</ref> 1925-Lake George & Lake Mohonk. 1930-Lake George. DOUBLES: 1921-Greenwich (Conn.) CC<ref>''The New York Times'', Oct. 17, 1921 p. 12 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up).</ref> & Milford (Pa.) Field Club. 1925-Lake Mohonk. 1926-South Yonkers TC.<ref>''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2 (doubles runner-up). Final: Franklin & Warren Osgood vs. Martin\u2013C. R. Watkins. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Aug. 8, 1929 p. 13 (singles quarter-finalist); Aug. 8, 1930 p. 16 (singles quarter-finalist).</ref> 1930-Lake George. 1931-Lake Mohonk.<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 1, 1923 p. 404 (singles quarter-finalist & mixed doubles semi-finalist); Aug. 15, 1924 p. 370 (mixed doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 29, 1924 p. 12 (singles & doubles titles); ''The New York Times'', July 18, 1925 p. 11 (singles & doubles runners-up); ''Long Island News'', July 18, 1929 p. 1 (doubles semi-finalist); ''The Kingston Daily Freeman'', July 13, 1931 p. 12 & ''American Lawn Tennis'', 1931 p. 48 (doubles runner-up).</ref> MIXED DOUBLES: 1921-Milford (Pa.).<ref>''The Evening Gazette'' (Port Jervis, N.Y.), Aug. 26, 1921 p. 8 (mixed doubles runner-up); ''American Lawn Tennis'', Oct. 15, 1921 p. 463 (singles semi-finalist & doubles runner-up). It ran from Aug. 16-20. His mixed doubles partner was not Lauretta. A rarity due to a scheduling conflict. She had a first-round singles match, at the Nationals on Aug. 15. ''The New York Times'', June 29, 1924 sec. 1 p. 27. Another rare instance. He paired here with a close acquaintance in Helen Simpson.</ref> 1925-Lake George (with Lauretta). 1930-Lake George (with Lauretta).<ref>''American Lawn Tennis'', Sept. 15, 1924 p. 536 (singles & doubles titles); ''Lake George Mirror'', Aug. 16, 1924 p. 9 (singles & doubles titles); Aug. 15, 1925 p. 7 (doubles title, singles & mixed doubles runners-up); July 12, 1930 p. 3 (singles, doubles & mixed doubles runners-up); ''Citizen Sentinel'', July 16, 1931 p. 12 (singles quarter-finalist); ''The New York Times'', July 19, 1931 sec. 10 p. 7 (doubles title); ''The Yonkers Statesman'', July 20, 1931 p. 14. Heading: \"Bassford, Martin Win Doubles Title.\" The Mrs. was a finalist in consolation singles.</ref> '''Misc.''' He also won many tournaments, which were open only to members of the County Tennis Club in [[Hartsdale, New York|Hartsdale]].<ref>''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', Oct. 5, 1928 p. 5 (reached the singles semi-finals, with no further results printed); Oct. 18, 1929 p. 22 (singles title); July 17, 1931 p. 1 (mixed doubles title); Oct. 16, 1931 p. 1 (singles runner-up & second straight doubles title); Aug. 26, 1932 p. 1. Excerpt: \"He was a ranking high player of the CC, having won the doubles championship there for several years with various partners, and always appeared in the finals.\" The results of club tourneys usually went unreported. Hence, most of them are lost to history.</ref>\n{{Quote box|width=128px|align=left|quote=<center>[[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] singles<br>1920 (1R)<br>[[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]] (2R)<br>1924 (2R)</center>}}\n'''[[Grand Slam (tennis)|Grand Slams]] (majors).''' This list is based solely on appearances. He lasted until the stated rounds. National Singles (3): 1920-1R. [[1921 U.S. National Championships \u2013 Men's Singles|1921]]-2R. 1924-2R.<ref name=\"nationals\"/> [Lauretta: 1921-1R.]<ref name=\"nets\"/> National Veterans' Singles for ages 45+ (4): 1928-4R. 1929-4R. 1930-3R. 1931-3R.<ref name=\"veterans\"/> It was renamed the [[US Open (tennis)|US Open]] in 1968.\n\n'''[[University Heights, Bronx|University Heights]] TC.''' A longtime committee and playing member, who lived in the immediate area. He competed in their annual North Side tournaments between 1913 & 1929 (consecutively 1915\u201325). These open events typically drew a large entry. Singles (12): 1915-5R. 1916-3R. 1917-2R. 1918-4R. 1919-5R. 1920-3R. 1922-3R. 1923-4R. 1924-SF. 1925-3R. 1928-SF. 1929-2R.<ref>''New York Tribune'', July 6, 1915 p. 15; July 2, 1917 p. 11; July 4, 1918 p. 12; July 3, 1919 p. 10; July 6, 1920 p. 12; May 23, 1922 p. 13; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post''; April 5, 1922 p. 15 (cmte.); April 25, 1924 (cmte.); April 22, 1926 p. 15 (cmte.); June 9, 1928 p. 16; ''The New York Times'', April 18, 1923 p. 19 (cmte.); May 9, 1923 p. 16; May 13, 1925 p. 19; ''Brooklyn Daily Eagle'', May 11, 1924 p. 2D; Sept. 25, 1929 p. 28. SF = semifinals.</ref> Doubles (6): 1913-SF. 1915-3R. 1916-3R. 1919-1R. 1920-3R. 1921-1R. 1922-discontinued.<ref>''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9; ''New York Tribune'', July 12, 1915 p. 13; July 2, 1919 p. 12; May 3, 1920 p. 11; May 2, 1921 p. 11; ''The Sun and New York Press'', July 5, 1916 p. 13; ''New York Evening Post'', April 5, 1922 p. 15 (D/C). He nearly reached the trophy round in 1913. Lost in semis 3-6, 7-5, 2-6.</ref> Mixed Doubles: 1923-1R.<ref>''The New York Times'', June 23, 1923 p. 7. This division replaced regular doubles, which was no longer on the agenda.</ref>\n\n'''Memberships.''' These spans were compiled from annuals and newspaper accounts. Maplewood (N.J.) FC 1909-12.<ref name=\"competing\"/> University Heights (Bronx) TC 1913-26.<ref>The Martins moved to the Bronx, after their marriage on Sept. 27, 1912. ''The Sun'', Aug. 7, 1913 p. 9. He first entered a University Heights tourney in 1913. ''New York Tribune'', June 5, 1916 p. 14; ''The New York Times'', Sept. 21, 1925 p. 24. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print. ''New York Evening Post'', April 22, 1926 p. 15. Non-playing committee member.</ref><ref>He could have joined the club btw. Oct. & Dec. 1912. It can't be verified, since the tennis season was nearly over by then.</ref> County (Hartsdale) TC 1926-32.<ref>He joined the County TC of Hartsdale / in Scarsdale, sometime after moving to Millwood in Aug. 1925. ''The Yonkers Statesman'', Sept. 20, 1926 p. S2; ''The Scarsdale Inquirer'', June 29, 1928 p. 8; June 26, 1931 p. 2. His association with their club is mentioned many times in print.</ref>\n\n'''Featured Match.''' Eastern New York State Championship of 1925. A first-hand account by ''New York Times'' sportswriter, [[Allison Danzig]]. Excerpts: \"This afternoon [[Bill Tilden|[Bill] Tilden]] and Strachan advanced from the semi-finals of the doubles, by putting out Alfred D. Hammett and Paul Martin at 6-4, 5-7, 6-1, 6-3. ... It required some of the best tennis that Tilden has played here all week, before the Philadelphians were able to overcome the New York pair. Hammett and Martin were always contenders, except in the third set when they slumped badly; and in order to hold them off, Tilden constantly found it necessary to invade his partner's territory and play the opposing pair single-handed. ... There was nothing to choose between the two teams in the first and second sets. In the third set, Hammett and Martin went to pieces as Tilden became rampant and raked their court with placement drives and volleys. After the Phlladelphians had gained a commanding lead [in that one], the New York pair allowed the set to go without making much effort, preferring to save their strength for the next chapter. But after the rest period, Tilden returned to the courts to play perhaps his best tennis of the match. Both Martin and Hammett fought with everything they had and their team work was splendidly coordinated, but all counted for nought against the individual brilliance of Tilden\" [then ranked [[World number 1 ranked male tennis players|World No. 1]]].<ref name=\"Tilden\"/><ref>''The New York Times'', Sept. 30, 1921 p. 12. Hammett and Martin were clubmates at University Heights. ''Big Bill Tilden'' by Deford, 1976 p. 221. Donald Strachan was one of Tilden's Philadelphia prot\u00e9g\u00e9s.</ref>\n\n==Magazine cover illustrator==\nMost of them are artist signed. The rest are imprinted with the words \"Cover by Paul Martin.\" His signature remained fairly consistent; with a curvature P & M, slanted crossing of the T, and underline mark. Also with the placement of given name above surname.\n[[File:People's Home Journal, May 1928.jpg|left|thumb|115px|(Runner slides home) ''PHJ'', 5-1928]]\n[[File:Collier's2-2-1924.jpg|thumb|117px| \"Business Men's Lunch\": cream pie, chocolate cake, rice pudding and an ice cream sundae. ''Collier's'' 2-2-1924]]\nHis artwork featured on ''Foreign Service'' was initially sold to ''Parents'' in 1930. It went unused and so was dealt to [[American Lithographic Co. v. Werkmeister|American Lithographic]]. They then sold it to the Veterans of Foreign Wars for their publication, in early 1932.<ref>[https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Foreign_Service_Poster_Letter.jpg Ownership]. A letter from Barney Yanofsky to Mrs. Martin.</ref> Martin's artwork featured on ''Die Hausfrau'' (published in Wisconsin) of a boy with five pups ''(pictured above)'', was initially used by the Gerlach Barklow Calendar Company. ''Farm & Fireside'''s  name changed to ''Country Home'' in February 1930.\n\n''Parents''' 25th anniversary issue came out in October 1951. Its unique cover featured twenty-five of their former covers, reproduced in miniature form (one for each year from 1926-50). Three of Martin's made it onto this [[wikt:silver jubilee|silver jubilee]] edition. Their issued dates were Oct. 1928, Aug. 1929 and Oct. 1930. He therefore, [[wikt:in a way|in a way]], won their coveted [[Person of the Year|\"Cover of the Year\"]] award for 1928, 29 & 30.\n\nThe following list contains thirty-seven known credits, from consumer (not trade) magazines. It includes three from September 1925.\n\n\u25cf '''''[[Girl Scouts of the USA#The American Girl|The American Girl]]''''' (1917\u20131979): 10-1931.<ref>It was called ''The Rally'' from 1917-20. This image later appeared on the cover of Girl Scout Equipment catalogs, for Fall 1932 and Spring 1933.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Collier's]]''''' (1888\u2013Jan.1957): 5-26-1923, 2-2-1924 ''(pictured right)'', 6-28-1924,<ref name=\"flute\"/> 10-25-1924 ''(pictured above)'', 11-22-1924, 12-27-1924, 5-2-1925, 5-30-1925, 6-27-1925 ''(self-portrait)'',<ref name=\"races\"/> 7-4-1925, 7-25-1925, 9-19-1925,<ref name=\"school\"/> 10-31-1925,<ref>Joe Winkworth paraphrases [[Babe Ruth]] on p. 15. [[wikiquote:Babe Ruth#Quotes|Excerpts]].</ref> 1-16-1926, 2-13-1926, 5-22-1926, 12-25-1926, 2-26-1927, 8-13-1927, 8-27-1927.<ref name=\"slide\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Everybody's Magazine|Everybody's]]''''' (1899\u20131929): 9-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t2970.htm#A63781 \"Everybody's\"]. The FictionMags Index. A young swimmer and his rascally dog, Sept. 1925. Alternative path: scroll up, and then click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist\">search by name.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Farm & Fireside|Farm & Fireside / Country Home]]''''' (1878\u20131939): 11-1923, 8-1930.<br />\n\u25cf '''''[[The Farmer's Wife (women's magazine)|The Farmer's Wife]]''''' (1897\u20131970): 1-1931.<ref>It was known as ''Farm Journal and Farmer's Wife'' (upon their merger), from May 1939 to July 1945. It was then retitled ''Farm Journal'', with a back section titled Farmer's Wife.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[VFW magazine|Foreign Service]]''''' (1914\u2013To Date): 5-1932.<ref>Memorial Day cover. A poster version is shown in ''Boys' Life'', May 1932 p. 52; May 1933 p. 30; May 1934 p. 44. The mag was renamed ''VFW'' (Veterans of Foreign Wars) in 1951.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Das Fenster|Die Hausfrau]]''''' (1904\u2013To Date): 4-1936.<ref>[https://archive.org/details/DieHausfrau193604 \"Die Hausfrau\" (The Housewife)]. Internet Archive, San Francisco. The mag had three titles: ''Die Deutsche Hausfrau'' 1904-18. ''Die Hausfrau'' 1919-92. ''Das Fenster'' 1992\u2013. This cover image originally appeared on calendars, ink blotter cards and prints in 1931.</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Liberty (general interest magazine)|Liberty]]''''' (1924\u20131950): 9-12-1925.<ref>[http://www.philsp.com/homeville/FMI/t/t4083.htm#A88949 \"Liberty\"]. The FictionMags Index. A doll carriage & wagon collide, Sept. 12, 1925. The girl's dark locks were added on. (ALT: scroll up>click \"table-of-contents\">\"artist.\")</ref><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[Parents (magazine)|Parents]]''''' (Oct.1926\u2013To Date): 10-1928,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Magazine for Parents'' from Oct. 1926 to Jan. 1929.</ref> 2-1929, 5-1929,<ref>It was called ''Children, the Parents' Magazine'' from February to July 1929.</ref> 8-1929, 10-1929, 2-1930, 10-1930.<ref name=\"reading\"/><br />\n\u25cf '''''[[People's Home Journal]]''''' (1885\u20131929): 5-1928 ''(pictured)'', 11-1928.\n\n==Book illustrator==\n[[File:BaseballDetective.jpg|left|thumb|69px|''The Baseball Detective'', 1928]]\nHis artistic contributions to [[short story|short stories]], include the following: 1. ''[[The Saturday Evening Post|Saturday Evening Post]]''. ''Short Turns and Encore'' by various writers, July 29, 1922 p.&nbsp;16.<ref>''Short Turns and Encore''. A boy and girl listening to a Civil War veteran, who's reminiscing about General Sherman. (Viewable online at books.google.com.)</ref> 2. ''[[Collier's]]''. ''The Blanket'' by [[Floyd Dell]], October 16, 1926 p.&nbsp;18.<ref>''The Blanket''. Trio of son (with scissors), dad and granddad.</ref> 3. ''Collier's''. ''The Unfairway'' by Burford Lorimer, December 25, 1926 pp.&nbsp;22-23.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Colliers-1926dec25-00022 \"The Unfairway\"]. Unz.com. A man, woman and caddie, p. 22. A father and son reading the headline news, p. 23.</ref> 4. ''[[Scribner's Magazine]]''. ''Tragedy'' by Eve Bernstein, April 1928 p.&nbsp;479.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928apr-00477 \"Tragedy\"]. Unz.com. \"The Unz Review.\" A school teacher consoling her grieving student.</ref> 5. ''Scribner's Magazine''. ''On the Dark Trail'' by Franklin Holt, July 1928 p.&nbsp;71.<ref>[https://www.unz.com/print/Scribners-1928jul-00061 \"On the Dark Trail\"]. Unz.com. Young Henry holding a flashlight and hatchet.</ref>\n\nThe first six listed below, are fictional or semi-fictional books for boys and or girls.\n\n\u25cf ''Philus, the Stable Boy of Bethlehem; and Other Children's Story-Sermons for Christmas ... ''. Edmund J. Cleveland, with foreword by the [[The Right Reverend|Rt. Rev.]]  [[Charles Lewis Slattery|Charles L. Slattery]], Sept. 1927. (Credits: [[dust jacket]], [[book frontispiece|frontispiece]] and facing pp.&nbsp;52, 66, 124.)<ref>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11810/pg11810.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1954 (listed under the author). ''[[The Herald News|Herald News]]'' (Fall River, Mass.), Oct. 22, 1927. The following words are atop a Martin illustration: \"Local Clergyman Writes Book.\"</ref> It includes eleven short stories covering the church year. The opener is about a stable boy, who was present at the [[Nativity of Jesus|Nativity]]. These are [[wikt:pseudonarrative|pseudo-narratives]] with a moral message.<br />\n\u25cf ''Puck Chasers Incorporated''. Charles G. Muller, Sept. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and inside pages.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=%22Puck%20chasers%2C%20incorporated%22&f=false#v=snippet&q=%22Muller%2C%20Charles%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927. The book's illustrator was not recorded.</ref> This is one of the earliest books with an [[ice hockey]] theme. Its predecessors tended to be on a combination of [[winter sports]], instead of solely on ice hockey.<br />\n\u25cf ''Araminta''. Helen Cady Forbes, Nov. 1927. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;134, 212.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=naMhAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1558&lpg=PA1558&dq=Araminta.+Helen+Cady#v=onepage&q=Araminta&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1927.</ref> Araminta turns eleven years old and finds a kidnapped baby.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Prince and the Pig's Gate, and Other Sermons in Story''. Robert Hugh Morris, May 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;48, 134, 166.)<ref name=gut>[https://www.gutenberg.org/cache/epub/11812/pg11812.txt \"Project Gutenberg\"]. U.S. \u00a9 Renewals, Jul.-Dec. 1955 (listed under the author).</ref><br />\n\u25cf ''The Baseball Detective''. Charles G. Muller, Aug. 1928. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and facing pp.&nbsp;22, 132, 250-''pictured''.)<ref name=gut/> It's a story of [[baseball]], competition, friendship and intrigue at the Fisk School for Boys.<br />\n\u25cf ''Chad of Knob Hill: The Tale of a Lone Scout''. [[Howard R. Garis]], Sept. 1929. Republished in 2013. (Credits: dust jacket, frontispiece and pp.&nbsp;14, 60, 85, 97, 163, 187, 213, 281.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=jJ8hAQAAIAAJ&pg=PA1645&lpg=PA1645&dq=Paul+Martin#v=onepage&q=Paul%20Martin&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1929.</ref> This book has a [[Scouts BSA|Boy Scouting]] theme. Garis created stories about [[Uncle Wiggily]], a gentlemanly [[wikt:rheumatism|rheumatism]]-stricken rabbit.<br />\n\u25cf ''Stories of To-day and Yesterday; Thirty Selected Short Stories, Nine Imitative Stories by Students ... ''. [[Frederick Houk Law|Frederick H. Law]], editor, Feb. 1930. (Credit: frontispiece.)<ref>[https://books.google.com/books?id=CKUhAQAAIAAJ&q=Frederick+H.+Law#v=snippet&q=%22edited%20by%20frederick%20Houk%20Law%22&f=false Google Books]. LOC, Copyright Office, Catalog of Copyright Entries for 1930.</ref> An instructional guide on how to appreciate and write short stories.<br />\n\u25cf ''The Bookshelf for Boys and Girls''. [[Clara Whitehill Hunt]], lead editor, 1930\u201331 and 1931\u201332 editions. (Credits: dust jackets.)<ref>Published annually by [[R.R. Bowker|R.R. Bowker Co.]], 45th St., NYC. They sold the dust jackets in bulk to bookstores. Bowker's would also imprint on them, the retailer's business name and address. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._1.jpg Readers #1]. [https://commons.wikimedia.org/wiki/File:Bookshelf-Dust_Jacket_no._2.jpg Readers #2]. [[Wikimedia Commons|Commons]].</ref> The best books for children are carefully selected. Catalog format with descriptive notes. An authoritative guide for parents.\n\n==References and notes==\nContinuity Guidelines. Notes come after the sources. They are directly related or give additional details. This pattern can be harder to follow, when the same source is cited more than once. Keywords are sometimes placed after the page number, in parenthesis.\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Paul_Martin_(illustrator)|Paul Martin (illustrator)|position=left}}\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Martin (illustrator), Paul}}\n[[Category:1883 births]]\n[[Category:1932 deaths]]\n[[Category:American illustrators]]\n[[Category:Artists from New York City]]\n[[Category:National Academy of Design alumni]]\n[[Category:New York Tribune personnel]]\n[[Category:Tennis people from New York (state)]]\n[[Category:American male tennis players]]\n", "name_user": "JimPercy", "label": "safe", "comment": "changed position of a reference", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Paul_Martin_(illustrator)"}
{"title_page": "William Golding", "text_new": "{{other people}}\n{{Distinguish|text=[[William Goldman]], the American novelist, playwright, and screenwriter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = William Golding\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]]\n| honorific_suffix = [[CBE]]\n| image        = William Golding 1983.jpg\n| caption      = Golding in 1983\n| birth_name   = William Geralld Golding\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1911|9|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Newquay]], [[Cornwall]],<br />England\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1993|6|19|1911|9|19|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Perranarworthal]], Cornwall, England\n| occupation   = Schoolteacher \u2022 Novelist \u2022 Playwright \u2022 Poet\n| period       = \n| alma_mater   = [[Oxford University]]\n| genre        = [[Survivalism in fiction|Survivalist fiction]] \u2022 [[Robinsonade]] \u2022 Adventure \u2022 [[Nautical fiction|Sea story]] \u2022 Science fiction \u2022 [[Essay]] \u2022 [[Historical fiction]] \u2022 Stageplay \u2022 Poetry\n| notableworks = ''[[Lord of the Flies]]'', ''[[Rites of Passage (novel)|Rites of Passage]]''\n| awards       = 1983 [[Nobel Prize in Literature]]<br />1980 [[Booker Prize]]\n| signature    = William_Golding_signature.jpg\n}}\n'''Sir William Gerald Golding''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (19 September 1911 \u2013 19 June 1993) was a British novelist, playwright, and poet. Best known for his debut novel ''[[Lord of the Flies]]'' (1954), he would go on to publish another eleven novels in his lifetime. In 1980, he was awarded the [[Booker Prize]] for ''[[Rites of Passage (novel)|Rites of Passage]]'',  the first novel in what became his sea trilogy, ''[[To the Ends of the Earth]]''. He was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] in 1983.\n\nAs a result of his contributions to literature, Golding was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1988.<ref name=\"awards\">[http://www.william-golding.co.uk/life/awards.aspx William Golding: Awards]. William Golding.co.uk. Retrieved 17 June 2012</ref><ref name=\"Lambert\"/> He was a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref name=\"awards\"/> In 2008, ''[[The Times]]'' ranked Golding third on their list of \"The 50 greatest [[British literature|British writers]] since 1945\".<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article3127837.ece The 50 greatest British writers since 1945]. ''The Times'' (5 January 2008). Retrieved on 1 February 2010.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\n[[File:William Golding's Plaque at Bishop Wordsworth's School.jpg|thumb|Plaque at [[Bishop Wordsworth's School]], [[Salisbury]].]]\nWilliam Golding was born in his maternal grandmother's house, 47 Mount Wise, [[Newquay]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Reference&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=true&displayGroups=&sortBy=&source=&search_within_results=&action=e&catId=GALE%7CNUIWHS509465048&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1631002582 |title=General Logon Page |publisher=Ic.galegroup.com |date= |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> [[Cornwall]].<ref name=ODNB>Kevin McCarron, \u2018Golding, Sir William Gerald (1911\u20131993)\u2019, [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], [[Oxford University Press]], September 2004; online edn, May 2006 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/52079  accessed 13 November 2007]</ref> The house was known as ''Karenza'', the [[Cornish language]] word for ''love'', and he spent many childhood holidays there.<ref>Carey, Childhood.</ref> He grew up in [[Marlborough, Wiltshire]], where his father (Alec Golding) was a science master at [[Marlborough Grammar School]] (1905 to retirement), the school the young Golding and his elder brother Joseph attended.<ref>(Which should not be confused with [[Marlborough College]], the nearby \"public\" boarding school).</ref>  His mother, Mildred (Curnoe),<ref>Raychel Haugrud Reiff, William Golding: Lord of the Flies, Marshall Cavendish, 2009</ref> kept house at 29, The Green, Marlborough, and was a campaigner for female suffrage. Golding's mother, who was [[Cornish people|Cornish]] and whom he considered \"a superstitious [[Celts|celt]]\", used to tell him old [[Cornish mythology|Cornish fairy tales]] from her own childhood.<ref>Carey, The House.</ref> When he was a teenager he attempted to rape a 15 year old girl.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/aug/16/william-golding-attempted-rape|title=Author William Golding tried to rape teenager, private papers show|last=Wainwright|first=Martin|date=2009-08-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 1930 Golding went to [[Brasenose College, Oxford]], where he read [[Natural Sciences]] for two years before transferring to [[English Literature]].<ref>Carey, pp. 41, 49</ref> His original [[Tutorial system|tutor]] was the chemist [[Thomas Taylor (chemist)|Thomas Taylor]].<ref>Carey, p. 15</ref>\n\nGolding took his B.A. degree with Second Class Honours in the summer of 1934, and later that year a book of his ''[[Poems (poetry by Golding)|Poems]]'' was published by [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan & Co]], with the help of his Oxford friend, the [[anthroposophy|anthroposophist]] Adam Bittleston.\n\nHe was a schoolmaster teaching English and music at [[Maidstone Grammar School]] 1938 - 1940 and then teaching [[Philosophy]] and English in 1939, then just English from 1945 to 1962 at [[Bishop Wordsworth's School]], [[Salisbury]], Wiltshire.\n\n[[John Carey (critic)|John Carey]], the emeritus professor of English literature at Oxford university, was given access to a personal journal kept by Golding in order to write his biography, in which Golding describes trying to set up his students against each other during his teaching years, which gave him inspiration for his first novel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/aug/16/william-golding-attempted-rape|title=Author William Golding tried to rape teenager, private papers show|last=Wainwright|first=Martin|date=2009-08-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Marriage and family===\nGolding married Ann Brookfield, an analytical chemist,<ref name=\"bloom\">{{cite book |title=William Golding's Lord of the Flies; Bloom's modern critical interpretations |pages=161\u2013165 |author=Harold Bloom |isbn=978-0-7910-9826-4 |year=2008 |publisher=Infobase Publishing}}</ref>{{Rp|page=161}} on 30 September 1939. They had two children, David (born 1940) and Judith (born July, 1945).<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\n===War service===\nDuring [[World War II]], Golding joined the [[Royal Navy]] in 1940.<ref>Raychel Haugrud Reiff, ''William Golding: Lord of the Flies'', page 58 (Marshall Cavendish, 2010). {{ISBN|978-0-7614-4276-9}}</ref> He served in a destroyer which was briefly involved in the pursuit and sinking of the German battleship [[German battleship Bismarck|''Bismarck'']]. He also participated in the invasion of [[Normandy]] on [[D-Day]], commanding a [[Landing Craft Tank (Rocket)|landing ship]] that fired salvoes of [[RP-3#Shore bombardment|rockets]] onto the beaches, and was in action at [[Walcheren]] in which 23 out of 24 assault craft were sunk.<ref>{{cite book| last=Mortimer| first=John| authorlink=John Mortimer| title=Character Parts| location=London| publisher=Penguin| year=1986| isbn=0-14-008959-4| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/characterparts00mort}}</ref>\n\n===Religious beliefs===\nWhile his father had been an insistent atheist, Golding himself was a Christian, though a member of no established Church.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/7826371/Sir-William-Golding.html |title = Sir William Golding|date = 21 June 1993}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nIn 1985, Golding and his wife moved to [[Tullimaar House]] at [[Perranarworthal]], near [[Truro]], Cornwall. He died of heart failure eight years later on 19 June 1993. His body was buried in the parish churchyard of [[Bowerchalke]], Wiltshire (near the Hampshire and Dorset county border).\n\nOn his death he left the draft of a novel, ''[[The Double Tongue]]'', set in [[Delphi|ancient Delphi]], which was published posthumously in 1995.<ref name=\"Lambert\">{{cite news| author=Bruce Lambert| title=William Golding Is Dead at 81; The Author of 'Lord of the Flies'| url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0919.html| work=The New York Times| date=20 June 1993| accessdate=6 September 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Golding | first=William | title=The Double Tongue| location=London| publisher=Faber | year=1996| isbn=978-0-571-17803-2| title-link=The Double Tongue }}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n\n===Writing success===\n[[File:Golding, Lundkvist och Sartre i Leningrad 1963.jpg|thumb|Golding, [[Artur Lundkvist]] and [[Jean-Paul Sartre]] at a writers' congress in [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]], [[USSR]], 1963.]]\nWhilst still a teacher at [[Bishop Wordsworth's School]] in Salisbury, Golding began writing a manuscript for a novel initially titled ''Strangers from Within'' in 1951.<ref name=\"Williams\"> Williams, Phoebe. \u201cNew BBC programme sheds light on the story behind the publication of Lord of the Flies.\u201d faber, Faber & Faber, 6/6/19, https://www.faber.co.uk/blog/new-bbc-programme-sheds-light-on-the-story-behind-the-publication-of-lord-of-the-flies/. Accessed 16/4/20. </ref> In September 1953, after rejections from seven other publishers, Golding sent a manuscript to [[Faber and Faber|Faber & Faber]] and was initially rejected by their reader, Jan Perkins, who labelled it as \"Rubbish & dull. Pointless\".<ref name=\"Sunday Feature BBC R3\"> Sunday Feature, 18:45 02/06/2019, BBC Radio 3, 45 mins. https://learningonscreen.ac.uk/ondemand/index.php/prog/13750939?bcast=129246943 (Accessed 16 Apr 2020) </ref> His book, however, was championed by Charles Monteith, a new editor at the firm. Monteith asked for some changes to the text and the novel was published in September 1954 as ''[[Lord of the Flies]]''.\n\nAfter moving in 1958 from [[Salisbury]] to nearby [[Bowerchalke]], he met his fellow villager and walking companion [[James Lovelock]]. The two discussed Lovelock's [[Gaia Hypothesis|hypothesis]], that the living matter of the planet Earth functions like a single organism, and Golding suggested naming this hypothesis after [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]], the Titan of the earth in Greek mythology.<ref name=\"ecolo.org\">James Lovelock, \u2018What is Gaia?\u2019, [http://www.ecolo.org/lovelock/what_is_Gaia.html accessed 16 May 2013]</ref> His publishing success made it possible for Golding to resign his teaching post at Bishop Wordsworth's School in 1961, and he spent that academic year in the United States as writer-in-residence at [[Hollins University|Hollins College]], near [[Roanoke, Virginia]].\n\nGolding won the [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]] for ''[[Darkness Visible (Golding)|Darkness Visible]]'' in 1979, and the [[Man Booker Prize|Booker Prize]] for ''[[Rites of Passage (novel)|Rites of Passage]]'' in 1980. In 1983 he was awarded the [[Nobel Prize for Literature]], and was according to the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' \"an unexpected and even contentious choice\".<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nIn 1988 Golding was appointed a [[Knight Bachelor]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=51558 |date=13 December 1988 |page=13986 }}</ref> In September 1993, only a few months after his sudden death, the First International William Golding Conference was held in France, where Golding's presence had been promised and was eagerly expected.<ref>F. Regard (ed.), F''ingering Netsukes: Selected Papers from the First International William Golding Conference'', Saint-Etienne, PUSE, 1995.</ref>\n\nDespite his success, Golding \"was abnormally thin-skinned when it came to criticism of his work. He simply could not read even the mildest reservation and on occasion left the country when his books were published.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/18/books/review/Boyd-t.html \"Man as an Island\"].\n ''The New York Times''.</ref>\n\n===Fiction===\nHis first novel, ''[[Lord of the Flies]]'' (1954; film, 1963 and 1990; play, adapted by [[Nigel Williams (author)|Nigel Williams]], 1995), describes a group of boys stranded on a tropical island reverting to savagery. ''[[The Inheritors (William Golding)|The Inheritors]]'' (1955) shows \"new people\" (generally identified with ''[[Homo sapiens sapiens]]''), triumphing over a gentler race (generally identified with [[Neanderthals]]) by deceit and violence. His 1956 novel ''[[Pincher Martin]]'' records the thoughts of a drowning sailor. ''[[Free Fall (Golding novel)|Free Fall]]'' (1959) explores the issue of free choice as a prisoner held in solitary confinement in a German POW camp during World War Two looks back over his life. ''[[The Spire]]'' (1964) follows the building (and near collapse) of a huge spire onto a medieval cathedral (generally assumed to be [[Salisbury Cathedral]]); the spire symbolizing both spiritual aspiration and worldly vanity.\n\nIn his 1967 novel ''[[The Pyramid (Golding)|The Pyramid]]'' three separate stories in a shared setting (a small English town in the 1920s) are linked by a narrator, and ''The Scorpion God'' (1971) consists of three novellas, the first set in a prehistoric African hunter-gatherer band ('Clonk, Clonk'), the second in an ancient Egyptian court ('The Scorpion God') and the third in the court of a Roman emperor ('Envoy Extraordinary'). The last of these reworks his 1958 play ''The Brass Butterfly''. His later novels include ''[[Darkness Visible (Golding)|Darkness Visible]]'' (1979), which is about a terrorist group, a paedophile teacher, and a mysterious angel-like figure who survives a fire in [[the Blitz]], ''[[The Paper Men]]'' (1984) which is about the conflict between a writer and his biographer, and a sea trilogy ''[[To the Ends of the Earth]]'', which includes ''Rites of Passage'' (1980), ''Close Quarters'' (1987), and ''Fire Down Below'' (1989), the first book of which (originally intended as a stand-alone novel) won the [[Booker Prize]].\n\n==List of works==\n\n===Poetry===\n*''[[Poems (poetry by Golding)|Poems]]'' (1934)\n\n===Drama===\n*''The Brass Butterfly''  (1958)\n\n===Novels===\n*''[[Lord of the Flies]]'' (1954) \n*''[[The Inheritors (William Golding)|The Inheritors]]'' (1955)\n*''[[Pincher Martin]]'' (1956)\n*''[[Free Fall (Golding)|Free Fall]]'' (1959)\n*''[[The Spire]]'' (1964)\n*''[[The Pyramid (Golding)|The Pyramid]]'' (1967)\n*''The Scorpion God''   (1971)\n*''[[Darkness Visible (Golding)|Darkness Visible]]'' (1979)\n*''[[The Paper Men]] (1984)\n*''[[To the Ends of the Earth]]'' (trilogy)\n**''[[Rites of Passage (novel)|Rites of Passage]]'' (1980)\n**''[[Close Quarters (Golding)|Close Quarters]]'' (1987)\n**''[[Fire Down Below (novel)|Fire Down Below]]'' (1989)\n*''[[The Double Tongue]]'' (posthumous publication 1995)<ref>''The Double Tongue'' 1996 Faber reprint {{ISBN|978-0-571-17720-2}}</ref>\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''[[The Hot Gates]]''  (1965)\n*''[[A Moving Target]]''  (1982)\n*''An Egyptian Journal'' (1985)\n\n===Unpublished works===\n*''Seahorse'' was written in 1948. It is a biographical account of sailing on the south coast of England whilst in training for [[D-Day]].<ref>Carey, p. 130</ref>\n*''Circle Under the Sea'' is an adventure novel about a writer who sails to discover archaeological treasures off the coast of the [[Scilly Isles]].<ref>Carey, p. 137</ref>\n*''Short Measure'' is a novel set in a British boarding school.<ref>Carey, p. 142</ref>\n\n== Audiobooks ==\n* 2005: ''Lord of the Flies'' (read by the author), Listening Library, {{ISBN|978-0307281708}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |title=William Golding: The Man Who Wrote Lord of the Flies |last=Carey |first=John |authorlink=John Carey (critic) |year=2009 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=New York |isbn=978-1-4391-8732-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/williamgoldingma0000unse_j6u3 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* L. L. Dickson, ''The Modern Allegories of William Golding'' (University of South Florida Press, 1990). {{ISBN|0-8130-0971-5}}.\n* R. A. Gekoski and P. A. Grogan, ''William Golding: A Bibliography'', London, Andr\u00e9 Deutsch, 1994. {{ISBN|978-0-233-98611-1}}.\n* \"Boys Armed with Sticks: William Golding's Lord of the Flies\". Chapter in B. Schoene-Harwood. ''Writing Men''. Edinburgh University Press, 2000.\n* Ladenthin, Volker: Golding, Herr der Fliegen; Verne, 2 Jahre Ferien; Schl\u00fcter, Level 4 - Stadt der Kinder. In: engagement (1998) H. 4  S. 271-274.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/writers/12203.shtml BBC television interview from 1959]\n*[https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/literature/1983/golding/biographical/ Biography of William Golding] at the [[Nobel Prize]] website\n* [http://aurora.icaap.org/index.php/aurora/article/view/50/63 Interview] by Mary Lynn Scott \u2013 Universal Pessimist, Cosmic Optimist\n* [http://www.william-golding.co.uk/ William Golding Ltd] Website of Golding family.\n* [http://books.guardian.co.uk/departments/generalfiction/story/0,,1793967,00.html ''Last Words'' An account of Golding's last evening] by [[D. M. Thomas]] \u2013 Guardian \u2013 Saturday 10 June 2006 (''Review'' Section)\n* [https://www.facebook.com/WilliamGoldingAuthor/ Official Facebook page]\n* [http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1983/golding-lecture.html Nobel Prize Lecture]\n* {{OL author}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/mar/11/william-golding-crisis \"William Golding's crisis\"]\n* {{IMDb name|0325717}}\n* [http://lib-archives.ex.ac.uk/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=EUL+MS+429 William Golding] at University of Exeter Special Collections\n\n{{William Golding}}\n{{Booker Prize}}\n{{Nobel Prize in Literature Laureates 1976-2000}}\n{{Culture of Cornwall}}\n{{Lord of the Flies}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golding, William}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Booker Prize winners]]\n[[Category:British Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:James Tait Black Memorial Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Nobel laureates in Literature]]\n[[Category:People from Marlborough, Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:People from Newquay]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Cornish writers]]\n[[Category:English historical novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers of fiction set in Prehistoric times]]\n[[Category:Writers of historical fiction set in the Middle Ages]]\n", "text_old": "{{other people}}\n{{Distinguish|text=[[William Goldman]], the American novelist, playwright, and screenwriter}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2015}}\n{{Infobox writer <!-- for more information see [[:Template:Infobox writer/doc]] -->\n| name         = William Golding\n| honorific_prefix = [[Sir]]\n| honorific_suffix = [[CBE]]\n| image        = William Golding 1983.jpg\n| caption      = Golding in 1983\n| birth_name   = William Gerald Golding\n| birth_date   = {{Birth date|1912|9|19|df=y}}\n| birth_place  = [[Newquay]], [[Cornwall]],<br />England\n| death_date   = {{death date and age|1993|6|19|1911|9|19|df=y}}\n| death_place  = [[Perranarworthal]], Cornwall, England\n| occupation   = Schoolteacher \u2022 Novelist \u2022 Playwright \u2022 Poet\n| period       = \n| alma_mater   = [[Oxford University]]\n| genre        = [[Survivalism in fiction|Survivalist fiction]] \u2022 [[Robinsonade]] \u2022 Adventure \u2022 [[Nautical fiction|Sea story]] \u2022 Science fiction \u2022 [[Essay]] \u2022 [[Historical fiction]] \u2022 Stageplay \u2022 Poetry\n| notableworks = ''[[Lord of the Flies]]'', ''[[Rites of Passage (novel)|Rites of Passage]]''\n| awards       = 1983 [[Nobel Prize in Literature]]<br />1980 [[Booker Prize]]\n| signature    = William_Golding_signature.jpg\n}}\n'''Sir William Gerald Golding''', {{post-nominals|country=GBR|size=100%|CBE}} (19 September 1911 \u2013 19 June 1993) was a British novelist, playwright, and poet. Best known for his debut novel ''[[Lord of the Flies]]'' (1954), he would go on to publish another eleven novels in his lifetime. In 1980, he was awarded the [[Booker Prize]] for ''[[Rites of Passage (novel)|Rites of Passage]]'',  the first novel in what became his sea trilogy, ''[[To the Ends of the Earth]]''. He was awarded the [[Nobel Prize in Literature]] in 1983.\n\nAs a result of his contributions to literature, Golding was [[Knight Bachelor|knighted]] in 1988.<ref name=\"awards\">[http://www.william-golding.co.uk/life/awards.aspx William Golding: Awards]. William Golding.co.uk. Retrieved 17 June 2012</ref><ref name=\"Lambert\"/> He was a fellow of the [[Royal Society of Literature]].<ref name=\"awards\"/> In 2008, ''[[The Times]]'' ranked Golding third on their list of \"The 50 greatest [[British literature|British writers]] since 1945\".<ref>[http://entertainment.timesonline.co.uk/tol/arts_and_entertainment/books/article3127837.ece The 50 greatest British writers since 1945]. ''The Times'' (5 January 2008). Retrieved on 1 February 2010.</ref>\n\n==Biography==\n\n===Early life===\n[[File:William Golding's Plaque at Bishop Wordsworth's School.jpg|thumb|Plaque at [[Bishop Wordsworth's School]], [[Salisbury]].]]\nWilliam Golding was born in his maternal grandmother's house, 47 Mount Wise, [[Newquay]],<ref>{{cite web|url=http://ic.galegroup.com/ic/bic1/ReferenceDetailsPage/ReferenceDetailsWindow?failOverType=&query=&windowstate=normal&contentModules=&mode=view&displayGroupName=Reference&limiter=&currPage=&disableHighlighting=true&displayGroups=&sortBy=&source=&search_within_results=&action=e&catId=GALE%7CNUIWHS509465048&activityType=&scanId=&documentId=GALE%7CK1631002582 |title=General Logon Page |publisher=Ic.galegroup.com |date= |accessdate=31 January 2013}}</ref> [[Cornwall]].<ref name=ODNB>Kevin McCarron, \u2018Golding, Sir William Gerald (1911\u20131993)\u2019, [[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]], [[Oxford University Press]], September 2004; online edn, May 2006 [http://www.oxforddnb.com/view/article/52079  accessed 13 November 2007]</ref> The house was known as ''Karenza'', the [[Cornish language]] word for ''love'', and he spent many childhood holidays there.<ref>Carey, Childhood.</ref> He grew up in [[Marlborough, Wiltshire]], where his father (Alec Golding) was a science master at [[Marlborough Grammar School]] (1905 to retirement), the school the young Golding and his elder brother Joseph attended.<ref>(Which should not be confused with [[Marlborough College]], the nearby \"public\" boarding school).</ref>  His mother, Mildred (Curnoe),<ref>Raychel Haugrud Reiff, William Golding: Lord of the Flies, Marshall Cavendish, 2009</ref> kept house at 29, The Green, Marlborough, and was a campaigner for female suffrage. Golding's mother, who was [[Cornish people|Cornish]] and whom he considered \"a superstitious [[Celts|celt]]\", used to tell him old [[Cornish mythology|Cornish fairy tales]] from her own childhood.<ref>Carey, The House.</ref> When he was a teenager he attempted to rape a 15 year old girl.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/aug/16/william-golding-attempted-rape|title=Author William Golding tried to rape teenager, private papers show|last=Wainwright|first=Martin|date=2009-08-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref> In 1930 Golding went to [[Brasenose College, Oxford]], where he read [[Natural Sciences]] for two years before transferring to [[English Literature]].<ref>Carey, pp. 41, 49</ref> His original [[Tutorial system|tutor]] was the chemist [[Thomas Taylor (chemist)|Thomas Taylor]].<ref>Carey, p. 15</ref>\n\nGolding took his B.A. degree with Second Class Honours in the summer of 1934, and later that year a book of his ''[[Poems (poetry by Golding)|Poems]]'' was published by [[Macmillan Publishers|Macmillan & Co]], with the help of his Oxford friend, the [[anthroposophy|anthroposophist]] Adam Bittleston.\n\nHe was a schoolmaster teaching English and music at [[Maidstone Grammar School]] 1938 - 1940 and then teaching [[Philosophy]] and English in 1939, then just English from 1945 to 1962 at [[Bishop Wordsworth's School]], [[Salisbury]], Wiltshire.\n\n[[John Carey (critic)|John Carey]], the emeritus professor of English literature at Oxford university, was given access to a personal journal kept by Golding in order to write his biography, in which Golding describes trying to set up his students against each other during his teaching years, which gave him inspiration for his first novel.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://www.theguardian.com/books/2009/aug/16/william-golding-attempted-rape|title=Author William Golding tried to rape teenager, private papers show|last=Wainwright|first=Martin|date=2009-08-16|work=The Guardian|access-date=2019-12-20|language=en-GB|issn=0261-3077}}</ref>\n\n===Marriage and family===\nGolding married Ann Brookfield, an analytical chemist,<ref name=\"bloom\">{{cite book |title=William Golding's Lord of the Flies; Bloom's modern critical interpretations |pages=161\u2013165 |author=Harold Bloom |isbn=978-0-7910-9826-4 |year=2008 |publisher=Infobase Publishing}}</ref>{{Rp|page=161}} on 30 September 1939. They had two children, David (born 1940) and Judith (born July, 1945).<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\n===War service===\nDuring [[World War II]], Golding joined the [[Royal Navy]] in 1940.<ref>Raychel Haugrud Reiff, ''William Golding: Lord of the Flies'', page 58 (Marshall Cavendish, 2010). {{ISBN|978-0-7614-4276-9}}</ref> He served in a destroyer which was briefly involved in the pursuit and sinking of the German battleship [[German battleship Bismarck|''Bismarck'']]. He also participated in the invasion of [[Normandy]] on [[D-Day]], commanding a [[Landing Craft Tank (Rocket)|landing ship]] that fired salvoes of [[RP-3#Shore bombardment|rockets]] onto the beaches, and was in action at [[Walcheren]] in which 23 out of 24 assault craft were sunk.<ref>{{cite book| last=Mortimer| first=John| authorlink=John Mortimer| title=Character Parts| location=London| publisher=Penguin| year=1986| isbn=0-14-008959-4| url-access=registration| url=https://archive.org/details/characterparts00mort}}</ref>\n\n===Religious beliefs===\nWhile his father had been an insistent atheist, Golding himself was a Christian, though a member of no established Church.<ref>{{Cite news | url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/news/obituaries/7826371/Sir-William-Golding.html |title = Sir William Golding|date = 21 June 1993}}</ref>\n\n===Death===\nIn 1985, Golding and his wife moved to [[Tullimaar House]] at [[Perranarworthal]], near [[Truro]], Cornwall. He died of heart failure eight years later on 19 June 1993. His body was buried in the parish churchyard of [[Bowerchalke]], Wiltshire (near the Hampshire and Dorset county border).\n\nOn his death he left the draft of a novel, ''[[The Double Tongue]]'', set in [[Delphi|ancient Delphi]], which was published posthumously in 1995.<ref name=\"Lambert\">{{cite news| author=Bruce Lambert| title=William Golding Is Dead at 81; The Author of 'Lord of the Flies'| url=https://www.nytimes.com/learning/general/onthisday/bday/0919.html| work=The New York Times| date=20 June 1993| accessdate=6 September 2007 }}</ref><ref>{{cite book| last=Golding | first=William | title=The Double Tongue| location=London| publisher=Faber | year=1996| isbn=978-0-571-17803-2| title-link=The Double Tongue }}</ref> \n\n==Career==\n\n===Writing success===\n[[File:Golding, Lundkvist och Sartre i Leningrad 1963.jpg|thumb|Golding, [[Artur Lundkvist]] and [[Jean-Paul Sartre]] at a writers' congress in [[Saint Petersburg|Leningrad]], [[USSR]], 1963.]]\nWhilst still a teacher at [[Bishop Wordsworth's School]] in Salisbury, Golding began writing a manuscript for a novel initially titled ''Strangers from Within'' in 1951.<ref name=\"Williams\"> Williams, Phoebe. \u201cNew BBC programme sheds light on the story behind the publication of Lord of the Flies.\u201d faber, Faber & Faber, 6/6/19, https://www.faber.co.uk/blog/new-bbc-programme-sheds-light-on-the-story-behind-the-publication-of-lord-of-the-flies/. Accessed 16/4/20. </ref> In September 1953, after rejections from seven other publishers, Golding sent a manuscript to [[Faber and Faber|Faber & Faber]] and was initially rejected by their reader, Jan Perkins, who labelled it as \"Rubbish & dull. Pointless\".<ref name=\"Sunday Feature BBC R3\"> Sunday Feature, 18:45 02/06/2019, BBC Radio 3, 45 mins. https://learningonscreen.ac.uk/ondemand/index.php/prog/13750939?bcast=129246943 (Accessed 16 Apr 2020) </ref> His book, however, was championed by Charles Monteith, a new editor at the firm. Monteith asked for some changes to the text and the novel was published in September 1954 as ''[[Lord of the Flies]]''.\n\nAfter moving in 1958 from [[Salisbury]] to nearby [[Bowerchalke]], he met his fellow villager and walking companion [[James Lovelock]]. The two discussed Lovelock's [[Gaia Hypothesis|hypothesis]], that the living matter of the planet Earth functions like a single organism, and Golding suggested naming this hypothesis after [[Gaia (mythology)|Gaia]], the Titan of the earth in Greek mythology.<ref name=\"ecolo.org\">James Lovelock, \u2018What is Gaia?\u2019, [http://www.ecolo.org/lovelock/what_is_Gaia.html accessed 16 May 2013]</ref> His publishing success made it possible for Golding to resign his teaching post at Bishop Wordsworth's School in 1961, and he spent that academic year in the United States as writer-in-residence at [[Hollins University|Hollins College]], near [[Roanoke, Virginia]].\n\nGolding won the [[James Tait Black Memorial Prize]] for ''[[Darkness Visible (Golding)|Darkness Visible]]'' in 1979, and the [[Man Booker Prize|Booker Prize]] for ''[[Rites of Passage (novel)|Rites of Passage]]'' in 1980. In 1983 he was awarded the [[Nobel Prize for Literature]], and was according to the ''[[Oxford Dictionary of National Biography]]'' \"an unexpected and even contentious choice\".<ref name=\"ODNB\"/>\n\nIn 1988 Golding was appointed a [[Knight Bachelor]].<ref>{{London Gazette|issue=51558 |date=13 December 1988 |page=13986 }}</ref> In September 1993, only a few months after his sudden death, the First International William Golding Conference was held in France, where Golding's presence had been promised and was eagerly expected.<ref>F. Regard (ed.), F''ingering Netsukes: Selected Papers from the First International William Golding Conference'', Saint-Etienne, PUSE, 1995.</ref>\n\nDespite his success, Golding \"was abnormally thin-skinned when it came to criticism of his work. He simply could not read even the mildest reservation and on occasion left the country when his books were published.\"<ref>[https://www.nytimes.com/2010/07/18/books/review/Boyd-t.html \"Man as an Island\"].\n ''The New York Times''.</ref>\n\n===Fiction===\nHis first novel, ''[[Lord of the Flies]]'' (1954; film, 1963 and 1990; play, adapted by [[Nigel Williams (author)|Nigel Williams]], 1995), describes a group of boys stranded on a tropical island reverting to savagery. ''[[The Inheritors (William Golding)|The Inheritors]]'' (1955) shows \"new people\" (generally identified with ''[[Homo sapiens sapiens]]''), triumphing over a gentler race (generally identified with [[Neanderthals]]) by deceit and violence. His 1956 novel ''[[Pincher Martin]]'' records the thoughts of a drowning sailor. ''[[Free Fall (Golding novel)|Free Fall]]'' (1959) explores the issue of free choice as a prisoner held in solitary confinement in a German POW camp during World War Two looks back over his life. ''[[The Spire]]'' (1964) follows the building (and near collapse) of a huge spire onto a medieval cathedral (generally assumed to be [[Salisbury Cathedral]]); the spire symbolizing both spiritual aspiration and worldly vanity.\n\nIn his 1967 novel ''[[The Pyramid (Golding)|The Pyramid]]'' three separate stories in a shared setting (a small English town in the 1920s) are linked by a narrator, and ''The Scorpion God'' (1971) consists of three novellas, the first set in a prehistoric African hunter-gatherer band ('Clonk, Clonk'), the second in an ancient Egyptian court ('The Scorpion God') and the third in the court of a Roman emperor ('Envoy Extraordinary'). The last of these reworks his 1958 play ''The Brass Butterfly''. His later novels include ''[[Darkness Visible (Golding)|Darkness Visible]]'' (1979), which is about a terrorist group, a paedophile teacher, and a mysterious angel-like figure who survives a fire in [[the Blitz]], ''[[The Paper Men]]'' (1984) which is about the conflict between a writer and his biographer, and a sea trilogy ''[[To the Ends of the Earth]]'', which includes ''Rites of Passage'' (1980), ''Close Quarters'' (1987), and ''Fire Down Below'' (1989), the first book of which (originally intended as a stand-alone novel) won the [[Booker Prize]].\n\n==List of works==\n\n===Poetry===\n*''[[Poems (poetry by Golding)|Poems]]'' (1934)\n\n===Drama===\n*''The Brass Butterfly''  (1958)\n\n===Novels===\n*''[[Lord of the Flies]]'' (1954) \n*''[[The Inheritors (William Golding)|The Inheritors]]'' (1955)\n*''[[Pincher Martin]]'' (1956)\n*''[[Free Fall (Golding)|Free Fall]]'' (1959)\n*''[[The Spire]]'' (1964)\n*''[[The Pyramid (Golding)|The Pyramid]]'' (1967)\n*''The Scorpion God''   (1971)\n*''[[Darkness Visible (Golding)|Darkness Visible]]'' (1979)\n*''[[The Paper Men]] (1984)\n*''[[To the Ends of the Earth]]'' (trilogy)\n**''[[Rites of Passage (novel)|Rites of Passage]]'' (1980)\n**''[[Close Quarters (Golding)|Close Quarters]]'' (1987)\n**''[[Fire Down Below (novel)|Fire Down Below]]'' (1989)\n*''[[The Double Tongue]]'' (posthumous publication 1995)<ref>''The Double Tongue'' 1996 Faber reprint {{ISBN|978-0-571-17720-2}}</ref>\n\n===Non-fiction===\n*''[[The Hot Gates]]''  (1965)\n*''[[A Moving Target]]''  (1982)\n*''An Egyptian Journal'' (1985)\n\n===Unpublished works===\n*''Seahorse'' was written in 1948. It is a biographical account of sailing on the south coast of England whilst in training for [[D-Day]].<ref>Carey, p. 130</ref>\n*''Circle Under the Sea'' is an adventure novel about a writer who sails to discover archaeological treasures off the coast of the [[Scilly Isles]].<ref>Carey, p. 137</ref>\n*''Short Measure'' is a novel set in a British boarding school.<ref>Carey, p. 142</ref>\n\n== Audiobooks ==\n* 2005: ''Lord of the Flies'' (read by the author), Listening Library, {{ISBN|978-0307281708}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist|30em}}\n\n==Sources==\n*{{cite book |title=William Golding: The Man Who Wrote Lord of the Flies |last=Carey |first=John |authorlink=John Carey (critic) |year=2009 |publisher=Simon & Schuster |location=New York |isbn=978-1-4391-8732-6 |url-access=registration |url=https://archive.org/details/williamgoldingma0000unse_j6u3 }}\n\n==Further reading==\n{{Portal|Cornwall}}\n* L. L. Dickson, ''The Modern Allegories of William Golding'' (University of South Florida Press, 1990). {{ISBN|0-8130-0971-5}}.\n* R. A. Gekoski and P. A. Grogan, ''William Golding: A Bibliography'', London, Andr\u00e9 Deutsch, 1994. {{ISBN|978-0-233-98611-1}}.\n* \"Boys Armed with Sticks: William Golding's Lord of the Flies\". Chapter in B. Schoene-Harwood. ''Writing Men''. Edinburgh University Press, 2000.\n* Ladenthin, Volker: Golding, Herr der Fliegen; Verne, 2 Jahre Ferien; Schl\u00fcter, Level 4 - Stadt der Kinder. In: engagement (1998) H. 4  S. 271-274.\n\n==External links==\n{{Wikiquote}}\n*[https://www.bbc.co.uk/archive/writers/12203.shtml BBC television interview from 1959]\n*[https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/literature/1983/golding/biographical/ Biography of William Golding] at the [[Nobel Prize]] website\n* [http://aurora.icaap.org/index.php/aurora/article/view/50/63 Interview] by Mary Lynn Scott \u2013 Universal Pessimist, Cosmic Optimist\n* [http://www.william-golding.co.uk/ William Golding Ltd] Website of Golding family.\n* [http://books.guardian.co.uk/departments/generalfiction/story/0,,1793967,00.html ''Last Words'' An account of Golding's last evening] by [[D. M. Thomas]] \u2013 Guardian \u2013 Saturday 10 June 2006 (''Review'' Section)\n* [https://www.facebook.com/WilliamGoldingAuthor/ Official Facebook page]\n* [http://nobelprize.org/nobel_prizes/literature/laureates/1983/golding-lecture.html Nobel Prize Lecture]\n* {{OL author}}\n* [https://www.theguardian.com/books/2012/mar/11/william-golding-crisis \"William Golding's crisis\"]\n* {{IMDb name|0325717}}\n* [http://lib-archives.ex.ac.uk/Record.aspx?src=CalmView.Catalog&id=EUL+MS+429 William Golding] at University of Exeter Special Collections\n\n{{William Golding}}\n{{Booker Prize}}\n{{Nobel Prize in Literature Laureates 1976-2000}}\n{{Culture of Cornwall}}\n{{Lord of the Flies}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Golding, William}}\n[[Category:1911 births]]\n[[Category:1993 deaths]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Brasenose College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:Booker Prize winners]]\n[[Category:British Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:Schoolteachers from Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:English dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:English Nobel laureates]]\n[[Category:James Tait Black Memorial Prize recipients]]\n[[Category:Knights Bachelor]]\n[[Category:Commanders of the Order of the British Empire]]\n[[Category:Nobel laureates in Literature]]\n[[Category:People from Marlborough, Wiltshire]]\n[[Category:People from Newquay]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy personnel of World War II]]\n[[Category:Royal Navy sailors]]\n[[Category:20th-century English novelists]]\n[[Category:20th-century English poets]]\n[[Category:20th-century British dramatists and playwrights]]\n[[Category:Cornish writers]]\n[[Category:English historical novelists]]\n[[Category:Writers of fiction set in Prehistoric times]]\n[[Category:Writers of historical fiction set in the Middle Ages]]\n", "name_user": "Axle bonbon", "label": "safe", "comment": "name spelled", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_Golding"}
{"title_page": "Christian Yelich", "text_new": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = Christian Yelich\n| image       =Yelichbrewers (cropped).jpg\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     = Yelich with the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] in 2018\n| team        = Milwaukee Brewers\n| number      = 22\n| position    = [[Outfielder]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1991|12|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Thousand Oaks, California]]\n| bats        = Left\n| throws      = Right\n| debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = July 23\n| debutyear   = 2013\n| debutteam   = Miami Marlins\n| statyear    = 2019 season\n| statleague  = MLB\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .301\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 139\n| stat3label  = [[Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value  = 500\n| stat4label  = [[Stolen base]]s\n| stat4value  = 124\n| teams       = \n* [[Miami Marlins]] ({{mlby|2013}}\u2013{{mlby|2017}})\n* [[Milwaukee Brewers]] ({{mlby|2018}}\u2013present)\n|highlights=\n* 2\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2018 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2018]], [[2019 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2019]])\n* [[All-MLB Team|All-MLB First Team]] (2019)\n* [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|NL MVP]] (2018)\n* [[Gold Glove Award]] (2014)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2016, 2018, 2019)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Hank Aaron Award|NL Hank Aaron Award]] (2018, 2019)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|NL batting champion]] (2018, 2019)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Hitting for the cycle|Hit for the cycle]] (2018)\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | the {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Baseball Classic]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2017 World Baseball Classic|2017 Los Angeles]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Christian Stephen Yelich''' (born December 5, 1991) is an [[Americans|American]] [[professional baseball]] [[outfielder]] for the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played for the [[Miami Marlins]].\n\nThe Marlins selected Yelich in the first round of the [[2010 Major League Baseball draft|2010 MLB draft]]. He made his major league debut for the Marlins in 2013, and was traded to the Brewers in the 2017-18 offseason. Yelich won a [[Gold Glove Award]] in 2014, the [[Silver Slugger Award]] in 2016 and 2018, and the [[National League]]'s [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] in 2018.\n\n==Career==\n===Amateur career===\nYel76yhn ich was born in [[Thousand Oaks, California]], and attended [[Westlake High School (California)|Westlake High School]].<ref name=\"pbp\">{{cite news|last1=Capozzi|first1=Joe|title=Miami Marlins outfield prospect Christian Yelich on path to majors|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/miami-marlins-outfield-prospect-yelich-on-path-to-/nWKsm/|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Palm Beach Post|date=February 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820080201/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/miami-marlins-outfield-prospect-yelich-on-path-to-/nWKsm/|archive-date=August 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During his freshman year, he batted .373 with 25 hits and 16 strikeouts in 67 [[at bats]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/AcgUfUavpUKUN4POUZyPBg/baseball-spring-07/stats-christian-yelich.htm |title=Christian Yelich Freshman Stats |work=MaxPreps |access-date=June 4, 2011}}</ref>  In his sophomore year, he batted .341 with 31 hits and 24 strikeouts in 91 at bats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/FnMuytNhD0iLvpVNLN39kg/baseball-spring-08/profile-christian-yelich.htm |title=Christian Yelich Sophomore Stats |website=MaxPreps |access-date=June 4, 2011}}</ref> During Yelich's junior year, he batted .489 with 46 hits and struck out 6 times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/69ARd4sztUyAmC7bS7QaiA/baseball-spring-09/profile-christian-yelich.htm |title=Christian Yelich Junior Stats |website=MaxPreps |access-date=June 4, 2011}}</ref> In his senior year, he batted .451 with 37 hits, nine strikeouts and nine home runs in 82 at bats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/swMG0HEmPE2Hdh24Tke5uQ/baseball-spring-10/profile-christian-yelich.htm |title=Christian Yelich Senior Stats |website=MaxPreps |access-date=June 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623232826/http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/swMG0HEmPE2Hdh24Tke5uQ/baseball-spring-10/profile-christian-yelich.htm |archive-date=June 23, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>  He was named Second Team All-American by Max Preps and was ranked 34 among the top 100 players in the nation in high school.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/baseball-recruiting/baseball-spring-10/r2IdWSY1Ed-UswAcxJTdpg/2010-top-100-/top-recruits.htm |title=Baseball Recruiting: 2010 Top 100 |website=MaxPreps |access-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430183808/https://www.maxpreps.com/baseball-recruiting/baseball-spring-10/r2IdWSY1Ed-UswAcxJTdpg/2010-top-100-/top-recruits.htm |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYelich accepted a scholarship to play [[college baseball]] for the [[Miami Hurricanes baseball]] team.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Millian|first1=Jorge|title=Top pick Christian Yelich picked Marlins over UM|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/top-pick-christian-yelich-picked-marlins-over-um-1/nL9Qk/|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Palm Beach Post|date=August 21, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820113322/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/top-pick-christian-yelich-picked-marlins-over-um-1/nL9Qk/|archive-date=August 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n===Professional career===\n====Miami Marlins====\n[[File:IMG 0018 Christian Yelich.jpg|right|upright|thumb|Yelich with the [[Jupiter Hammerheads]] in 2012]]\nThe [[Miami Marlins]] selected Yelich in the first round, with the 23rd overall selection, in the [[2010 Major League Baseball draft]]. Yelich and the Marlins agreed to a $1.7&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]] on August 17, shortly before the deadline to sign 2010 draftees was about to pass.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Juan C.|title=Marlins, first-rounder Yelich agree just before deadline|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2010-08-17/sports/fl-marlins-notes-0818-20100817_1_christian-yelich-chad-james-first-puerto-rican-born-manager|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=August 17, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826004532/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2010-08-17/sports/fl-marlins-notes-0818-20100817_1_christian-yelich-chad-james-first-puerto-rican-born-manager|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Marlins sign Yelich for $1.7 million bonus|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/2010-08-17-450955388_x.htm|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=USA Today|agency=Associated Press|date=August 17, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025031109/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/2010-08-17-450955388_x.htm|archive-date=October 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich played for the [[Gulf Coast League Marlins]] for six games, getting nine hits and seven strikeouts with a batting average of .375 before being advanced to Class-A. He played in six games for the [[Greensboro Grasshoppers]] in 2010, batting .348. In 2011, he batted .261 with 43 hits, six strikeouts and four home runs. Yelich was named the Marlins' Minor League Player of the Year in both 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duarte|first1=Shaunte|title=Marlins Top Prospects: #1 Christian Yelich|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120329&content_id=27727732&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t588|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MILB.com|date=March 30, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914110952/http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120329&content_id=27727732&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t588|archive-date=September 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Juan C.|title=Marlins recognize top minor leaguers Yelich, Fernandez|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-09-29/sports/fl-miami-marlins-0930-20120929_1_tampa-alonso-high-school-christian-yelich-marlins-park|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=September 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610215000/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-09-29/sports/fl-miami-marlins-0930-20120929_1_tampa-alonso-high-school-christian-yelich-marlins-park|archive-date=June 10, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 23, 2013, the Marlins promoted Yelich to the major leagues from the Double-A [[Jacksonville Suns]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spencer|first1=Clark|title=Christian Yelich and Jake Marisnick called up to join the Marlins|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article1953506.html|accessdate=March 22, 2015|work=Miami Herald|date=July 24, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402190130/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article1953506.html|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Marlins call up two outfield prospects|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/9503916/miami-marlins-call-outfielders-christian-yelich-jake-marisnick|accessdate=March 22, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=July 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403002154/http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/9503916/miami-marlins-call-outfielders-christian-yelich-jake-marisnick|archive-date=April 3, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In the 2014 season, Yelich batted .284 with 21 steals out of the leadoff spot for the Miami Marlins.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fialkov|first1=Harvey|title=Christian Yelich returning to form|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/fl-miami-marlins-news-0704-20150703-story.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=July 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826005710/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/fl-miami-marlins-news-0704-20150703-story.html|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He also won a [[Gold Glove Award]] in left field, becoming the franchise's youngest ever player and first outfielder to win the award.<ref>{{cite news|last1=De Nicola|first1=Christina|title=Marlins left fielder Christian Yelich wins NL Gold Glove|url=http://www.foxsports.com/florida/story/miami-marlins-christian-yelich-gold-glove-110414|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=Fox Sports|date=November 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816150004/http://www.foxsports.com/florida/story/miami-marlins-christian-yelich-gold-glove-110414|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Navarro|first1=Manny|title=Miami Marlins outfielder Christian Yelich wins Gold Glove|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article3562951.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Miami Herald|date=November 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807023144/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article3562951.html|archive-date=August 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich first Marlins outfielder to win Gold Glove|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/100564712/christian-yelich-first-marlins-outfielder-to-win-gold-glove|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=November 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109110105/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/100564712/christian-yelich-first-marlins-outfielder-to-win-gold-glove|archive-date=November 9, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> During the season, Yelich set a franchise record for fielding percentage in left field, at .996.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Craig|title=Marlins' Christian Yelich wins first Gold Glove|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/sfl-christian-yelich-gold-glove-20141104-story.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=November 3, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825235011/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/sfl-christian-yelich-gold-glove-20141104-story.html|archive-date=August 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He served as the final out of [[Jordan Zimmermann]]'s no-hitter on September 28, 2014, when [[Steven Souza Jr.]] made a diving play to save the no-hitter.\n\nYelich and the Marlins finalized a seven-year, $49.57 million contract extension on March 22, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Marlins lock up Yelich with seven-year pact|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/114144786/miami-marlins-lock-up-christian-yelich-with-seven-year-pact|accessdate=March 22, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|date=March 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324142716/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/114144786/miami-marlins-lock-up-christian-yelich-with-seven-year-pact|archive-date=March 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He struggled to start the season, and was placed on the disabled list in April with lower back strain before making his return on May 8.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Navarro|first1=Manny|title=Miami Marlins left fielder Christian Yelich placed on disabled list|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article19426680.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Miami Herald|date=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807061034/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article19426680.html|archive-date=August 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Marlins activate LF Christian Yelich off DL; Reid Brignac sent down|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/sfl-marlins-activate-christian-yelich-20150508-story.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=May 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826001930/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/sfl-marlins-activate-christian-yelich-20150508-story.html|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> His batting average reached a season low of .178 on May 22.<ref name=\"hotfinish\">{{cite news|last1=D'Angelo|first1=Tom|title=After hot 2015 finish, Christian Yelich doesn't want another cold start|url=http://www.mypalmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/after-hot-2015-finish-christian-yelich-doesnt-want/nqWFP/|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Palm Beach Post|date=February 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917225114/http://www.mypalmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/after-hot-2015-finish-christian-yelich-doesnt-want/nqWFP/|archive-date=September 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In August, Yelich bruised his right knee and was again placed on the disabled list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miami Marlins put Christian Yelich on disabled list|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-0816-baseball-notes-20150816-story.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=Associated Press|date=August 15, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817024711/http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-0816-baseball-notes-20150816-story.html|archivedate=August 17, 2016|via=ESPN.com|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich had improved from his earlier offensive struggles and was hitting .275/.343/.376 with six home runs, 29 RBIs and 14 stolen bases up to that point in the season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilaj|first1=Steve|title=Yelich day to day with right knee injury|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/142520112/christian-yelich-has-right-knee-contusion|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Knee swelling continues to hamper Yelich|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/143163360/swollen-knee-keeping-christian-yelich-out|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222175521/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/143163360/swollen-knee-keeping-christian-yelich-out|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite aggravating the injury shortly after his return, Yelich remained an active player for the quality of his bat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=No DL stint, but Yelich likely to miss rest of trip|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/145955664/christian-yelich-likely-out-rest-of-road-trip|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227232732/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/145955664/christian-yelich-likely-out-rest-of-road-trip|archive-date=December 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich to be handled carefully after pinch-hit|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/146348972/christian-yelich-limited-to-pinch-hitting|accessdate=July 3, 2016|date=August 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229003228/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/146348972/christian-yelich-limited-to-pinch-hitting|archive-date=December 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Near the end of the season, Yelich shared the field with [[Marcell Ozuna]], the outfielder who had replaced him during his second stint on the disabled list.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich, Ozuna beginning to click for Marlins|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146947282/marlins-begin-to-see-what-yelich-ozuna-can-do|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=September 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230103450/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146947282/marlins-begin-to-see-what-yelich-ozuna-can-do|archive-date=December 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich closed the 2015 season with a .300 average.<ref name=\"hotfinish\"/> For the season, he had the highest [[ground ball]] percentage (62.5%), and the lowest [[Fly ball (baseball)|fly ball]] percentage (15.0%), of all major league hitters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2016&month=0&season1=2016&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=6,d |title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2016 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Batted Ball Statistics {{!}} FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=December 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222082041/https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2016&month=0&season1=2016&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=6,d |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYelich was projected to bat third to start 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Andre C.|title=Marlins' Christian Yelich 'excited' about starting fresh in 2016|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article69344317.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Miami Herald|date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807061908/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article69344317.html|archive-date=August 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He hit well in that spot, and managed to increase his power output.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich's power surfacing as No. 3 hitter|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/184732822/marlins-christian-yelich-homers-vs-rockies|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=June 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619141418/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/184732822/marlins-christian-yelich-homers-vs-rockies|archive-date=June 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Putterman|first1=Alex|title=Yelich finding pop in his bat this season|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/178140460/marlins-christian-yelich-hits-homer-vs-nats|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521231919/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/178140460/marlins-christian-yelich-hits-homer-vs-nats|archive-date=May 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 23, in a game against the [[San Francisco Giants]], Yelich hit three doubles, which tied a franchise record.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich's double trio not enough for Marlins|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/174038822/marlins-christian-yelich-hits-3-doubles|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=April 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424112712/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/174038822/marlins-christian-yelich-hits-3-doubles|archive-date=April 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Defensively, Yelich was a starting outfielder, alongside Ozuna and [[Giancarlo Stanton]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bloom|first1=Barry M.|title=Tough for Ichiro to crack Marlins' talented outfield|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/172146164/young-marlins-outfield-keeping-ichiro-on-bench|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=April 13, 2016}}</ref> In late May, Yelich missed some time due to back spasms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Ichiro, 42, wows with 4 hits in Marlins' win|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/179456806/ichiro-suzuki-has-4-hits-in-marlins-win|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525211041/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/179456806/ichiro-suzuki-has-4-hits-in-marlins-win|archive-date=May 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich, Giancarlo not being rushed back|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/180572940/marlins-yelich-giancarlo-stanton-are-better|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529111739/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/180572940/marlins-yelich-giancarlo-stanton-are-better|archive-date=May 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After Stanton was placed on the disabled list, Ozuna played Stanton's usual position in right field, while Yelich took Ozuna's spot in center on days that backup outfielder [[Ichiro Suzuki]] was unavailable.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Healey|first1=Tim|title=Marlins option Brian Ellington to New Orleans to activate A.J. Ramos|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/fl-marlins-news-0822-20160821-story.html|accessdate=August 27, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=August 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915164420/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/fl-marlins-news-0822-20160821-story.html|archive-date=September 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Milwaukee Brewers====\nOn January 25, 2018, the Marlins traded Yelich to the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] for [[Lewis Brinson]], [[Isan D\u00edaz]], [[Monte Harrison]], and [[Jordan Yamamoto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/22214491/miami-marlins-trade-outfielder-christian-yelich-milwaukee-brewers|title=Brewers acquire OF Christian Yelich from rebuilding Marlins|work=ESPN.com|date=January 25, 2018|accessdate=January 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126001422/http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/22214491/miami-marlins-trade-outfielder-christian-yelich-milwaukee-brewers|archive-date=January 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich was named to the [[2018 MLB All-Star Game]] after batting .285 with 11 home runs, 36 RBIs, and 11 stolen bases.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://host.madison.com/wsj/sports/baseball/professional/lorenzo-cain-christian-yelich-and-josh-hader-selected-to-nl/article_e532d30e-eb7e-5eef-8b26-648e9504f023.html |title=Lorenzo Cain, Christian Yelich, Josh Hader selected to All-Star Game; Jesus Aguilar needs fans' votes |first=Andrew |last=Wagner |newspaper=[[Wisconsin State Journal]] |via=madison.com |date=July 9, 2018 |access-date=July 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712025425/https://host.madison.com/wsj/sports/baseball/professional/lorenzo-cain-christian-yelich-and-josh-hader-selected-to-nl/article_e532d30e-eb7e-5eef-8b26-648e9504f023.html |archive-date=July 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Yelich, a reserve for the [[National League]], replaced [[Matt Kemp]] in left field and went 1-for-3, hitting a solo home run in an 8\u20136 extra-inning loss to the [[American League]]. On August 29, Yelich [[hitting for the cycle|hit for the cycle]] against the [[Cincinnati Reds]], collecting a total of six hits in the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-for-cycle-against-reds/c-292511126 |title=Yelich completes cycle with game-tying triple |first=Adam |last=McCalvy |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 29, 2018 |accessdate=August 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830033556/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-for-cycle-against-reds/c-292511126 |archive-date=August 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 2, Yelich hit his first career [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]], in a game against the [[Washington Nationals]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-first-career-slam-in-win/c-293018914 |title=Yelich hits 1st career slam as Crew takes series |first=Adam |last=McCalvy |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 2, 2018 |accessdate=September 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903013513/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-first-career-slam-in-win/c-293018914 |archive-date=September 3, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 17, Yelich hit for the cycle, also against the [[Cincinnati Reds]], for the second time in 19 days, becoming the fifth player in MLB history to hit two cycles in the same season and the first player in MLB history to do so against the same team.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-for-2nd-cycle-of-season/c-294990668 |title=Yelich's historic bi-cycle vs. Reds fuels Crew |first=Adam |last=McCalvy |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919133946/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-for-2nd-cycle-of-season/c-294990668 |archive-date=September 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYelich finished the 2018 season with a .326/.402/.598 [[slash line]], 36 homers, and 110 RBIs, winning the first [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|NL batting title]] in Brewers history, while narrowly falling short of a [[Triple Crown (baseball)|triple crown]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCalvy |first1=Adam |title=Yelich wins batting title, falls shy of Triple Crown |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-falls-short-of-triple-crown/c-296663648 |website=MLB |publisher=MLB Advanced Media |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001232703/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-falls-short-of-triple-crown/c-296663648 |archive-date=October 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Haudricourt |first1=Tom |title=Christian Yelich gets an extra day to shoot for first Triple Crown in NL in 81 years |url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/sports/mlb/brewers/2018/09/30/brewers-christian-yelich-gets-extra-game-go-nl-triple-crown/1478754002/ |website=Journal Sentinel |publisher=The Milwaukee Journal Sentinel |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> He also was 2nd in the league in [[power-speed number]] (27.3).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/2018-batting-leaders.shtml |title=2018 National League Batting Leaders |website=Baseball-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125004512/https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/2018-batting-leaders.shtml |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On October 26, Yelich was announced as the National League recipient of the annual [[Hank Aaron Award]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/aaron-winners-jd-martinez-christian-yelich/c-299746010 |title=J.D., Yelich named 2018 Aaron Award winners |first=Anthony |last=Castrovince |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=October 26, 2018 |accessdate=October 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027040836/https://www.mlb.com/news/aaron-winners-jd-martinez-christian-yelich/c-299746010 |archive-date=October 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On November 16, Yelich was named [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] of the National League, falling one vote shy of a unanimous selection.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-wins-2018-nl-mvp-award/c-300793484 |title=Yelich crowned MVP in first year with Crew |last=McCalvy |first=Adam |date=November 16, 2018 |publisher=MLB.com |access-date=November 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122111930/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-wins-2018-nl-mvp-award/c-300793484 |archive-date=November 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 2019, Yelich became the sixth player in MLB history to hit a home run in each of his team's first four games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-homers-in-four-straight-games |title=Yelich's HR in 4th straight game ties record |last=McCalvy |first=Adam |date=March 31, 2019 |publisher=MLB.com |access-date=March 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331203206/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-homers-in-four-straight-games |archive-date=March 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2019, Yelich became the first player in Brewers franchise history to reach 30 home runs before the All-Star Break, beating former Brewer [[Prince Fielder]]'s record of 29 home runs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/wisconsin/story/christian-yelich-hits-30th-homer-milwaukee-brewers-top-reds-8-6-070119 |title=Yelich hits 30th homer, Brewers top Reds 8-6 |date=July 1, 2019 |publisher=FOXSports.com |access-date=July 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704043522/https://www.foxsports.com/wisconsin/story/christian-yelich-hits-30th-homer-milwaukee-brewers-top-reds-8-6-070119 |archive-date=July 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Yelich was selected to participate in the Home Run Derby but had to withdraw due to a back injury. He was replaced by [[Matt Chapman]] in the Home Run Derby. On September 10, 2019, Yelich hit a foul ball off his kneecap and left the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-exits-with-knee-injury|title=Yelich out for season after fracturing kneecap|website=MLB.com|date=September 11, 2019|access-date=September 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911214530/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-exits-with-knee-injury|archive-date=September 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, it was revealed that his right kneecap was fractured, which prematurely ended his 2019 season.\n\nIn 2019, Yelich won his second National League batting title. He batted .329/.429 (leading the NL)/.671 (leading the major leagues) with a 1.100 [[On-base plus slugging|OPS]] (leading the majors), 44 home runs (4th in the NL), 11.1 at bats per home runs (leading the league), a .342 [[Isolated Power|ISO]] (leading the NL), 30 stolen bases (3rd), a 93.75 stolen base percentage (3rd), and 97 RBIs in 130 games.<ref name=\"WTMJ News\">{{cite news |last1=Sorgi |first1=Jay |title=Brewers' Christian Yelich clinches second National League batting title |url=http://www.wtmj.com/sports/baseball/milwaukee-brewers/brewers-christian-yelich-clinches-second-national-league-batting-title/1126765172 |accessdate=30 September 2019 |publisher=WTMJ News |date=29 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930034841/http://www.wtmj.com/sports/baseball/milwaukee-brewers/brewers-christian-yelich-clinches-second-national-league-batting-title/1126765172 |archive-date=September 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=1&season=2019&month=0&season1=2019&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&startdate=2019-01-01&enddate=2019-12-31&sort=11,d |title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2019 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Advanced Statistics &#124; FanGraphs Baseball |publisher=Fangraphs.com |date=2019-01-01 |accessdate=2019-10-07}}</ref> He had the highest Hard Contact Percentage of all National League batters, at 50.8%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2019&month=0&season1=2019&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&startdate=2019-01-01&enddate=2019-12-31&sort=19,d |title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2019 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Batted Ball Statistics &#124; FanGraphs Baseball |publisher=Fangraphs.com |date=2019-01-01 |accessdate=2019-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229083640/https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2019&month=0&season1=2019&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&startdate=2019-01-01&enddate=2019-12-31&sort=19,d |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He won the NL [[Hank Aaron Award]] for the second year in a row<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/mike-trout-christian-yelich-win-aaron-award|title=Mike Trout, Christian Yelich win Aaron award|website=MLB.com|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119091103/https://www.mlb.com/news/mike-trout-christian-yelich-win-aaron-award|archive-date=November 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and finished second in NL MVP voting.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-mvp-award-vote-totals |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115133447/https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-mvp-award-vote-totals |archive-date=November 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2020, Yelich signed a nine-year, $215&nbsp;million contract extension with the Brewers.<ref>https://www.jsonline.com/story/sports/mlb/brewers/2020/03/06/brewers-make-official-signing-christian-yelich-nine-years/4967961002/</ref>\n\n==International career==\n\nYelich played for the [[United States national baseball team]] in the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]].  Following the conclusion of the tournament, he was named to the [[2017 World Baseball Classic#2017 All-World Baseball Classic team|All-World Baseball Classic team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/world-baseball-classic-previous-champs-results-medal-count-mvps-all-wbc-teams/ |title=World Baseball Classic: Previous champs, results, medal count, MVPs, All-WBC teams |last=Perry |first=Dayn |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627230644/https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/world-baseball-classic-previous-champs-results-medal-count-mvps-all-wbc-teams/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2018, he was selected to play with the MLB All-Stars at the [[2018 MLB Japan All-Star Series]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mlbplayers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=34000&ATCLID=211771396 | title=Eight Players Selected for Japan All-Star Series | work=The Official Site of Major League Baseball Players Association | date=September 10, 2018 | accessdate=September 12, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912054652/http://www.mlbplayers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=34000&ATCLID=211771396 | archive-date=September 12, 2018 | url-status=dead }}</ref> but he later withdrew from the event.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.japan-baseball.jp/jp/news/press/20181029_3.html | title=2018\u65e5\u7c73\u91ce\u7403 MLB\u30aa\u30fc\u30eb\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30c1\u30fc\u30e0\u51fa\u5834\u4e88\u5b9a\u9078\u624b\u306e\u8f9e\u9000\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 | work=\u91ce\u7403\u65e5\u672c\u4ee3\u8868 \u4f8d\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3 \u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 | language=Japanese | date=October 29, 2018 | accessdate=December 5, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102084519/http://www.japan-baseball.jp/jp/news/press/20181029_3.html | archive-date=November 2, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYelich appeared in an episode of ''[[Magnum P.I. (2018 TV series)|Magnum P.I.]]'' that aired on March 4, 2019. Yelich once invited [[Cleveland Browns]] quarterback and 2017 [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Baker Mayfield]] to Brewers batting practice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/871269/2019/03/15/christian-yelich-brought-a-friend-to-brewers-batting-practice-baker-mayfield/|title=Christian Yelich brought a friend to Brewers batting practice: Baker Mayfield|last=Murray|first=Robert|date=March 15, 2019|work=The Athletic|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401003346/https://theathletic.com/871269/2019/03/15/christian-yelich-brought-a-friend-to-brewers-batting-practice-baker-mayfield/|archive-date=April 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nYelich's maternal great-grandfather was [[American football]] player [[Fred Gehrke]].<ref name=\"pbp\"/> An uncle, Chris Yelich, played football for the [[UCLA Bruins football|UCLA Bruins]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Juan C.|title=Marlins notes: Yelich branches off family football tree|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2014-03-04/sports/fl-marlins-0305-20140304_1_christian-yelich-reeves-pioneer-award-fred-gehrke|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=March 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825221131/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2014-03-04/sports/fl-marlins-0305-20140304_1_christian-yelich-reeves-pioneer-award-fred-gehrke|archive-date=August 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich is the oldest of three children; his brothers are Collin and Cameron.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich shares his favorite holiday memories|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/66109836/|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=December 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814175618/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/66109836/|archive-date=August 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Collin was selected by the [[Atlanta Braves]] in the [[2015 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Andrade|first1=Jonathan|title=Yelich is a name to remember|url=http://www.toacorn.com/news/2015-07-23/Sports/Yelich_is_a_name_to_remember.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Thousand Oaks Acorn|date=July 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013175006/http://www.toacorn.com/news/2015-07-23/Sports/Yelich_is_a_name_to_remember.html|archive-date=October 13, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Cameron is a [[United States Marine]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Strang|first1=Katie|title=Marlins with military ties look forward to 'perfect weekend' at Fort Bragg|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/71913/marlins-braves-look-forward-to-perfect-weekend-at-fort-bragg|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=ESPN.com|date=July 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703115207/http://espn.go.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/71913/marlins-braves-look-forward-to-perfect-weekend-at-fort-bragg|archive-date=July 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Fort Bragg trip hits home for Yelich|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/186893018/christian-yelich-honored-to-play-at-fort-bragg|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=June 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702062156/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/186893018/christian-yelich-honored-to-play-at-fort-bragg|archive-date=July 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> His paternal grandfather was [[Serbs|Serbian]] while his maternal grandfather was [[Japanese_people|Japanese]].\n\nYelich grew up both a [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] fan and a [[New York Yankees]] fan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/mlb/la-sp-baseball-milwaukee-brewers-20180324-story.html |title=Christian Yelich's outfielder talents could lift Brewers while Dodgers miss out |date=2018-03-24 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412183525/https://www.latimes.com/sports/mlb/la-sp-baseball-milwaukee-brewers-20180324-story.html |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/28844157/christian-yelich-cody-bellinger-walk-bar |title=\nHang Time: Christian Yelich and Cody Bellinger walk into a bar |date=March 6, 2020 |website=ESPN |language=en-US |access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n* [[List of Major League Baseball single-game hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players to hit for the cycle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Christian Yelich}}\n{{baseballstats|espn=31283|fangraphs=11477|mlb=592885|br=y/yelicch01|brm=yelich001chr|retro=Y/Pyelic001}}\n*{{twitter}}\n*{{instagram|christianyelich|christianyelich}}\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{succession box| before = [[Mookie Betts]] | title = [[Hitting for the cycle]]| years = August 29, 2018 | after = himself}}\n{{Succession box| before = himself | title = [[Hitting for the cycle]]| years = September 17, 2018 | after = [[Charlie Blackmon]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{2010 MLB Draft}}\n{{Miami Marlins first-round draft picks}}\n{{NL MVPs}}\n{{NL batting title}}\n{{NL OF Gold Glove Award}}\n{{NL OF Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{NL Hank Aaron Award Winners}}\n{{2019 All MLB Team}}\n{{United States roster 2017 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{2017 World Baseball Classic All WBC Team}}\n{{Milwaukee Brewers roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yelich, Christian}}\n\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:2017 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:American baseball players of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Greensboro Grasshoppers players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Marlins players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Suns players]]\n[[Category:Jupiter Hammerheads players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball left fielders]]\n[[Category:Miami Marlins players]]\n[[Category:Milwaukee Brewers players]]\n[[Category:National League batting champions]]\n[[Category:National League Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Zephyrs players]]\n[[Category:People from Thousand Oaks, California]]\n[[Category:Phoenix Desert Dogs players]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ventura County, California]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|American baseball player}}\n{{Use mdy dates|date=January 2019}}\n{{Infobox baseball biography\n| name        = Christian Yelich\n| image       =Yelichbrewers (cropped).jpg\n| image_size  = 250px\n| caption     = Yelich with the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] in 2018\n| team        = Milwaukee Brewers\n| number      = 22\n| position    = [[Outfielder]]\n| birth_date  = {{Birth date and age|1991|12|5}}\n| birth_place = [[Thousand Oaks, California]]\n| bats        = Left\n| throws      = Right\n| debutleague = MLB\n| debutdate   = July 23\n| debutyear   = 2013\n| debutteam   = Miami Marlins\n| statyear    = 2019 season\n| statleague  = MLB\n| stat1label  = [[Batting average (baseball)|Batting average]]\n| stat1value  = .301\n| stat2label  = [[Home run]]s\n| stat2value  = 139\n| stat3label  = [[Runs batted in]]\n| stat3value  = 500\n| stat4label  = [[Stolen base]]s\n| stat4value  = 124\n| teams       = \n* [[Miami Marlins]] ({{mlby|2013}}\u2013{{mlby|2017}})\n* [[Milwaukee Brewers]] ({{mlby|2018}}\u2013present)\n|highlights=\n* 2\u00d7 [[Major League Baseball All-Star Game|All-Star]] ([[2018 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2018]], [[2019 Major League Baseball All-Star Game|2019]])\n* [[All-MLB Team|All-MLB First Team]] (2019)\n* [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|NL MVP]] (2018)\n* [[Gold Glove Award]] (2014)\n* 3\u00d7 [[Silver Slugger Award]] (2016, 2018, 2019)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Hank Aaron Award|NL Hank Aaron Award]] (2018, 2019)\n* 2\u00d7 [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|NL batting champion]] (2018, 2019)\n* 2\u00d7 [[Hitting for the cycle|Hit for the cycle]] (2018)\n| medaltemplates =\n{{MedalSport | Men's [[baseball]]}}\n{{MedalCountry | the {{USA}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition | [[World Baseball Classic]]}}\n{{MedalGold | [[2017 World Baseball Classic|2017 Los Angeles]] | [[United States national baseball team|Team]]}}\n}}\n\n'''Christian Stephen Yelich''' (born December 5, 1991) is an [[Americans|American]] [[professional baseball]] [[outfielder]] for the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] of [[Major League Baseball]] (MLB). He previously played for the [[Miami Marlins]].\n\nThe Marlins selected Yelich in the first round of the [[2010 Major League Baseball draft|2010 MLB draft]]. He made his major league debut for the Marlins in 2013, and was traded to the Brewers in the 2017-18 offseason. Yelich won a [[Gold Glove Award]] in 2014, the [[Silver Slugger Award]] in 2016 and 2018, and the [[National League]]'s [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player Award]] in 2018.\n\n==Career==\n===Amateur career===\nYelich was born in [[Thousand Oaks, California]], and attended [[Westlake High School (California)|Westlake High School]].<ref name=\"pbp\">{{cite news|last1=Capozzi|first1=Joe|title=Miami Marlins outfield prospect Christian Yelich on path to majors|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/miami-marlins-outfield-prospect-yelich-on-path-to-/nWKsm/|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Palm Beach Post|date=February 9, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820080201/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/miami-marlins-outfield-prospect-yelich-on-path-to-/nWKsm/|archive-date=August 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> During his freshman year, he batted .373 with 25 hits and 16 strikeouts in 67 [[at bats]].<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/AcgUfUavpUKUN4POUZyPBg/baseball-spring-07/stats-christian-yelich.htm |title=Christian Yelich Freshman Stats |work=MaxPreps |access-date=June 4, 2011}}</ref>  In his sophomore year, he batted .341 with 31 hits and 24 strikeouts in 91 at bats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/FnMuytNhD0iLvpVNLN39kg/baseball-spring-08/profile-christian-yelich.htm |title=Christian Yelich Sophomore Stats |website=MaxPreps |access-date=June 4, 2011}}</ref> During Yelich's junior year, he batted .489 with 46 hits and struck out 6 times.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/69ARd4sztUyAmC7bS7QaiA/baseball-spring-09/profile-christian-yelich.htm |title=Christian Yelich Junior Stats |website=MaxPreps |access-date=June 4, 2011}}</ref> In his senior year, he batted .451 with 37 hits, nine strikeouts and nine home runs in 82 at bats.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/swMG0HEmPE2Hdh24Tke5uQ/baseball-spring-10/profile-christian-yelich.htm |title=Christian Yelich Senior Stats |website=MaxPreps |access-date=June 4, 2011 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20130623232826/http://www.maxpreps.com/athletes/swMG0HEmPE2Hdh24Tke5uQ/baseball-spring-10/profile-christian-yelich.htm |archive-date=June 23, 2013 |url-status=live }}</ref>  He was named Second Team All-American by Max Preps and was ranked 34 among the top 100 players in the nation in high school.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.maxpreps.com/baseball-recruiting/baseball-spring-10/r2IdWSY1Ed-UswAcxJTdpg/2010-top-100-/top-recruits.htm |title=Baseball Recruiting: 2010 Top 100 |website=MaxPreps |access-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190430183808/https://www.maxpreps.com/baseball-recruiting/baseball-spring-10/r2IdWSY1Ed-UswAcxJTdpg/2010-top-100-/top-recruits.htm |archive-date=April 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYelich accepted a scholarship to play [[college baseball]] for the [[Miami Hurricanes baseball]] team.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Millian|first1=Jorge|title=Top pick Christian Yelich picked Marlins over UM|url=http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/top-pick-christian-yelich-picked-marlins-over-um-1/nL9Qk/|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Palm Beach Post|date=August 21, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160820113322/http://www.palmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/top-pick-christian-yelich-picked-marlins-over-um-1/nL9Qk/|archive-date=August 20, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> \n\n===Professional career===\n====Miami Marlins====\n[[File:IMG 0018 Christian Yelich.jpg|right|upright|thumb|Yelich with the [[Jupiter Hammerheads]] in 2012]]\nThe [[Miami Marlins]] selected Yelich in the first round, with the 23rd overall selection, in the [[2010 Major League Baseball draft]]. Yelich and the Marlins agreed to a $1.7&nbsp;million [[signing bonus]] on August 17, shortly before the deadline to sign 2010 draftees was about to pass.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Juan C.|title=Marlins, first-rounder Yelich agree just before deadline|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2010-08-17/sports/fl-marlins-notes-0818-20100817_1_christian-yelich-chad-james-first-puerto-rican-born-manager|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=August 17, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826004532/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2010-08-17/sports/fl-marlins-notes-0818-20100817_1_christian-yelich-chad-james-first-puerto-rican-born-manager|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Marlins sign Yelich for $1.7 million bonus|url=http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/2010-08-17-450955388_x.htm|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=USA Today|agency=Associated Press|date=August 17, 2010|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161025031109/http://usatoday30.usatoday.com/sports/baseball/nl/2010-08-17-450955388_x.htm|archive-date=October 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich played for the [[Gulf Coast League Marlins]] for six games, getting nine hits and seven strikeouts with a batting average of .375 before being advanced to Class-A. He played in six games for the [[Greensboro Grasshoppers]] in 2010, batting .348. In 2011, he batted .261 with 43 hits, six strikeouts and four home runs. Yelich was named the Marlins' Minor League Player of the Year in both 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Duarte|first1=Shaunte|title=Marlins Top Prospects: #1 Christian Yelich|url=http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120329&content_id=27727732&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t588|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MILB.com|date=March 30, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160914110952/http://www.milb.com/news/article.jsp?ymd=20120329&content_id=27727732&fext=.jsp&vkey=news_t588|archive-date=September 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Juan C.|title=Marlins recognize top minor leaguers Yelich, Fernandez|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-09-29/sports/fl-miami-marlins-0930-20120929_1_tampa-alonso-high-school-christian-yelich-marlins-park|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=September 29, 2012|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150610215000/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2012-09-29/sports/fl-miami-marlins-0930-20120929_1_tampa-alonso-high-school-christian-yelich-marlins-park|archive-date=June 10, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nOn July 23, 2013, the Marlins promoted Yelich to the major leagues from the Double-A [[Jacksonville Suns]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Spencer|first1=Clark|title=Christian Yelich and Jake Marisnick called up to join the Marlins|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article1953506.html|accessdate=March 22, 2015|work=Miami Herald|date=July 24, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150402190130/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article1953506.html|archive-date=April 2, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Marlins call up two outfield prospects|url=http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/9503916/miami-marlins-call-outfielders-christian-yelich-jake-marisnick|accessdate=March 22, 2015|agency=Associated Press|publisher=ESPN.com|date=July 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150403002154/http://espn.go.com/mlb/story/_/id/9503916/miami-marlins-call-outfielders-christian-yelich-jake-marisnick|archive-date=April 3, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> In the 2014 season, Yelich batted .284 with 21 steals out of the leadoff spot for the Miami Marlins.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fialkov|first1=Harvey|title=Christian Yelich returning to form|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/fl-miami-marlins-news-0704-20150703-story.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=July 3, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826005710/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/fl-miami-marlins-news-0704-20150703-story.html|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He also won a [[Gold Glove Award]] in left field, becoming the franchise's youngest ever player and first outfielder to win the award.<ref>{{cite news|last1=De Nicola|first1=Christina|title=Marlins left fielder Christian Yelich wins NL Gold Glove|url=http://www.foxsports.com/florida/story/miami-marlins-christian-yelich-gold-glove-110414|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=Fox Sports|date=November 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160816150004/http://www.foxsports.com/florida/story/miami-marlins-christian-yelich-gold-glove-110414|archive-date=August 16, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Navarro|first1=Manny|title=Miami Marlins outfielder Christian Yelich wins Gold Glove|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article3562951.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Miami Herald|date=November 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807023144/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article3562951.html|archive-date=August 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich first Marlins outfielder to win Gold Glove|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/100564712/christian-yelich-first-marlins-outfielder-to-win-gold-glove|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=November 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20141109110105/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/100564712/christian-yelich-first-marlins-outfielder-to-win-gold-glove|archive-date=November 9, 2014|url-status=live}}</ref> During the season, Yelich set a franchise record for fielding percentage in left field, at .996.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Davis|first1=Craig|title=Marlins' Christian Yelich wins first Gold Glove|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/sfl-christian-yelich-gold-glove-20141104-story.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=November 3, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825235011/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/sfl-christian-yelich-gold-glove-20141104-story.html|archive-date=August 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He served as the final out of [[Jordan Zimmermann]]'s no-hitter on September 28, 2014, when [[Steven Souza Jr.]] made a diving play to save the no-hitter.\n\nYelich and the Marlins finalized a seven-year, $49.57 million contract extension on March 22, 2015.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Marlins lock up Yelich with seven-year pact|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/114144786/miami-marlins-lock-up-christian-yelich-with-seven-year-pact|accessdate=March 22, 2015|publisher=MLB.com|date=March 22, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150324142716/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/114144786/miami-marlins-lock-up-christian-yelich-with-seven-year-pact|archive-date=March 24, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> He struggled to start the season, and was placed on the disabled list in April with lower back strain before making his return on May 8.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Navarro|first1=Manny|title=Miami Marlins left fielder Christian Yelich placed on disabled list|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article19426680.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Miami Herald|date=April 24, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807061034/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article19426680.html|archive-date=August 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|title=Marlins activate LF Christian Yelich off DL; Reid Brignac sent down|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/sfl-marlins-activate-christian-yelich-20150508-story.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=May 8, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160826001930/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/sfl-marlins-activate-christian-yelich-20150508-story.html|archive-date=August 26, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> His batting average reached a season low of .178 on May 22.<ref name=\"hotfinish\">{{cite news|last1=D'Angelo|first1=Tom|title=After hot 2015 finish, Christian Yelich doesn't want another cold start|url=http://www.mypalmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/after-hot-2015-finish-christian-yelich-doesnt-want/nqWFP/|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Palm Beach Post|date=February 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160917225114/http://www.mypalmbeachpost.com/news/sports/baseball/after-hot-2015-finish-christian-yelich-doesnt-want/nqWFP/|archive-date=September 17, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> In August, Yelich bruised his right knee and was again placed on the disabled list.<ref>{{cite news|title=Miami Marlins put Christian Yelich on disabled list|url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-0816-baseball-notes-20150816-story.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Los Angeles Times|agency=Associated Press|date=August 15, 2015|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20160817024711/http://www.latimes.com/sports/la-sp-0816-baseball-notes-20150816-story.html|archivedate=August 17, 2016|via=ESPN.com|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich had improved from his earlier offensive struggles and was hitting .275/.343/.376 with six home runs, 29 RBIs and 14 stolen bases up to that point in the season.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Wilaj|first1=Steve|title=Yelich day to day with right knee injury|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/142520112/christian-yelich-has-right-knee-contusion|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 11, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Knee swelling continues to hamper Yelich|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/143163360/swollen-knee-keeping-christian-yelich-out|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 14, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151222175521/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/143163360/swollen-knee-keeping-christian-yelich-out|archive-date=December 22, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Despite aggravating the injury shortly after his return, Yelich remained an active player for the quality of his bat.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=No DL stint, but Yelich likely to miss rest of trip|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/145955664/christian-yelich-likely-out-rest-of-road-trip|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=August 28, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151227232732/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/145955664/christian-yelich-likely-out-rest-of-road-trip|archive-date=December 27, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich to be handled carefully after pinch-hit|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/146348972/christian-yelich-limited-to-pinch-hitting|accessdate=July 3, 2016|date=August 30, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151229003228/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/146348972/christian-yelich-limited-to-pinch-hitting|archive-date=December 29, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Near the end of the season, Yelich shared the field with [[Marcell Ozuna]], the outfielder who had replaced him during his second stint on the disabled list.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich, Ozuna beginning to click for Marlins|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146947282/marlins-begin-to-see-what-yelich-ozuna-can-do|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=September 2, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20151230103450/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/146947282/marlins-begin-to-see-what-yelich-ozuna-can-do|archive-date=December 30, 2015|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich closed the 2015 season with a .300 average.<ref name=\"hotfinish\"/> For the season, he had the highest [[ground ball]] percentage (62.5%), and the lowest [[Fly ball (baseball)|fly ball]] percentage (15.0%), of all major league hitters.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2016&month=0&season1=2016&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=6,d |title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2016 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Batted Ball Statistics {{!}} FanGraphs Baseball<!-- Bot generated title --> |access-date=December 21, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181222082041/https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2016&month=0&season1=2016&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&sort=6,d |archive-date=December 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYelich was projected to bat third to start 2016.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Fernandez|first1=Andre C.|title=Marlins' Christian Yelich 'excited' about starting fresh in 2016|url=http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article69344317.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Miami Herald|date=March 31, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160807061908/http://www.miamiherald.com/sports/mlb/miami-marlins/article69344317.html|archive-date=August 7, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> He hit well in that spot, and managed to increase his power output.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich's power surfacing as No. 3 hitter|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/184732822/marlins-christian-yelich-homers-vs-rockies|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=June 18, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160619141418/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/184732822/marlins-christian-yelich-homers-vs-rockies|archive-date=June 19, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Putterman|first1=Alex|title=Yelich finding pop in his bat this season|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/178140460/marlins-christian-yelich-hits-homer-vs-nats|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 14, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160521231919/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/178140460/marlins-christian-yelich-hits-homer-vs-nats|archive-date=May 21, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> On April 23, in a game against the [[San Francisco Giants]], Yelich hit three doubles, which tied a franchise record.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich's double trio not enough for Marlins|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/174038822/marlins-christian-yelich-hits-3-doubles|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=April 23, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160424112712/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/174038822/marlins-christian-yelich-hits-3-doubles|archive-date=April 24, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Defensively, Yelich was a starting outfielder, alongside Ozuna and [[Giancarlo Stanton]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Bloom|first1=Barry M.|title=Tough for Ichiro to crack Marlins' talented outfield|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/172146164/young-marlins-outfield-keeping-ichiro-on-bench|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=April 13, 2016}}</ref> In late May, Yelich missed some time due to back spasms.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Ichiro, 42, wows with 4 hits in Marlins' win|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/179456806/ichiro-suzuki-has-4-hits-in-marlins-win|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160525211041/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/179456806/ichiro-suzuki-has-4-hits-in-marlins-win|archive-date=May 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich, Giancarlo not being rushed back|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/180572940/marlins-yelich-giancarlo-stanton-are-better|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=May 22, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160529111739/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/180572940/marlins-yelich-giancarlo-stanton-are-better|archive-date=May 29, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> After Stanton was placed on the disabled list, Ozuna played Stanton's usual position in right field, while Yelich took Ozuna's spot in center on days that backup outfielder [[Ichiro Suzuki]] was unavailable.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Healey|first1=Tim|title=Marlins option Brian Ellington to New Orleans to activate A.J. Ramos|url=http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/fl-marlins-news-0822-20160821-story.html|accessdate=August 27, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=August 21, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160915164420/http://www.sun-sentinel.com/sports/miami-marlins/fl-marlins-news-0822-20160821-story.html|archive-date=September 15, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\n====Milwaukee Brewers====\nOn January 25, 2018, the Marlins traded Yelich to the [[Milwaukee Brewers]] for [[Lewis Brinson]], [[Isan D\u00edaz]], [[Monte Harrison]], and [[Jordan Yamamoto]].<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/22214491/miami-marlins-trade-outfielder-christian-yelich-milwaukee-brewers|title=Brewers acquire OF Christian Yelich from rebuilding Marlins|work=ESPN.com|date=January 25, 2018|accessdate=January 25, 2018|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180126001422/http://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/22214491/miami-marlins-trade-outfielder-christian-yelich-milwaukee-brewers|archive-date=January 26, 2018|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich was named to the [[2018 MLB All-Star Game]] after batting .285 with 11 home runs, 36 RBIs, and 11 stolen bases.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://host.madison.com/wsj/sports/baseball/professional/lorenzo-cain-christian-yelich-and-josh-hader-selected-to-nl/article_e532d30e-eb7e-5eef-8b26-648e9504f023.html |title=Lorenzo Cain, Christian Yelich, Josh Hader selected to All-Star Game; Jesus Aguilar needs fans' votes |first=Andrew |last=Wagner |newspaper=[[Wisconsin State Journal]] |via=madison.com |date=July 9, 2018 |access-date=July 11, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180712025425/https://host.madison.com/wsj/sports/baseball/professional/lorenzo-cain-christian-yelich-and-josh-hader-selected-to-nl/article_e532d30e-eb7e-5eef-8b26-648e9504f023.html |archive-date=July 12, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> Yelich, a reserve for the [[National League]], replaced [[Matt Kemp]] in left field and went 1-for-3, hitting a solo home run in an 8\u20136 extra-inning loss to the [[American League]]. On August 29, Yelich [[hitting for the cycle|hit for the cycle]] against the [[Cincinnati Reds]], collecting a total of six hits in the game.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-for-cycle-against-reds/c-292511126 |title=Yelich completes cycle with game-tying triple |first=Adam |last=McCalvy |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=August 29, 2018 |accessdate=August 29, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180830033556/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-for-cycle-against-reds/c-292511126 |archive-date=August 30, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 2, Yelich hit his first career [[grand slam (baseball)|grand slam]], in a game against the [[Washington Nationals]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-first-career-slam-in-win/c-293018914 |title=Yelich hits 1st career slam as Crew takes series |first=Adam |last=McCalvy |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 2, 2018 |accessdate=September 2, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180903013513/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-first-career-slam-in-win/c-293018914 |archive-date=September 3, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On September 17, Yelich hit for the cycle, also against the [[Cincinnati Reds]], for the second time in 19 days, becoming the fifth player in MLB history to hit two cycles in the same season and the first player in MLB history to do so against the same team.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-for-2nd-cycle-of-season/c-294990668 |title=Yelich's historic bi-cycle vs. Reds fuels Crew |first=Adam |last=McCalvy |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=September 17, 2018 |accessdate=September 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180919133946/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-hits-for-2nd-cycle-of-season/c-294990668 |archive-date=September 19, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nYelich finished the 2018 season with a .326/.402/.598 [[slash line]], 36 homers, and 110 RBIs, winning the first [[List of Major League Baseball batting champions|NL batting title]] in Brewers history, while narrowly falling short of a [[Triple Crown (baseball)|triple crown]].<ref>{{cite web |last1=McCalvy |first1=Adam |title=Yelich wins batting title, falls shy of Triple Crown |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-falls-short-of-triple-crown/c-296663648 |website=MLB |publisher=MLB Advanced Media |accessdate=October 1, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001232703/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-falls-short-of-triple-crown/c-296663648 |archive-date=October 1, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |last1=Haudricourt |first1=Tom |title=Christian Yelich gets an extra day to shoot for first Triple Crown in NL in 81 years |url=https://www.jsonline.com/story/sports/mlb/brewers/2018/09/30/brewers-christian-yelich-gets-extra-game-go-nl-triple-crown/1478754002/ |website=Journal Sentinel |publisher=The Milwaukee Journal Sentinel |accessdate=October 1, 2018}}</ref> He also was 2nd in the league in [[power-speed number]] (27.3).<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/2018-batting-leaders.shtml |title=2018 National League Batting Leaders |website=Baseball-Reference.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190125004512/https://www.baseball-reference.com/leagues/NL/2018-batting-leaders.shtml |archive-date=January 25, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>  On October 26, Yelich was announced as the National League recipient of the annual [[Hank Aaron Award]].<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/aaron-winners-jd-martinez-christian-yelich/c-299746010 |title=J.D., Yelich named 2018 Aaron Award winners |first=Anthony |last=Castrovince |website=[[MLB.com]] |date=October 26, 2018 |accessdate=October 26, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181027040836/https://www.mlb.com/news/aaron-winners-jd-martinez-christian-yelich/c-299746010 |archive-date=October 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref> On November 16, Yelich was named [[Major League Baseball Most Valuable Player Award|Most Valuable Player]] of the National League, falling one vote shy of a unanimous selection.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-wins-2018-nl-mvp-award/c-300793484 |title=Yelich crowned MVP in first year with Crew |last=McCalvy |first=Adam |date=November 16, 2018 |publisher=MLB.com |access-date=November 18, 2018 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181122111930/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-wins-2018-nl-mvp-award/c-300793484 |archive-date=November 22, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 31, 2019, Yelich became the sixth player in MLB history to hit a home run in each of his team's first four games.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-homers-in-four-straight-games |title=Yelich's HR in 4th straight game ties record |last=McCalvy |first=Adam |date=March 31, 2019 |publisher=MLB.com |access-date=March 31, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190331203206/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-homers-in-four-straight-games |archive-date=March 31, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn July 1, 2019, Yelich became the first player in Brewers franchise history to reach 30 home runs before the All-Star Break, beating former Brewer [[Prince Fielder]]'s record of 29 home runs.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.foxsports.com/wisconsin/story/christian-yelich-hits-30th-homer-milwaukee-brewers-top-reds-8-6-070119 |title=Yelich hits 30th homer, Brewers top Reds 8-6 |date=July 1, 2019 |publisher=FOXSports.com |access-date=July 3, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190704043522/https://www.foxsports.com/wisconsin/story/christian-yelich-hits-30th-homer-milwaukee-brewers-top-reds-8-6-070119 |archive-date=July 4, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> Yelich was selected to participate in the Home Run Derby but had to withdraw due to a back injury. He was replaced by [[Matt Chapman]] in the Home Run Derby. On September 10, 2019, Yelich hit a foul ball off his kneecap and left the game.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-exits-with-knee-injury|title=Yelich out for season after fracturing kneecap|website=MLB.com|date=September 11, 2019|access-date=September 11, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190911214530/https://www.mlb.com/news/christian-yelich-exits-with-knee-injury|archive-date=September 11, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> Shortly thereafter, it was revealed that his right kneecap was fractured, which prematurely ended his 2019 season.\n\nIn 2019, Yelich won his second National League batting title. He batted .329/.429 (leading the NL)/.671 (leading the major leagues) with a 1.100 [[On-base plus slugging|OPS]] (leading the majors), 44 home runs (4th in the NL), 11.1 at bats per home runs (leading the league), a .342 [[Isolated Power|ISO]] (leading the NL), 30 stolen bases (3rd), a 93.75 stolen base percentage (3rd), and 97 RBIs in 130 games.<ref name=\"WTMJ News\">{{cite news |last1=Sorgi |first1=Jay |title=Brewers' Christian Yelich clinches second National League batting title |url=http://www.wtmj.com/sports/baseball/milwaukee-brewers/brewers-christian-yelich-clinches-second-national-league-batting-title/1126765172 |accessdate=30 September 2019 |publisher=WTMJ News |date=29 September 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190930034841/http://www.wtmj.com/sports/baseball/milwaukee-brewers/brewers-christian-yelich-clinches-second-national-league-batting-title/1126765172 |archive-date=September 30, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=1&season=2019&month=0&season1=2019&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&startdate=2019-01-01&enddate=2019-12-31&sort=11,d |title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2019 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Advanced Statistics &#124; FanGraphs Baseball |publisher=Fangraphs.com |date=2019-01-01 |accessdate=2019-10-07}}</ref> He had the highest Hard Contact Percentage of all National League batters, at 50.8%.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2019&month=0&season1=2019&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&startdate=2019-01-01&enddate=2019-12-31&sort=19,d |title=Major League Leaderboards \u00bb 2019 \u00bb Batters \u00bb Batted Ball Statistics &#124; FanGraphs Baseball |publisher=Fangraphs.com |date=2019-01-01 |accessdate=2019-10-07 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191229083640/https://www.fangraphs.com/leaders.aspx?pos=all&stats=bat&lg=all&qual=y&type=2&season=2019&month=0&season1=2019&ind=0&team=0&rost=0&age=0&filter=&players=0&startdate=2019-01-01&enddate=2019-12-31&sort=19,d |archive-date=December 29, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref> He won the NL [[Hank Aaron Award]] for the second year in a row<ref>{{citeweb|url=https://www.mlb.com/news/mike-trout-christian-yelich-win-aaron-award|title=Mike Trout, Christian Yelich win Aaron award|website=MLB.com|date=October 23, 2019|accessdate=November 19, 2019|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191119091103/https://www.mlb.com/news/mike-trout-christian-yelich-win-aaron-award|archive-date=November 19, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref> and finished second in NL MVP voting.<ref>{{Cite web |url=https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-mvp-award-vote-totals |title=Archived copy |access-date=November 19, 2019 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20191115133447/https://www.mlb.com/news/2019-mvp-award-vote-totals |archive-date=November 15, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn March 6, 2020, Yelich signed a nine-year, $215&nbsp;million contract extension with the Brewers.<ref>https://www.jsonline.com/story/sports/mlb/brewers/2020/03/06/brewers-make-official-signing-christian-yelich-nine-years/4967961002/</ref>\n\n==International career==\n\nYelich played for the [[United States national baseball team]] in the [[2017 World Baseball Classic]].  Following the conclusion of the tournament, he was named to the [[2017 World Baseball Classic#2017 All-World Baseball Classic team|All-World Baseball Classic team]].<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/world-baseball-classic-previous-champs-results-medal-count-mvps-all-wbc-teams/ |title=World Baseball Classic: Previous champs, results, medal count, MVPs, All-WBC teams |last=Perry |first=Dayn |website=CBSSports.com |language=en |access-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180627230644/https://www.cbssports.com/mlb/news/world-baseball-classic-previous-champs-results-medal-count-mvps-all-wbc-teams/ |archive-date=June 27, 2018 |url-status=live }}</ref>\n\nOn September 10, 2018, he was selected to play with the MLB All-Stars at the [[2018 MLB Japan All-Star Series]],<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.mlbplayers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=34000&ATCLID=211771396 | title=Eight Players Selected for Japan All-Star Series | work=The Official Site of Major League Baseball Players Association | date=September 10, 2018 | accessdate=September 12, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20180912054652/http://www.mlbplayers.com/ViewArticle.dbml?DB_OEM_ID=34000&ATCLID=211771396 | archive-date=September 12, 2018 | url-status=dead }}</ref> but he later withdrew from the event.<ref>{{cite web | url=http://www.japan-baseball.jp/jp/news/press/20181029_3.html | title=2018\u65e5\u7c73\u91ce\u7403 MLB\u30aa\u30fc\u30eb\u30b9\u30bf\u30fc\u30c1\u30fc\u30e0\u51fa\u5834\u4e88\u5b9a\u9078\u624b\u306e\u8f9e\u9000\u306b\u3064\u3044\u3066 | work=\u91ce\u7403\u65e5\u672c\u4ee3\u8868 \u4f8d\u30b8\u30e3\u30d1\u30f3 \u30aa\u30d5\u30a3\u30b7\u30e3\u30eb\u30b5\u30a4\u30c8 | language=Japanese | date=October 29, 2018 | accessdate=December 5, 2018 | archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20181102084519/http://www.japan-baseball.jp/jp/news/press/20181029_3.html | archive-date=November 2, 2018 | url-status=live }}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nYelich appeared in an episode of ''[[Magnum P.I. (2018 TV series)|Magnum P.I.]]'' that aired on March 4, 2019. Yelich once invited [[Cleveland Browns]] quarterback and 2017 [[Heisman Trophy]] winner [[Baker Mayfield]] to Brewers batting practice.<ref>{{Cite news|url=https://theathletic.com/871269/2019/03/15/christian-yelich-brought-a-friend-to-brewers-batting-practice-baker-mayfield/|title=Christian Yelich brought a friend to Brewers batting practice: Baker Mayfield|last=Murray|first=Robert|date=March 15, 2019|work=The Athletic|access-date=|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190401003346/https://theathletic.com/871269/2019/03/15/christian-yelich-brought-a-friend-to-brewers-batting-practice-baker-mayfield/|archive-date=April 1, 2019|url-status=live}}</ref>\n\nYelich's maternal great-grandfather was [[American football]] player [[Fred Gehrke]].<ref name=\"pbp\"/> An uncle, Chris Yelich, played football for the [[UCLA Bruins football|UCLA Bruins]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Rodriguez|first1=Juan C.|title=Marlins notes: Yelich branches off family football tree|url=http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2014-03-04/sports/fl-marlins-0305-20140304_1_christian-yelich-reeves-pioneer-award-fred-gehrke|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Sun Sentinel|date=March 4, 2014|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160825221131/http://articles.sun-sentinel.com/2014-03-04/sports/fl-marlins-0305-20140304_1_christian-yelich-reeves-pioneer-award-fred-gehrke|archive-date=August 25, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Yelich is the oldest of three children; his brothers are Collin and Cameron.<ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Yelich shares his favorite holiday memories|url=http://m.mlb.com/news/article/66109836/|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=December 23, 2013|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160814175618/http://m.mlb.com/news/article/66109836/|archive-date=August 14, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> Collin was selected by the [[Atlanta Braves]] in the [[2015 Major League Baseball draft]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Andrade|first1=Jonathan|title=Yelich is a name to remember|url=http://www.toacorn.com/news/2015-07-23/Sports/Yelich_is_a_name_to_remember.html|accessdate=July 3, 2016|work=Thousand Oaks Acorn|date=July 23, 2015|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20161013175006/http://www.toacorn.com/news/2015-07-23/Sports/Yelich_is_a_name_to_remember.html|archive-date=October 13, 2016|url-status=dead}}</ref> Cameron is a [[United States Marine]].<ref>{{cite news|last1=Strang|first1=Katie|title=Marlins with military ties look forward to 'perfect weekend' at Fort Bragg|url=http://espn.go.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/71913/marlins-braves-look-forward-to-perfect-weekend-at-fort-bragg|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=ESPN.com|date=July 2, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160703115207/http://espn.go.com/blog/sweetspot/post/_/id/71913/marlins-braves-look-forward-to-perfect-weekend-at-fort-bragg|archive-date=July 3, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|last1=Frisaro|first1=Joe|title=Fort Bragg trip hits home for Yelich|url=http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/186893018/christian-yelich-honored-to-play-at-fort-bragg|accessdate=July 3, 2016|publisher=MLB.com|date=June 29, 2016|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20160702062156/http://m.marlins.mlb.com/news/article/186893018/christian-yelich-honored-to-play-at-fort-bragg|archive-date=July 2, 2016|url-status=live}}</ref> His paternal grandfather was [[Serbs|Serbian]] while his maternal grandfather was [[Japanese_people|Japanese]].\n\nYelich grew up both a [[Los Angeles Dodgers]] fan and a [[New York Yankees]] fan.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.latimes.com/sports/mlb/la-sp-baseball-milwaukee-brewers-20180324-story.html |title=Christian Yelich's outfielder talents could lift Brewers while Dodgers miss out |date=2018-03-24 |website=Los Angeles Times |language=en-US |access-date=2019-07-18 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20190412183525/https://www.latimes.com/sports/mlb/la-sp-baseball-milwaukee-brewers-20180324-story.html |archive-date=April 12, 2019 |url-status=live }}</ref><ref>{{cite web |url=https://www.espn.com/mlb/story/_/id/28844157/christian-yelich-cody-bellinger-walk-bar |title=\nHang Time: Christian Yelich and Cody Bellinger walk into a bar |date=March 6, 2020 |website=ESPN |language=en-US |access-date=March 7, 2020}}</ref>\n\n==See also==\n{{Portal|Baseball}}\n* [[List of Major League Baseball single-game hits leaders]]\n* [[List of Major League Baseball players to hit for the cycle]]\n\n==References==\n{{reflist|30em}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commonscat|Christian Yelich}}\n{{baseballstats|espn=31283|fangraphs=11477|mlb=592885|br=y/yelicch01|brm=yelich001chr|retro=Y/Pyelic001}}\n*{{twitter}}\n*{{instagram|christianyelich|christianyelich}}\n:<br>\n\n{{s-start}}\n{{s-ach|ach}}\n{{succession box| before = [[Mookie Betts]] | title = [[Hitting for the cycle]]| years = August 29, 2018 | after = himself}}\n{{Succession box| before = himself | title = [[Hitting for the cycle]]| years = September 17, 2018 | after = [[Charlie Blackmon]]}}\n{{s-end}}\n\n{{2010 MLB Draft}}\n{{Miami Marlins first-round draft picks}}\n{{NL MVPs}}\n{{NL batting title}}\n{{NL OF Gold Glove Award}}\n{{NL OF Silver Slugger Award}}\n{{NL Hank Aaron Award Winners}}\n{{2019 All MLB Team}}\n{{United States roster 2017 World Baseball Classic}}\n{{2017 World Baseball Classic All WBC Team}}\n{{Milwaukee Brewers roster navbox}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Yelich, Christian}}\n\n[[Category:1991 births]]\n[[Category:2017 World Baseball Classic players]]\n[[Category:American baseball players of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:American people of German descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Serbian descent]]\n[[Category:American people of Japanese descent]]\n[[Category:Baseball players from California]]\n[[Category:Gold Glove Award winners]]\n[[Category:Greensboro Grasshoppers players]]\n[[Category:Gulf Coast Marlins players]]\n[[Category:Jacksonville Suns players]]\n[[Category:Jupiter Hammerheads players]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Major League Baseball left fielders]]\n[[Category:Miami Marlins players]]\n[[Category:Milwaukee Brewers players]]\n[[Category:National League batting champions]]\n[[Category:National League Most Valuable Player Award winners]]\n[[Category:New Orleans Zephyrs players]]\n[[Category:People from Thousand Oaks, California]]\n[[Category:Phoenix Desert Dogs players]]\n[[Category:Silver Slugger Award winners]]\n[[Category:Sportspeople from Ventura County, California]]\n", "name_user": "68.191.147.226", "label": "unsafe", "comment": "(\u2192\u200eAmateur career)", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Christian_Yelich"}
{"title_page": "Gem (radio station)", "text_new": "{{short description|Radio station in the East Midlands, England}}\n{{about|the FM regional station for the East Midlands|the station formed from Leicester Sound and Radio Trent's AM transmitters between 1988 and 2007|Classic Gold GEM}}\n{{Radio station\n| image        = Gem 106 logo.png\n| image_size   = 175px\n| name         = Gem\n| airdate      = \n| frequency    = 106.0FM\n| area         = [[East Midlands]] \n| format       = [[Hot AC]]\n| slogan       = ''The Biggest Hits, The Biggest Throwbacks''\n| owner        = [[Bauer Radio]]\n| website      = [https://planetradio.co.uk/gem-106 Gem]\n|city=Nottingham|coordinates=}}\n\n'''Gem''' is an English regional [[radio station]] broadcasting to the [[East Midlands]], owned and operated by [[Bauer Radio]] and forms part of the [[Hits Radio]] network. The station is transmitted from the [[Copt Oak]] transmitter close to the [[M1 motorway|M1]] north of [[Leicester]] in the [[National Forest, England|National Forest]]. \n\n==History==\n===Radio 106===\nRadio 106 launched at 6{{nbsp}}am on Tuesday 23 September 1997. Billed as ''Radio for Grown Ups'', with an advertising campaign on Central TV for the launch, And an episode of Central TV\u2019s \u201824 hours\u2019 in 1998 documented the launch and the relaunch of the station, The new regional station was led by ex-Radio Trent managing director Ron Coles with former [[Centre Radio]] MD Ken Warburton as programming controller. The first presenter on air was Dickie Dodd.\n\nRadio 106's launch schedule included a heavy emphasis on speech content, including daily guests on mid-morning shows and a nightly 3-hour phone-in. Specialist music output featured country, soul and motown at weekends. The station's launch team included Kevin Fernihough, Mark Keen, Willie Morgan, Kenny Hague, Jake Yapp, Peter King and Sarah Graham.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.justin-case.co.uk/simon/keen.htm | title = Mark Keen information | accessdate = 2010-05-17}}</ref>\n\nAgainst competition from established [[BBC Local Radio]] and [[GWR Group|GWR]]-owned commercial stations, Radio 106 recorded poor listening figures for its first set of [[RAJAR]] audience figures, so within seven months of launch, the station's owners [[Border Radio Holdings]] opted for a complete relaunch.\n\n===Century 106===\nIn April 1998, [[John Myers (radio executive)|John Myers]] took control of the station, which was rebranded as Century 106 and relaunched with a new team of presenters including [[Adrian Allen]] and Chris Ashley.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ofcom.org.uk/static/archive/rau/radio-stations/analogue/AL200-1.htm | title = Radio Authority Century 106 file | accessdate = 2010-05-17}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Radio Trent]] [[Radio presenter|presenter]] [[David Lloyd (broadcaster)|David Lloyd]] became the station's Managing Director and Programme Controller with ex-Trent colleagues including Tony Lyman, Craig Strong, Gary Burton and Andy Marriott joining the presenting line-up. Other additions to the team included Steve Jordan (breakfast) and Bernie Keith (afternoons).\n\nIn May 2000, Century 106, along with the other Century stations in the North East and North West, were sold to [[Capital Radio]]. David Lloyd left the station to join [[Galaxy 105]] in Leeds while presenter Adrian Allen walked out mid-show in protest. The sale to Capital brought an increase in the station's sports coverage - as emphasised in the slogan ''music, fun and football''. More new presenters joined Century, including Ian Skye, [http://www.jason-king.com Jason King], Stuart Ellis, [[Sam Pinkham]] and Paula White.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.geocities.com/thehotw/aircheck_UKLeics.htm | title = History of radio in East Midlands | accessdate = 2010-05-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022091041/http://geocities.com/thehotw/aircheck_UKLeics.htm| url-status = dead |archivedate=2009-10-22}}</ref>\n\n===Heart 106 ===\nWhen Capital later merged with GWR, the [[Office of Fair Trading]] ordered Century to be sold off. [[Chrysalis Group|Chrysalis]] bought Century 106 for \u00a329.5m and planned to rebrand the station as '''[[Heart 106]]''', to go with [[100.7 Heart FM]] in the West Midlands as the area matched that of the [[ITV Central]] region and would make it more attractive to advertisers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/radio/ifi/rbl/car/ccr/century/century106.pdf |title=Ofcom file: Details of Chrysalis |accessdate=2010-05-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204195411/http://www.ofcom.org.uk/radio/ifi/rbl/car/ccr/century/century106.pdf |archivedate=2008-12-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.brandrepublic.com/News/474452/Chrysalis-acquires-106-Century-FM-GCap-begins-trading-downbeat-note/?DCMP=ILC-SEARCH | title = Ofcom file: Details of Chrysalis | accessdate = 2010-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.justin-case.co.uk/simon/lrfm.htm | title = Simon's Midlands FM Radio Stations | accessdate = 2010-05-18}}</ref>\n\nHeart 106 was launched on 29 August 2005. A further, more subtle rebrand was applied in September 2006 which saw the dropping of the frequencies from station names across the [[Heart Network]].\n\nOn 25 June 2007, Chrysalis announced the sale of Heart, along with its sister stations [[The Arrow (radio)|The Arrow]], [[LBC]] and [[Galaxy Radio|Galaxy]], for \u00a3170 million to [[Global Radio]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/money/main.jhtml?xml=/money/2007/06/25/bcnchrys125.xml Chrysalis sells three radio stations]</ref>\n\nFollowing Global's takeover of [[GCap Media]], the Office of Fair Trading again ordered Global to sell off Heart and four other Midlands stations - [[BRMB]], [[Mercia FM]], [[Wyvern FM]] and [[Beacon Radio]]. In May 2009, the stations were sold to [[Orion Media]], a company backed by [[Lloyds Development Capital]] and [[Phil Riley]].\n\n===Gem Radio===\nOn 9 November 2010, Orion Media announced that Heart 106 would be relaunched and renamed as 'Gem 106' on 1 January 2011.<ref>[http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.6448.2 Gem to replace Heart East Mids] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427085151/http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.6448.2 |date=2012-04-27 }}</ref> Under the rebrand, the station ended its franchise agreement with Global Radio which allowed it to use the Heart identity and carry networked programming from London.<ref>[http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/news/Heart-106-local-Gem/article-2859696-detail/article.html Heart 106 to become a local Gem], Nottingham Evening Post, 9 November 2010</ref>\n\nGem 106 was launched at midnight on Saturday 1 January 2011 with a special programme presented by Orion's director of programming and marketing [[David Lloyd (broadcaster)|David Lloyd]]. The GEM name stands for 'Great East Midlands', the name created and used from 1988 onwards for [[GEM-AM]] (later Classic Gold GEM) an AM (medium wave), 'solid gold' secondary service of Radio Trent. The majority of the station's programming is locally produced and broadcast from Nottingham. \n\nAs of March 2016, Gem refreshed their imaging and jingle package using a custom package from Wise Buddah.\n\nOn 6 May 2016, the station's owners, Orion, announced they had been bought by [[Bauer Media Group|Bauer]] for an undisclosed fee, reportedly between \u00a340 and \u00a350 million.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/may/06/bauer-buys-radio-group-orion-media Bauer buys radio group Orion Media], The Guardian, 6 May 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/05/06/orion-media-sold-to-bauer-for-50m/ Orion Media sold to Bauer for \u00a350m], The Telegraph, 6 May 2016</ref> As of August 2016, Gem 106 is aligned with the [[Hits Radio]] network, using its generic on-air imaging package. The station retains its own regional programming throughout the day.<ref>[http://radiotoday.co.uk/2016/08/bauer-puts-network-musical-logo-on-gem-106/ Bauer puts network musical logo on Gem 106], Radio Today, 17 August 2016</ref>\n\nOn 14 August 2018 the station dropped the \"106\" from the FM name and changed the DAB name from \"Gem 106 EastMids\" to just \"Gem\" this was because most radio stations were advertising that they were on smart speakers but when asked to play \"Gem One Oh Six\" they would never find it. So to combat this they changed the website and socials to [https://plantetradio.co.uk/gem-106 PlayGemRadio.com] and [https://twitter.com/PlayGemRadio @PlayGemRadio] so people can find them.\n\nIn July 2019, Gem began taking overnight programming from the [[Hits Radio Network]] in Manchester on Sunday - Thursday nights. The station continues to air local automated output at weekends.<ref>[https://radiotoday.co.uk/2019/07/gem-to-take-hits-radio-strapline-and-night-programmes/ Gem to take Hits Radio strapline and night programmes], Radio Today, 8 July 2019</ref>\n\n==Audience==\nAccording to [[RAJAR]] figures up to June 2016, the station was listened to by 503,000 people (out of a possible 2,384,000 listeners) per week, with each listener tuning in for an average of 7.1 hours over the course of 7 days.\n\n==Programming and presenters==\nThe majority of Gem's programming is produced and broadcast at City Link in Nottingham. Late night and overnight programming on Sunday - Thursday, along with ''The UK Chart Show'' on Sunday afternoons and The Throwback on Sunday evenings, originates from the [[Hits Radio]] network, based in [[Manchester]].\n\nThe station's current presenters include [[Jo Russell]] and Mark 'Sparky' Colerangle (weekday breakfast), [[Dan Wood (broadcaster)|Dan Wood]] (weekday mid-mornings), Cat James (weekday drivetime), Andy Goulding (evenings), Jennie Longdon (''Hits Chilled'' / Saturday mornings) and Iain Chambers (Saturday mornings).\n\n===Notable past presenters===\n<!--Any non-notable presenters (those without Wikipedia articles) added here are liable to be removed - if someone is considered notable (red linking is not enough), please write a Wikipedia article on them first, or provide multiple reputable independent sources to show they deserve an article and are associated with the station. Any presenters with Wikipedia articles also need such sources on this page to stay here.-->\n*[[Sam Pinkham]]\n*[[Sam and Mark|Sam Nixon & Mark Rhodes]]\n*[[Amy Voce]]\n\n===News===\nGem broadcasts regional news bulletins hourly from 6{{nbsp}}am to 7{{nbsp}}pm on weekdays, from 7{{nbsp}}am to 1{{nbsp}}pm on Saturdays and Sundays. Headlines are broadcast on the half hour during weekday breakfast with updates every 20 minutes during weekday drivetime.<ref>[https://planetradio.co.uk/gem-106/public-file/ Gem 106 public file]</ref>\n\nRegional bulletins originate from Gem's Nottingham studios or the [[Free Radio (network)|Free Radio]] Midlands newsroom in Birmingham. National bulletins from [[Sky News Radio]] are carried hourly at all other times, apart from Sunday afternoons.\n\n==Notts TV link-up==\nSince August 2015, Gem 106's weekday breakfast show has been simulcast live on [[Notts TV]] with a live video feed from the studio. As of February 2017, ''Gem Anthems'' on Saturday evenings is also simulcast on the channel.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://planetradio.co.uk/gem-106 Gem]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091022091041/http://geocities.com/thehotw/aircheck_UKLeics.htm History of local radio in Leicestershire]\n\n{{Coord|52.94881|-1.13418|display=title}}\n{{Hits Radio}}\n{{Nottinghamshire radio}}\n\n[[Category:Bauer Radio]]\n[[Category:Hits Radio]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Media in Nottingham]]\n[[Category:Defunct Heart Network stations]]\n", "text_old": "{{short description|Radio station in the East Midlands, England}}\n{{about|the FM regional station for the East Midlands|the station formed from Leicester Sound and Radio Trent's AM transmitters between 1988 and 2007|Classic Gold GEM}}\n{{Radio station\n| image        = Gem 106 logo.png\n| image_size   = 175px\n| name         = Gem\n| airdate      = \n| frequency    = 106.0FM\n| area         = [[East Midlands]] \n| format       = [[Hot AC]]\n| slogan       = ''The Biggest Hits, The Biggest Throwbacks''\n| owner        = [[Bauer Radio]]\n| website      = [https://planetradio.co.uk/gem-106 Gem]\n|city=Nottingham|coordinates=}}\n\n'''Gem''' is an English regional [[radio station]] broadcasting to the [[East Midlands]], owned and operated by [[Bauer Radio]] and forms part of the [[Hits Radio]] network. The station is transmitted from the [[Copt Oak]] transmitter close to the [[M1 motorway|M1]] north of [[Leicester]] in the [[National Forest, England|National Forest]]. \n\n==History==\n===Radio 106===\nRadio 106 launched at 6{{nbsp}}am on Tuesday 23 September 1997. Billed as ''Radio for Grown Ups'', with an advertising campaign on Central TV for the launch, And an episode of Central TV\u2019s \u201824 hours\u2019 in 1998 documented the launch and the relaunch of the station, The new regional station was led by ex-Radio Trent managing director Ron Coles with former [[Centre Radio]] MD Ken Warburton as programming controller. The first presenter on air was Dickie Dodd.\n\nRadio 106's launch schedule included a heavy emphasis on speech content, including daily guests on mid-morning shows and a nightly 3-hour phone-in. Specialist music output featured country, soul and motown at weekends. The station's launch team included Kevin Fernihough, Mark Keen, Willie Morgan, Kenny Hague, Jake Yapp, Peter King and Sarah Graham.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.justin-case.co.uk/simon/keen.htm | title = Mark Keen information | accessdate = 2010-05-17}}</ref>\n\nAgainst competition from established [[BBC Local Radio]] and [[GWR Group|GWR]]-owned commercial stations, Radio 106 recorded poor listening figures for its first set of [[RAJAR]] audience figures, so within seven months of launch, the station's owners [[Border Radio Holdings]] opted for a complete relaunch.\n\n===Century 106===\nIn April 1998, [[John Myers (radio executive)|John Myers]] took control of the station, which was rebranded as Century 106 and relaunched with a new team of presenters including [[Adrian Allen]] and Chris Ashley.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.ofcom.org.uk/static/archive/rau/radio-stations/analogue/AL200-1.htm | title = Radio Authority Century 106 file | accessdate = 2010-05-17}}</ref>\n\nFormer [[Radio Trent]] [[Radio presenter|presenter]] [[David Lloyd (broadcaster)|David Lloyd]] became the station's Managing Director and Programme Controller with ex-Trent colleagues including Tony Lyman, Craig Strong, Gary Burton and Andy Marriott joining the presenting line-up. Other additions to the team included Steve Jordan (breakfast) and Bernie Keith (afternoons).\n\nIn May 2000, Century 106, along with the other Century stations in the North East and North West, were sold to [[Capital Radio]]. David Lloyd left the station to join [[Galaxy 105]] in Leeds while presenter Adrian Allen walked out mid-show in protest. The sale to Capital brought an increase in the station's sports coverage - as emphasised in the slogan ''music, fun and football''. More new presenters joined Century, including Ian Skye, [http://www.jason-king.com Jason King], Stuart Ellis, [[Sam Pinkham]] and Paula White.<ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.geocities.com/thehotw/aircheck_UKLeics.htm | title = History of radio in East Midlands | accessdate = 2010-05-17|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20091022091041/http://geocities.com/thehotw/aircheck_UKLeics.htm| url-status = dead |archivedate=2009-10-22}}</ref>\n\n===Heart 106 ===\nWhen Capital later merged with GWR, the [[Office of Fair Trading]] ordered Century to be sold off. [[Chrysalis Group|Chrysalis]] bought Century 106 for \u00a329.5m and planned to rebrand the station as '''[[Heart 106]]''', to go with [[100.7 Heart FM]] in the West Midlands as the area matched that of the [[ITV Central]] region and would make it more attractive to advertisers.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.ofcom.org.uk/radio/ifi/rbl/car/ccr/century/century106.pdf |title=Ofcom file: Details of Chrysalis |accessdate=2010-05-17 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20081204195411/http://www.ofcom.org.uk/radio/ifi/rbl/car/ccr/century/century106.pdf |archivedate=2008-12-04 }}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.brandrepublic.com/News/474452/Chrysalis-acquires-106-Century-FM-GCap-begins-trading-downbeat-note/?DCMP=ILC-SEARCH | title = Ofcom file: Details of Chrysalis | accessdate = 2010-05-17}}</ref><ref>{{cite web | url = http://www.justin-case.co.uk/simon/lrfm.htm | title = Simon's Midlands FM Radio Stations | accessdate = 2010-05-18}}</ref>\n\nHeart 106 was launched on 29 August 2005. A further, more subtle rebrand was applied in September 2006 which saw the dropping of the frequencies from station names across the [[Heart Network]].\n\nOn 25 June 2007, Chrysalis announced the sale of Heart, along with its sister stations [[The Arrow (radio)|The Arrow]], [[LBC]] and [[Galaxy Radio|Galaxy]], for \u00a3170 million to [[Global Radio]].<ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/money/main.jhtml?xml=/money/2007/06/25/bcnchrys125.xml Chrysalis sells three radio stations]</ref>\n\nFollowing Global's takeover of [[GCap Media]], the Office of Fair Trading again ordered Global to sell off Heart and four other Midlands stations - [[BRMB]], [[Mercia FM]], [[Wyvern FM]] and [[Beacon Radio]]. In May 2009, the stations were sold to [[Orion Media]], a company backed by [[Lloyds Development Capital]] and [[Phil Riley]].\n\n===Gem Radio===\nOn 9 November 2010, Orion Media announced that Heart 106 would be relaunched and renamed as 'Gem 106' on 1 January 2011.<ref>[http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.6448.2 Gem to replace Heart East Mids] {{webarchive|url=https://web.archive.org/web/20120427085151/http://radiotoday.co.uk/news.php?extend.6448.2 |date=2012-04-27 }}</ref> Under the rebrand, the station ended its franchise agreement with Global Radio which allowed it to use the Heart identity and carry networked programming from London.<ref>[http://www.thisisnottingham.co.uk/news/Heart-106-local-Gem/article-2859696-detail/article.html Heart 106 to become a local Gem], Nottingham Evening Post, 9 November 2010</ref>\n\nGem 106 was launched at midnight on Saturday 1 January 2011 with a special programme presented by Orion's director of programming and marketing [[David Lloyd (broadcaster)|David Lloyd]]. The GEM name stands for 'Great East Midlands', the name created and used from 1988 onwards for [[GEM-AM]] (later Classic Gold GEM) an AM (medium wave), 'solid gold' secondary service of Radio Trent. The majority of the station's programming is locally produced and broadcast from Nottingham. \n\nAs of March 2016, Gem refreshed their imaging and jingle package using a custom package from Wise Buddah.\n\nOn 6 May 2016, the station's owners, Orion, announced they had been bought by [[Bauer Media Group|Bauer]] for an undisclosed fee, reportedly between \u00a340 and \u00a350 million.<ref>[https://www.theguardian.com/media/2016/may/06/bauer-buys-radio-group-orion-media Bauer buys radio group Orion Media], The Guardian, 6 May 2016</ref><ref>[https://www.telegraph.co.uk/business/2016/05/06/orion-media-sold-to-bauer-for-50m/ Orion Media sold to Bauer for \u00a350m], The Telegraph, 6 May 2016</ref> As of August 2016, Gem 106 is aligned with the [[Hits Radio]] network, using its generic on-air imaging package. The station retains its own regional programming throughout the day.<ref>[http://radiotoday.co.uk/2016/08/bauer-puts-network-musical-logo-on-gem-106/ Bauer puts network musical logo on Gem 106], Radio Today, 17 August 2016</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Gem began taking overnight programming from the [[Hits Radio Network]] in Manchester on Sunday - Thursday nights. The station continues to air local automated output at weekends.<ref>[https://radiotoday.co.uk/2019/07/gem-to-take-hits-radio-strapline-and-night-programmes/ Gem to take Hits Radio strapline and night programmes], Radio Today, 8 July 2019</ref>\n\n==Audience==\nAccording to [[RAJAR]] figures up to June 2016, the station was listened to by 503,000 people (out of a possible 2,384,000 listeners) per week, with each listener tuning in for an average of 7.1 hours over the course of 7 days.\n\n==Programming and presenters==\nThe majority of Gem's programming is produced and broadcast at City Link in Nottingham. Late night and overnight programming on Sunday - Thursday, along with ''The UK Chart Show'' on Sunday afternoons and The Throwback on Sunday evenings, originates from the [[Hits Radio]] network, based in [[Manchester]].\n\nThe station's current presenters include [[Jo Russell]] and Mark 'Sparky' Colerangle (weekday breakfast), [[Dan Wood (broadcaster)|Dan Wood]] (weekday mid-mornings), Cat James (weekday drivetime), Andy Goulding (evenings), Jennie Longdon (''Hits Chilled'' / Saturday mornings) and Iain Chambers (Saturday mornings).\n\n===Notable past presenters===\n<!--Any non-notable presenters (those without Wikipedia articles) added here are liable to be removed - if someone is considered notable (red linking is not enough), please write a Wikipedia article on them first, or provide multiple reputable independent sources to show they deserve an article and are associated with the station. Any presenters with Wikipedia articles also need such sources on this page to stay here.-->\n*[[Sam Pinkham]]\n*[[Sam and Mark|Sam Nixon & Mark Rhodes]]\n*[[Amy Voce]]\n\n===News===\nGem broadcasts regional news bulletins hourly from 6{{nbsp}}am to 7{{nbsp}}pm on weekdays, from 7{{nbsp}}am to 1{{nbsp}}pm on Saturdays and Sundays. Headlines are broadcast on the half hour during weekday breakfast with updates every 20 minutes during weekday drivetime.<ref>[https://planetradio.co.uk/gem-106/public-file/ Gem 106 public file]</ref>\n\nRegional bulletins originate from Gem's Nottingham studios or the [[Free Radio (network)|Free Radio]] Midlands newsroom in Birmingham. National bulletins from [[Sky News Radio]] are carried hourly at all other times, apart from Sunday afternoons.\n\n==Notts TV link-up==\nSince August 2015, Gem 106's weekday breakfast show has been simulcast live on [[Notts TV]] with a live video feed from the studio. As of February 2017, ''Gem Anthems'' on Saturday evenings is also simulcast on the channel.\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* [https://planetradio.co.uk/gem-106 Gem]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20091022091041/http://geocities.com/thehotw/aircheck_UKLeics.htm History of local radio in Leicestershire]\n\n{{Coord|52.94881|-1.13418|display=title}}\n{{Hits Radio}}\n{{Nottinghamshire radio}}\n\n[[Category:Bauer Radio]]\n[[Category:Hits Radio]]\n[[Category:Radio stations in Nottinghamshire]]\n[[Category:Radio stations established in 1997]]\n[[Category:Media in Nottingham]]\n[[Category:Defunct Heart Network stations]]\n", "name_user": "R.Button", "label": "safe", "comment": "Added about the name and website changes", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Gem_(radio_station)"}
{"title_page": "Raigad Fort", "text_new": "{{For|the town in Chhattisgarh|Raigarh}}\n{{distinguish|Rajgad Fort}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = Raigad Fort\n| partof =\n| location = [[Raigad District]], [[Maharashtra]]<br />(near [[Mahad]])\n| image = Raigad fort towers.jpg\n| caption = Raigad Fort towers\n| pushpin_map =India Maharashtra#India\n| pushpin_mapsize =300\n| pushpin_map_caption =Shown within [[Maharashtra]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|18.2335|73.4406|type:landmark_region:IN-MH|format=dms|display=inline}}\n| type = Hill fort\n| code =\n| height = {{convert|1356|m|ft|-2}} ASL\n| ownership = \n*[[Maratha Empire]] (1656-1689; 1707-1818)\n*[[Mughal Empire]] (1689-1707)\n*[[British East India Company]] (1818-1858)\n*[[British Empire]] (1858-1947)\n*[[Government of India|Central Government]] of (1947-present)\n\n| open_to_public = Yes\n| condition =\n| built =\n| builder =  Hiroji Indulkar\n| used =\n| materials = Stone, Lead\n| demolished =\n| battles =\n| current_commander =\n| past_commanders = [[Chhtrapati Shivaji]], [[Chhtrapati Sambhaji]]\n| occupants = \n| events =\n}}\n\n'''Raigad''' ([[Marathi language|Marathi]]:\u0930\u093e\u092f\u0917\u0921) is a [[hill fort]] situated in [[Mahad]], [[Raigad district]] of [[Maharashtra]], India. The Raigad Fort, formerly known as Rairi, was built by Chandraraoji More, the King of Jawali, who was then seized by  [[Shivaji]] who made it his capital in 1674 when he was crowned the King of a Maratha Kingdom which later developed into the [[Maratha Empire]], eventually covering much of western and central India.<ref name=imp>{{cite web | title =Raigarh |publisher=[[Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Volume 21|pages= 47\u201348|year=1909| url = http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V21_053.gif| accessdate = 2014-02-19 }}</ref>\n\nThe fort rises {{convert|820|m|ft|-2}} above the sea level and is located in the [[Sahyadri]] mountain range. There are approximately 1737 steps leading to the fort. The [[Raigad Ropeway]], an [[aerial tramway]]  exists to reach the top of the fort in 10 minutes. The fort was looted and destroyed by the British after it was captured in 1818.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Ghats from Ryghur.jpg|thumb|left|The Ghats from Ryghur]]\n\n[[Shivaji]]Maharaj seized the fort in 1656, then known as the fort of ''Rairi'' from Chandraraoji More, The King of Jawali. Chhtrapati Shivaji Maharaj renovated and expanded the fort of Rairi and renamed it as Raigad (''King's Fort''). It became the capital of Chhtrapati Shivaji Maharaj's Maratha Empire.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nThe villages of Pachad and Raigadwadi are located at the base of the Raigad fort. These two villages were considered very important during the Maratha rule in Raigad. The actual climb to the top of the Raigad fort starts from Pachad. During Shivaji Maharaj's rule, A cavalry of 10,000 was always kept on standby in Pachad village. {{citation needed|date=July 2017}}Chhtrapati Shivaji Maharaj also built another fort [[Lingana]] around 2 miles away from Raigad. The Lingana fort was used to keep prisoners.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n[[File:Raigad 1896.jpg|thumb|Raigad 1896]]\n\nIn 1689, Zulfikhar Khan captured Raigad and Aurangzeb renamed it as ''Islamgad''. In 1707, Siddi Fathekan captured the fort and held it until 1733.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Naravane|first1=M.S.|title=The maritime and coastal forts of India|date=1998|publisher=APH Pub. Corp.|location=New Delhi|isbn=9788170249108|page=61|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=siddi+raigad+1707&ots=S0VQPZLLnm&sig=9hL2_AZ9l4MfdvzsZhtVWp4QKZY#v=onepage&q=siddi&f=false}}</ref>\n\nIn 1765, The fort of Raigad along with [[Malwan]] in present [[Sindhudurg District]], the southernmost district of [[Maharashtra]], was the target of an armed expedition by the [[East India Company|British East India Company]], which considered it a [[pirate|piratical]] stronghold.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nIn 1818, the fort was bombarded and destroyed by cannons from the hill of Kalkai. And on 9 May 1818, as per the treaty, it was handed over to the [[East India Company|British East India Company]].{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n==Major features==\n\n[[File:Raigad fort walls hidden in the green.JPG|Hidden Walls of the Raigad Fort|thumb|right]]\n[[File:RaigadFort1.jpg|Raigad Fort Palace Ruins|thumb|right]]\n\nThe Raigad Fort was built by [[Shivaji]], Maharashtra  and the chief architect/engineer was Hiroji Indulkar. The main palace was constructed using wood, of which only the base pillars remain. The main fort ruins consist of the queen's quarters, six chambers, with each chamber having its own private restroom. In addition, ruins of three watch towers can be seen directly in front of the palace grounds out of which only two remain as the third one was destroyed during a bombardment. The Raigad Fort also has ruins of a market which was accessible to horseback riders. The fort also overlooks an artificial lake known as the Ganga Sagar Lake.\n\n[[File:MahaDarwaja Raigad Fort.JPG|thumb|left|The Maha Darwaja]]\n\nThe only main pathway to the fort passes through the \"Maha Darwaja\" (Huge Door) which was previously closed at sunset. The Maha Darwaja has two huge bastions on both sides of the door which are approximately 65\u201370 feet in height. The top of the fort is 600&nbsp;ft above this door.\n\nThe fort has a famous wall called \"Hirakani Buruj\" (Hirakani Bastion) constructed over a huge steep cliff. The legend goes \"that a woman by the name of Hirakani from a nearby village had come to sell milk to the people living at the fort. She happened to be inside the fort when the gates got closed and locked at sunset. Hearing the cries of her infant son back at the village echo after nightfall, the anxious mother couldn't wait till dawn and courageously climbed down the steep cliff in pitch darkness all for the love of her little one. She later repeated this extraordinary feat in front of Shivaji and was bravely rewarded for it.\" In appreciation of her courage and bravery, Shivaji built the Hirakani Bastion over this cliff.\n\nThe King's ''[[Durbar (court)|durbar]]'' inside the Raigad Fort has a replica of the original throne that faces the main doorway called the ''Nagarkhana Darwaja''. This enclosure had been acoustically designed to aid hearing from the doorway to the throne. A secondary entrance, called the ''Mena Darwaja'', was supposedly the private entrance for the royal ladies of the fort that lead to the queen's quarters. The convoy of the king and the king himself used the ''Palkhi Darwaja.'' To the right of Palkhi Darwaja, is a row of three dark and deep chambers. Historians believe that these were the granaries for the fort.<ref>[http://www.raigadropeway.com/fort.htm Write-up from the Raigad ropeway]</ref>\n\n[[File:Raigad Fort Tak Mak Tok The famous cliff.JPG|thumb|right|The Takmak Tok]]\n\nFrom the fort, one can view the execution point called ''Takmak Tok'', a cliff from which sentenced prisoners were thrown to their death. This area has been fenced off.<ref name=\"gunaji\">{{cite book|last=Gunaji|first=Milind|title=Offbeat Tracks in Maharashtra|publisher=Popular Prakashan|year=2005|pages=41|isbn=81-7154-669-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JIjmDLardesC&pg=PA41&dq=raigad+fort&lr=|accessdate=2009-03-17}}</ref>\n\nThe statue of Shivaji is erected in front of the ruins of the main market avenue that leads to the ''Jagdishwar Mandir'' and his own [[Sam\u0101dhi|Samadhi]] and that of his loyal dog named ''Waghya''. The Samadhi of [[Jijabai]], \nShivaji's mother, can be seen at base village of Pachad.\n\n[[File:Jijamata Samadhi at Pachad, Raigadh, Maharashtra.jpg|thumb|left|The Samadhi of Jijabai]]\n\nAdditional famous attractions of the fort include the Khubladha Buruj, Nane Darwaja and the Hatti Talav (Elephant Lake).\n\n==Incidents==\n* The statue of Shivaji's pet dog was removed by alleged members of the [[Sambhaji Brigade]]<ref>{{cite news|title=73 held for removing Shivaji's dog's statue from Raigad fort|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_73-held-for-removing-shivaji-dogs-statue-from-raigad-fort_1723352|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=DNA}}</ref>  in July 2012 as a protest but was re-instated by Shri Shivaji Raigad Smarak Samiti, the [[Archaeological Survey of India]], sculptor Rambhau Parkhi and the District Administration<ref>{{cite news|title=Vaghyacha putala punha basavala|url=http://72.78.249.107/Sakal/3Aug2012/Enlarge/PuneCity/page8.htm|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=Sakal}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Raigad fort towers.jpg\nFile:Chatrapati Shivaji Maharaj at Raigad.JPG\nFile:Raigad fort long view.jpeg\nFile:RaigadFort1.jpg\nFile:RaigadFort2.jpg\nFile:Raigad Fort Plateau.JPG\nFile:RaigadFort3.jpg\nFile:RaigadFort4.jpg\nFile:RaigadFort7.jpg\nFile:Raigad Fort Inscription.JPG\nFile:MarathaCanon.jpg\nFile:Opes of Raigad Ropeway.JPG\nFile:LegalAdvisorsHouses.jpg\nFile:Raigad gangasagar and takmak tok.jpg\nFile:Raigad ropeway.JPG\nFile:Raigad front towers.jpg\nFile:Raigad Maha Darwaja.jpg\nFile:Darwaja (The Gate).jpg\nFile:Shivaji-Maharajs-Samadhi-in-Raigad.jpg\nFile:RaigadFort6.jpg\nFile:Shivaji Maharaj Raigad.jpg|  Statue of Shivaji maharaj at Raigad fort\nFile:Raygad Map.JPG|Map of Raigad\nFile:Rajad's information.jpg|Information in English\nFile:Raigad Information.JPG|Information of Raigad Fort in Marathi Language\nFile:Hiroji step.JPG| The step of Hiroji Indalkar(Deshmukh). He constructed the fort\nFile:Shilalekh on Raigad.jpeg| \"Prasado Jagadishwarasya....\"\nFile:Bajarpeth and Nagarkhana.jpeg|Bajarpeth and Nagarkhana\nFile:Main Door shape of Raigad fort.JPG|Main Door shape of Raigad fort\nFile:Statue of Shivaji Maharaj.JPG|Statue of Shivaji at the spot where his [[w:Rajyabhishek|rajyabhishek]] took place.\nFile:Ganga sagar talav.JPG|The Ganga Sagar Lake, main water reservoir for the fort\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Raigad Fort}}\n*[http://www.raigadfort.in Raigad Fort Photos & Information (Travel Guide)]\n*http://www.amazingmaharashtra.com/2012/08/raigad.html\n*[http://www.punetrekkers.com/raigad-fort-fort Raigad Fort Trek]\n* [http://indiaouting.com/maharashtra/raigad-fort/ Raigad Fort Pictures]\n*[http://www.yashwantnaik.com/outing/one-trip-raigad-travel-guide-tourist-information/ (Raigad Fort Place to See)]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of forts in Maharashtra]]\n* [[Mughal\u2013Maratha Wars]]\n\n{{Forts in Maharashtra}}\n{{Forts in India}}\n{{MarathaEmpire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raigad Fort}}\n[[Category:Former capital cities in India]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures of the Maratha Empire]]\n[[Category:Forts in Raigad district]]\n[[Category:16th-century forts in India]]\n[[Category:Tourist attractions in Pune district]]\n[[Category:Former populated places in India]]\n[[Category:Hiking trails in India]]\n", "text_old": "{{For|the town in Chhattisgarh|Raigarh}}\n{{distinguish|Rajgad Fort}}\n{{Use dmy dates|date=December 2012}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=December 2012}}\n{{Infobox military installation\n| name = Raigad Fort\n| partof =\n| location = [[Raigad District]], [[Maharashtra]]<br />(near [[Mahad]])\n| image = Raigad fort towers.jpg\n| caption = Raigad Fort towers\n| pushpin_map =India Maharashtra#India\n| pushpin_mapsize =300\n| pushpin_map_caption =Shown within [[Maharashtra]]\n| coordinates = {{coord|18.2335|73.4406|type:landmark_region:IN-MH|format=dms|display=inline}}\n| type = Hill fort\n| code =\n| height = {{convert|1356|m|ft|-2}} ASL\n| ownership = \n*[[Maratha Empire]] (1656-1689; 1707-1818)\n*[[Mughal Empire]] (1689-1707)\n*[[British East India Company]] (1818-1858)\n*[[British Empire]] (1858-1947)\n*[[Government of India|Central Government]] of (1947-present)\n\n| open_to_public = Yes\n| condition =\n| built =\n| builder =  Hiroji Indulkar\n| used =\n| materials = Stone, Lead\n| demolished =\n| battles =\n| current_commander =\n| past_commanders = [[Chhtrapati Shivaji]], [[Chhtrapati Sambhaji]]\n| occupants = \n| events =\n}}\n\n'''Raigad''' ([[Marathi language|Marathi]]:\u0930\u093e\u092f\u0917\u0921) is a [[hill fort]] situated in [[Mahad]], [[Raigad district]] of [[Maharashtra]], India. The Raigad Fort, formerly known as Rairi, was built by Chandraraoji More, the King of Jawali, who was then seized by  [[Shivaji]] who made it his capital in 1674 when he was crowned the King of a Maratha Kingdom which later developed into the [[Maratha Empire]], eventually covering much of western and central India.<ref name=imp>{{cite web | title =Raigarh |publisher=[[Imperial Gazetteer of India]], Volume 21|pages= 47\u201348|year=1909| url = http://dsal.uchicago.edu/reference/gazetteer/pager.html?objectid=DS405.1.I34_V21_053.gif| accessdate = 2014-02-19 }}</ref>\n\nThe fort rises {{convert|820|m|ft|-2}} above the sea level and is located in the [[Sahyadri]] mountain range. There are approximately 1737 steps leading to the fort. The [[Raigad Ropeway]], an [[aerial tramway]]  exists to reach the top of the fort in 10 minutes. The fort was looted and destroyed by the British after it was captured in 1818.{{citation needed|date=March 2018}}\n\n==History==\n[[File:The Ghats from Ryghur.jpg|thumb|left|The Ghats from Ryghur]]\n\n[[Shivaji]]Maharaj seized the fort in 1656, then known as the fort of ''Rairi'' from Chandraraoji More, The King of Jawali. Chhtrapati Shivaji Maharaj renovated and expanded the fort of Rairi and renamed it as Raigad (''King's Fort''). It became the capital of Chhtrapati Shivaji Maharaj's Maratha Empire.{{citation needed|date=January 2016}}\n\nThe villages of Pachad and Raigadwadi are located at the base of the Raigad fort. These two villages were considered very important during the Maratha rule in Raigad. The actual climb to the top of the Raigad fort starts from Pachad. During \n  Shivaji Maharaj's rule, A cavalry of 10,000 was always kept on standby in Pachad village. {{citation needed|date=July 2017}}Chhtrapati\nShivaji Maharaj also built another fort [[Lingana]] around 2 miles away from Raigad. The Lingana fort was used to keep prisoners.{{citation needed|date=May 2018}}\n\n[[File:Raigad 1896.jpg|thumb|Raigad 1896]]\n\nIn 1689, Zulfikhar Khan captured Raigad and Aurangzeb renamed it as ''Islamgad''. In 1707, Siddi Fathekan captured the fort and held it until 1733.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Naravane|first1=M.S.|title=The maritime and coastal forts of India|date=1998|publisher=APH Pub. Corp.|location=New Delhi|isbn=9788170249108|page=61|url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=iHK-BhVXOU4C&oi=fnd&pg=PR9&dq=siddi+raigad+1707&ots=S0VQPZLLnm&sig=9hL2_AZ9l4MfdvzsZhtVWp4QKZY#v=onepage&q=siddi&f=false}}</ref>\n\nIn 1765, The fort of Raigad along with [[Malwan]] in present [[Sindhudurg District]], the southernmost district of [[Maharashtra]], was the target of an armed expedition by the [[East India Company|British East India Company]], which considered it a [[pirate|piratical]] stronghold.{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\nIn 1818, the fort was bombarded and destroyed by cannons from the hill of Kalkai. And on 9 May 1818, as per the treaty, it was handed over to the [[East India Company|British East India Company]].{{citation needed|date=December 2012}}\n\n==Major features==\n\n[[File:Raigad fort walls hidden in the green.JPG|Hidden Walls of the Raigad Fort|thumb|right]]\n[[File:RaigadFort1.jpg|Raigad Fort Palace Ruins|thumb|right]]\n\nThe Raigad Fort was built by [[Shivaji]], Maharashtra  and the chief architect/engineer was Hiroji Indulkar. The main palace was constructed using wood, of which only the base pillars remain. The main fort ruins consist of the queen's quarters, six chambers, with each chamber having its own private restroom. In addition, ruins of three watch towers can be seen directly in front of the palace grounds out of which only two remain as the third one was destroyed during a bombardment. The Raigad Fort also has ruins of a market which was accessible to horseback riders. The fort also overlooks an artificial lake known as the Ganga Sagar Lake.\n\n[[File:MahaDarwaja Raigad Fort.JPG|thumb|left|The Maha Darwaja]]\n\nThe only main pathway to the fort passes through the \"Maha Darwaja\" (Huge Door) which was previously closed at sunset. The Maha Darwaja has two huge bastions on both sides of the door which are approximately 65\u201370 feet in height. The top of the fort is 600&nbsp;ft above this door.\n\nThe fort has a famous wall called \"Hirakani Buruj\" (Hirakani Bastion) constructed over a huge steep cliff. The legend goes \"that a woman by the name of Hirakani from a nearby village had come to sell milk to the people living at the fort. She happened to be inside the fort when the gates got closed and locked at sunset. Hearing the cries of her infant son back at the village echo after nightfall, the anxious mother couldn't wait till dawn and courageously climbed down the steep cliff in pitch darkness all for the love of her little one. She later repeated this extraordinary feat in front of Shivaji and was bravely rewarded for it.\" In appreciation of her courage and bravery, Shivaji built the Hirakani Bastion over this cliff.\n\nThe King's ''[[Durbar (court)|durbar]]'' inside the Raigad Fort has a replica of the original throne that faces the main doorway called the ''Nagarkhana Darwaja''. This enclosure had been acoustically designed to aid hearing from the doorway to the throne. A secondary entrance, called the ''Mena Darwaja'', was supposedly the private entrance for the royal ladies of the fort that lead to the queen's quarters. The convoy of the king and the king himself used the ''Palkhi Darwaja.'' To the right of Palkhi Darwaja, is a row of three dark and deep chambers. Historians believe that these were the granaries for the fort.<ref>[http://www.raigadropeway.com/fort.htm Write-up from the Raigad ropeway]</ref>\n\n[[File:Raigad Fort Tak Mak Tok The famous cliff.JPG|thumb|right|The Takmak Tok]]\n\nFrom the fort, one can view the execution point called ''Takmak Tok'', a cliff from which sentenced prisoners were thrown to their death. This area has been fenced off.<ref name=\"gunaji\">{{cite book|last=Gunaji|first=Milind|title=Offbeat Tracks in Maharashtra|publisher=Popular Prakashan|year=2005|pages=41|isbn=81-7154-669-2|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=JIjmDLardesC&pg=PA41&dq=raigad+fort&lr=|accessdate=2009-03-17}}</ref>\n\nThe statue of Shivaji is erected in front of the ruins of the main market avenue that leads to the ''Jagdishwar Mandir'' and his own [[Sam\u0101dhi|Samadhi]] and that of his loyal dog named ''Waghya''. The Samadhi of [[Jijabai]], \nShivaji's mother, can be seen at base village of Pachad.\n\n[[File:Jijamata Samadhi at Pachad, Raigadh, Maharashtra.jpg|thumb|left|The Samadhi of Jijabai]]\n\nAdditional famous attractions of the fort include the Khubladha Buruj, Nane Darwaja and the Hatti Talav (Elephant Lake).\n\n==Incidents==\n* The statue of Shivaji's pet dog was removed by alleged members of the [[Sambhaji Brigade]]<ref>{{cite news|title=73 held for removing Shivaji's dog's statue from Raigad fort|url=http://www.dnaindia.com/mumbai/report_73-held-for-removing-shivaji-dogs-statue-from-raigad-fort_1723352|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=DNA}}</ref>  in July 2012 as a protest but was re-instated by Shri Shivaji Raigad Smarak Samiti, the [[Archaeological Survey of India]], sculptor Rambhau Parkhi and the District Administration<ref>{{cite news|title=Vaghyacha putala punha basavala|url=http://72.78.249.107/Sakal/3Aug2012/Enlarge/PuneCity/page8.htm|accessdate=4 August 2012|newspaper=Sakal}}</ref>\n\n== Gallery ==\n<gallery>\nFile:Raigad fort towers.jpg\nFile:Chatrapati Shivaji Maharaj at Raigad.JPG\nFile:Raigad fort long view.jpeg\nFile:RaigadFort1.jpg\nFile:RaigadFort2.jpg\nFile:Raigad Fort Plateau.JPG\nFile:RaigadFort3.jpg\nFile:RaigadFort4.jpg\nFile:RaigadFort7.jpg\nFile:Raigad Fort Inscription.JPG\nFile:MarathaCanon.jpg\nFile:Opes of Raigad Ropeway.JPG\nFile:LegalAdvisorsHouses.jpg\nFile:Raigad gangasagar and takmak tok.jpg\nFile:Raigad ropeway.JPG\nFile:Raigad front towers.jpg\nFile:Raigad Maha Darwaja.jpg\nFile:Darwaja (The Gate).jpg\nFile:Shivaji-Maharajs-Samadhi-in-Raigad.jpg\nFile:RaigadFort6.jpg\nFile:Shivaji Maharaj Raigad.jpg|  Statue of Shivaji maharaj at Raigad fort\nFile:Raygad Map.JPG|Map of Raigad\nFile:Rajad's information.jpg|Information in English\nFile:Raigad Information.JPG|Information of Raigad Fort in Marathi Language\nFile:Hiroji step.JPG| The step of Hiroji Indalkar(Deshmukh). He constructed the fort\nFile:Shilalekh on Raigad.jpeg| \"Prasado Jagadishwarasya....\"\nFile:Bajarpeth and Nagarkhana.jpeg|Bajarpeth and Nagarkhana\nFile:Main Door shape of Raigad fort.JPG|Main Door shape of Raigad fort\nFile:Statue of Shivaji Maharaj.JPG|Statue of Shivaji at the spot where his [[w:Rajyabhishek|rajyabhishek]] took place.\nFile:Ganga sagar talav.JPG|The Ganga Sagar Lake, main water reservoir for the fort\n</gallery>\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n{{commons category|Raigad Fort}}\n*[http://www.raigadfort.in Raigad Fort Photos & Information (Travel Guide)]\n*http://www.amazingmaharashtra.com/2012/08/raigad.html\n*[http://www.punetrekkers.com/raigad-fort-fort Raigad Fort Trek]\n* [http://indiaouting.com/maharashtra/raigad-fort/ Raigad Fort Pictures]\n*[http://www.yashwantnaik.com/outing/one-trip-raigad-travel-guide-tourist-information/ (Raigad Fort Place to See)]\n\n== See also ==\n* [[List of forts in Maharashtra]]\n* [[Mughal\u2013Maratha Wars]]\n\n{{Forts in Maharashtra}}\n{{Forts in India}}\n{{MarathaEmpire}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Raigad Fort}}\n[[Category:Former capital cities in India]]\n[[Category:Buildings and structures of the Maratha Empire]]\n[[Category:Forts in 