{"title_page": "Up Your Alley (album)", "text_new": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Up Your Alley\n| type       = [[Studio album]]\n| artist     = [[Joan Jett#Joan Jett & the Blackhearts|Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]\n| cover      = Up_Your_Alley.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1988|5|23}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{Collapsible list|title=Various|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:12px;background:transparent;text-align:left|{{plainlist|\n* [[The Hit Factory]], New York City\n* [[Record Plant]], New York City,\n* [[Bearsville Studios]], Bearsville, New York,\n* Dreamland Recording Studios, Woodstock, New York\n}}}}\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hard rock]]\n* [[glam metal]]\n}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=41|s=20}}\n| label      = [[Blackheart Records|Blackheart]]/[[Columbia Records|CBS-Sony]] <small>(US)</small><br>[[Polydor Records|Polydor]] <small>(Europe and Japan)</small>\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Kenny Laguna]]\n* [[Ric Browde]]\n* [[Desmond Child]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Good Music (Joan Jett and the Blackhearts album)|Good Music]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[The Hit List (Joan Jett album)|The Hit List]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Up Your Alley\n | type        = [[Studio album]]\n | single1     = [[I Hate Myself for Loving You]]\n | single1date = 1988\n | single2     = Little Liar\n | single2date = 1988\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r10403|first=Steve|last=Huey|accessdate=June 27, 2011}}</ref> \n| rev2      = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/up-your-alley-19880811 |title=Joan Jett / Joan Jett & the Blackhearts - Up Yor Alley |last=Tennenbaum |first=Rob |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=August 11, 1988 |accessdate=July 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n| rev3      = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev3Score = B+<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=May 24, 1988|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv588-88.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n|noprose    = yes\n}}\n'''''Up Your Alley''''' is the sixth [[studio album]] by the American rock band [[Joan Jett#Joan Jett & the Blackhearts|Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]. It was originally released in May 1988, on the labels [[Blackheart Records|Blackheart]] and [[Columbia Records|CBS-Sony]] in the U.S., and [[Polydor Records|Polydor]] in (Europe and Japan), a year and a half after their previous album ''[[Good Music (Joan Jett and the Blackhearts album)|Good Music]]''. This album contains the single \"[[I Hate Myself for Loving You]]\", which peaked at No. 8 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref name=\"singles\" >{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-your-alley-mw0000195313/awards |title=Up Your Alley Billboard Singles |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=July 10, 2015 }}</ref> and had been used as the theme song for ''[[NBC Sunday Night Football|Sunday Night Football]]'' [[National Football League|NFL]] games in America (with altered lyrics, by two singers) during the [[2006 NFL season|2006]] and [[2007 NFL season|2007 seasons]]. The follow-up single \"Little Liar\" continued Jett's chart success, peaking at No. 19 on the Hot 100 in late 1988/early 1989.<ref name=\"singles\" />\n\n''Up Your Alley'' peaked at No. 19 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart<ref name=\"album\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-your-alley-mw0000195313/awards|title=Up Your Alley Billboard Albums |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=July 10, 2015 }}</ref> and has since been certified [[RIAA certification|Platinum]].<ref name=\"RIAA\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database |title=RIAA Searchable Database: search for Jett |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |accessdate=July 10, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFormer [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] guitarist [[Mick Taylor]] played the guitar solo on \"I Hate Myself for Loving You\".<ref>Wissmuller, Christian (Oct/Nov 2007) \"Mick Taylor: Soul Survivor\". ''Jazzed Magazine''.</ref>\n\n\"I Hate Myself for Loving You\" was released as the first single, backed with a live version of the Jett composition \"Love Is Pain\" (the original version of which appears on 1981's ''[[I Love Rock 'n Roll (album)|I Love Rock 'n Roll]]'').  \"Little Liar\" was the second single, backed with an obscure Jett/Laguna composition \"What Can I Do for You\", which had been recorded for a movie Jett was set to make in 1979 that was never completed. The song eventually turned up again on the Jett fan-club only CD 1979. For Record Store Day in 2015, the track was included on the [https://www.turntablelab.com/products/joan-jett-the-first-sessions-colored-vinyl-vinyl-lp-record-store-day limited edition (4000 split color vinyl)  LP \"The First Sessions\"] documenting the first several songs Joan wrote with Kenny Laguna, her newly acquired producer.  This was to be the first of many Jett/Laguna collaborations, as they were inseparable from that moment in 1979 to the present day. \n\nTwo videos were shot for \"Little Liar\", the first, a concept video, feature a slightly confusing storyline with two Joans (one in white, one in black) interacting. After seeing the result of the first Little Liar video, Jett was unhappy with the silliness and visual translation so immediately shot a new live video (synced with the studio version of the song) for this track. The new video captured a more authentic feel with raw live shots combined with cutaways and studio shot closeups of Joan. It was a more stylized live video with [[David Bowie#1972\u201373: Ziggy Stardust|Ziggy Stardust]]-like artistic flourishes.  \n\n== Awards & acclamation ==\nJoan Jett and the Blackhearts were nominated for a [https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/joan-jett-and-blackhearts GRAMMY] in 1988 for [https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/joan-jett-and-blackhearts <nowiki>[BEST ROCK PERFORMANCE BY A DUO OR GROUP WITH VOCAL]  for \"I Hate Myself For Loving You\" (Single)</nowiki>]\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n\n| title1 = [[I Hate Myself for Loving You]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Joan Jett]]|[[Desmond Child]]}}\n| length1 = 4:07\n\n| title2 = Ridin' with James Dean\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Jett|Ricky Byrd|[[Ric Browde]]}}\n| length2 = 3:17\n\n| title3 = Little Liar\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Jett|Child}}\n| length3 = 4:01\n\n| title4 = Tulane\n| note4 = [[Chuck Berry]] cover\n| writer4 = [[Chuck Berry]]\n| length4 = 2:54\n\n| title5 = [[I Wanna Be Your Dog]]\n| note5 = [[The Stooges]] cover\n| writer5 = {{hlist|[[Iggy Pop|James Osterberg Jr.]]|[[Dave Alexander (musician)|Dave Alexander]]|[[Ron Asheton]]|[[Scott Asheton]]}}\n| length5 = 5:12\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| total_length = 41:20\n\n| title6 = I Still Dream About You\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Jett|Byrd|Gary Rottger}}\n| length6 = 3:23\n\n| title7 = You Want In, I Want Out\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Jett|Child}}\n| length7 = 4:15\n\n| title8 = Just Like in the Movies\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Jett|Browde|Byrd|[[Kenny Laguna]]}}\n| length8 = 3:05\n\n| title9 = Desire\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Jett|[[Diane Warren]]|Laguna}}\n| length9 = 3:53\n\n| title10 = Back It Up\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Jett|Byrd|Browde}}\n| length10 = 3:31\n\n| title11 = Play That Song Again\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Jett|Byrd|[[Frank Carillo]]}}\n| length11 = 3:42\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title=Up Your Alley ''liner notes''|year=1988|publisher=[[Blackheart Records|Blackheart]]/[[Columbia Records|CBS-Sony]]/[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Joan Jett and the Blackhearts\n*[[Joan Jett]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]]s\n*Ricky Byrd&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead guitars]], [[backing vocals]]\n*[[Kasim Sulton]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar|bass]], backing vocals\n*[[Thommy Price]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n;Additional musicians\n*The Uptown Horns:\n**Crispin Choe&nbsp;\u2013 [[baritone saxophone]]\n**Arno Hecht&nbsp;\u2013 [[tenor saxophone]]\n**Paul Litteral&nbsp;\u2013 [[trumpet]]\n**Robert Funk&nbsp;\u2013 [[trombone]]\n*Ronnie Lawson&nbsp;\u2013 [[Electronic keyboard|keyboards]]\n*[[Mick Taylor]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar solo on track 1\n*[[Frank Carillo]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar; [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n*[[Kenny Laguna]]&nbsp;\u2013 various instruments; backing vocals\n*[[Desmond Child]]&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*Chuck Kentis&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*Louie Merlino&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*Paul Carrizzo&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n{{Col-2}}\n;Production team\n*[[Kenny Laguna]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Record producer|producer]] on all tracks\n*[[Ric Browde]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer on tracks 2, 4-6, 8-11\n*[[Desmond Child]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer on tracks 1 and 3\n*[[Thom Panunzio]]&nbsp;\u2013 associate producer; [[audio engineer|engineer]]; [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixer]]\n*Jay Healy&nbsp;\u2013 engineer; mixer on track 5\n*Arthur Payson&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n*James A. Ball&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n*John Aiosa&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n*Andrew Spigleman&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*David Cook&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Rich Travali&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Roger Talkov&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Scott Forman&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Teddy Trewhella&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Thom Cadley&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*[[Bob Ludwig]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]] at [[Masterdisk]], New York\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1988)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{album chart|Canada|48|chartid=8728|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n|-\n! scope=\"row\"| Finnish Albums ([[The Official Finnish Charts|Suomen virallinen lista]])<ref>{{cite book |last=Pennanen |first=Timo |title=Sis\u00e4lt\u00e4\u00e4 hitin \u2013 levyt ja esitt\u00e4j\u00e4t Suomen musiikkilistoilla vuodesta 1972 |language=Finnish |edition=1st |location=Helsinki |publisher=[[Otava (publisher)|Kustannusosakeyhti\u00f6 Otava]] |year=2006 |isbn=978-951-1-21053-5}}</ref>\n| 33\n|-\n{{album chart|New Zealand|31|artist=Joan Jett & the Blackhearts|album=Up Your Alley|rowheader=true|accessdate=August 30, 2019}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Sweden|16|artist=Joan Jett & the Blackhearts|album=Up Your Alley|rowheader=true|accessdate=July 10, 2015}}\n|-\n{{album chart|Billboard200|19|artist=Joan Jett the Blackhearts|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n|}\n\n==Certifications==\n{{Certification Table Top}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=Canada|artist=Joan Jett and the Blackhearts|title=Up Your Alley|award=Gold|type=album|relyear=1988|certyear=1988|date=October 31, 1988|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Entry|region=United States|artist=Joan Jett & the Blackhearts|title=Up Your Alley|award=Platinum|type=album|relyear=1988|certyear=1989|date=February 17, 1989|accessdate=April 15, 2020}}\n{{Certification Table Bottom|nosales=yes}}\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{Discogs master|type=album|1813029|name=Up Your Alley}}\n\n{{Joan Jett}}\n\n[[Category:Joan Jett albums]]\n[[Category:1988 albums]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Desmond Child]]\n[[Category:Albums produced by Thom Panunzio]]\n[[Category:Blackheart Records albums]]\n[[Category:Columbia Records albums]]\n[[Category:Polydor Records albums]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use mdy dates|date=July 2015}}\n{{Infobox album\n| name       = Up Your Alley\n| type       = [[Studio album]]\n| artist     = [[Joan Jett#Joan Jett & the Blackhearts|Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]\n| cover      = Up_Your_Alley.jpg\n| alt        =\n| released   = {{Start date|1988|5|23}}\n| recorded   =\n| venue      =\n| studio     = {{Collapsible list|title=Various|titlestyle=font-weight:normal;font-size:12px;background:transparent;text-align:left|{{plainlist|\n* [[The Hit Factory]], New York City\n* [[Record Plant]], New York City,\n* [[Bearsville Studios]], Bearsville, New York,\n* Dreamland Recording Studios, Woodstock, New York\n}}}}\n| genre      = {{flatlist|\n* [[Hard rock]]\n* [[glam metal]]\n}}\n| length     = {{duration|m=41|s=20}}\n| label      = [[Blackheart Records|Blackheart]]/[[Columbia Records|CBS-Sony]] <small>(US)</small><br>[[Polydor Records|Polydor]] <small>(Europe and Japan)</small>\n| producer   = {{flatlist|\n* [[Kenny Laguna]]\n* [[Ric Browde]]\n* [[Desmond Child]]\n}}\n| prev_title = [[Good Music (Joan Jett and the Blackhearts album)|Good Music]]\n| prev_year  = 1986\n| next_title = [[The Hit List (Joan Jett album)|The Hit List]]\n| next_year  = 1990\n| misc       = {{Singles\n | name        = Up Your Alley\n | type        = [[Studio album]]\n | single1     = [[I Hate Myself for Loving You]]\n | single1date = 1988\n | single2     = Little Liar\n | single2date = 1988\n}}\n}}\n{{Album ratings\n| rev1      = [[AllMusic]]\n| rev1Score = {{Rating|2|5}}<ref>{{Allmusic|class=album|id=r10403|first=Steve|last=Huey|accessdate=June 27, 2011}}</ref> \n| rev2      = ''[[Rolling Stone]]''\n| rev2Score = {{Rating|3|5}}<ref>{{cite magazine |url=https://www.rollingstone.com/music/albumreviews/up-your-alley-19880811 |title=Joan Jett / Joan Jett & the Blackhearts - Up Yor Alley |last=Tennenbaum |first=Rob |magazine=[[Rolling Stone]] |date=August 11, 1988 |accessdate=July 9, 2015 }}</ref>\n| rev3      = ''[[The Village Voice]]''\n| rev3Score = B+<ref name=\"Christgau\">{{cite news|last=Christgau|first=Robert|authorlink=Robert Christgau|date=May 24, 1988|url=http://www.robertchristgau.com/xg/cg/cgv588-88.php|title=Consumer Guide|newspaper=[[The Village Voice]]|location=New York|accessdate=March 30, 2013}}</ref>\n|noprose    = yes\n}}\n'''''Up Your Alley''''' is the sixth [[studio album]] by the American rock band [[Joan Jett#Joan Jett & the Blackhearts|Joan Jett and the Blackhearts]]. It was originally released in May 1988, on the labels [[Blackheart Records|Blackheart]] and [[Columbia Records|CBS-Sony]] in the U.S., and [[Polydor Records|Polydor]] in (Europe and Japan), a year and a half after their previous album ''[[Good Music (Joan Jett and the Blackhearts album)|Good Music]]''. This album contains the single \"[[I Hate Myself for Loving You]]\", which peaked at No. 8 on the [[Billboard Hot 100|''Billboard'' Hot 100]],<ref name=\"singles\" >{{cite web |url= http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-your-alley-mw0000195313/awards |title=Up Your Alley Billboard Singles |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=July 10, 2015 }}</ref> and had been used as the theme song for ''[[NBC Sunday Night Football|Sunday Night Football]]'' [[National Football League|NFL]] games in America (with altered lyrics, by two singers) during the [[2006 NFL season|2006]] and [[2007 NFL season|2007 seasons]]. The follow-up single \"Little Liar\" continued Jett's chart success, peaking at No. 19 on the Hot 100 in late 1988/early 1989.<ref name=\"singles\" />\n\n''Up Your Alley'' peaked at No. 19 on the [[Billboard 200|''Billboard'' 200]] albums chart<ref name=\"album\" >{{cite web |url=http://www.allmusic.com/album/up-your-alley-mw0000195313/awards|title=Up Your Alley Billboard Albums |work=[[AllMusic]] |publisher=[[All Media Network]] |accessdate=July 10, 2015 }}</ref> and has since been certified [[RIAA certification|Platinum]].<ref name=\"RIAA\" >{{cite web |url=https://www.riaa.com/goldandplatinumdata.php?content_selector=gold-platinum-searchable-database |title=RIAA Searchable Database: search for Jett |publisher=[[Recording Industry Association of America]] |accessdate=July 10, 2015 }}</ref>\n\nFormer [[The Rolling Stones|Rolling Stones]] guitarist [[Mick Taylor]] played the guitar solo on \"I Hate Myself for Loving You\".<ref>Wissmuller, Christian (Oct/Nov 2007) \"Mick Taylor: Soul Survivor\". ''Jazzed Magazine''.</ref>\n\n\"I Hate Myself for Loving You\" was released as the first single, backed with a live version of the Jett composition \"Love Is Pain\" (the original version of which appears on 1981's ''[[I Love Rock 'n Roll (album)|I Love Rock 'n Roll]]'').  \"Little Liar\" was the second single, backed with an obscure Jett/Laguna composition \"What Can I Do for You\", which had been recorded for a movie Jett was set to make in 1979 that was never completed. The song eventually turned up again on the Jett fan-club only CD 1979. For Record Store Day in 2015, the track was included on the [https://www.turntablelab.com/products/joan-jett-the-first-sessions-colored-vinyl-vinyl-lp-record-store-day limited edition (4000 split color vinyl)  LP \"The First Sessions\"] documenting the first several songs Joan wrote with Kenny Laguna, her newly acquired producer.  This was to be the first of many Jett/Laguna collaborations, as they were inseparable from that moment in 1979 to the present day. \n\nTwo videos were shot for \"Little Liar\", the first, a concept video, feature a slightly confusing storyline with two Joans (one in white, one in black) interacting. After seeing the result of the first Little Liar video, Jett was unhappy with the silliness and visual translation so immediately shot a new live video (synced with the studio version of the song) for this track. The new video captured a more authentic feel with raw live shots combined with cutaways and studio shot closeups of Joan. It was a more stylized live video with [[David Bowie#1972\u201373: Ziggy Stardust|Ziggy Stardust]]-like artistic flourishes.  \n\n\n\n== Awards & acclamation ==\nJoan Jett and the Blackhearts were nominated for a [https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/joan-jett-and-blackhearts GRAMMY] in 1988 for [https://www.grammy.com/grammys/artists/joan-jett-and-blackhearts <nowiki>[BEST ROCK PERFORMANCE BY A DUO OR GROUP WITH VOCAL]  for \"I Hate Myself For Loving You\" (Single)</nowiki>]\n\n==Track listing==\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side one\n\n| title1 = [[I Hate Myself for Loving You]]\n| writer1 = {{hlist|[[Joan Jett]]|[[Desmond Child]]}}\n| length1 = 4:07\n\n| title2 = Ridin' with James Dean\n| writer2 = {{hlist|Jett|Ricky Byrd|[[Ric Browde]]}}\n| length2 = 3:17\n\n| title3 = Little Liar\n| writer3 = {{hlist|Jett|Child}}\n| length3 = 4:01\n\n| title4 = Tulane\n| note4 = [[Chuck Berry]] cover\n| writer4 = [[Chuck Berry]]\n| length4 = 2:54\n\n| title5 = [[I Wanna Be Your Dog]]\n| note5 = [[The Stooges]] cover\n| writer5 = {{hlist|[[Iggy Pop|James Osterberg Jr.]]|[[Dave Alexander (musician)|Dave Alexander]]|[[Ron Asheton]]|[[Scott Asheton]]}}\n| length5 = 5:12\n}}\n\n{{Track listing\n| headline = Side two\n| total_length = 41:20\n\n| title6 = I Still Dream About You\n| writer6 = {{hlist|Jett|Byrd|Gary Rottger}}\n| length6 = 3:23\n\n| title7 = You Want In, I Want Out\n| writer7 = {{hlist|Jett|Child}}\n| length7 = 4:15\n\n| title8 = Just Like in the Movies\n| writer8 = {{hlist|Jett|Browde|Byrd|[[Kenny Laguna]]}}\n| length8 = 3:05\n\n| title9 = Desire\n| writer9 = {{hlist|Jett|[[Diane Warren]]|Laguna}}\n| length9 = 3:53\n\n| title10 = Back It Up\n| writer10 = {{hlist|Jett|Byrd|Browde}}\n| length10 = 3:31\n\n| title11 = Play That Song Again\n| writer11 = {{hlist|Jett|Byrd|[[Frank Carillo]]}}\n| length11 = 3:42\n}}\n\n==Personnel==\nCredits are adapted from the album's liner notes.<ref name=\"booklet\">{{cite book|title=Up Your Alley ''liner notes''|year=1988|publisher=[[Blackheart Records|Blackheart]]/[[Columbia Records|CBS-Sony]]/[[Polydor Records|Polydor]]}}</ref>\n{{col-begin}}\n{{Col-2}}\n;Joan Jett and the Blackhearts\n*[[Joan Jett]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead vocals]], [[rhythm guitar]]s\n*Ricky Byrd&nbsp;\u2013 [[lead guitars]], [[backing vocals]]\n*[[Kasim Sulton]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[bass guitar|bass]], backing vocals\n*[[Thommy Price]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Drum kit|drums]]\n;Additional musicians\n*The Uptown Horns:\n**Crispin Choe&nbsp;\u2013 [[baritone saxophone]]\n**Arno Hecht&nbsp;\u2013 [[tenor saxophone]]\n**Paul Litteral&nbsp;\u2013 [[trumpet]]\n**Robert Funk&nbsp;\u2013 [[trombone]]\n*Ronnie Lawson&nbsp;\u2013 [[Electronic keyboard|keyboards]]\n*[[Mick Taylor]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar solo on track 1\n*[[Frank Carillo]]&nbsp;\u2013 guitar; [[Backing vocalist|backing vocals]]\n*[[Kenny Laguna]]&nbsp;\u2013 various instruments; backing vocals\n*[[Desmond Child]]&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*Chuck Kentis&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*Louie Merlino&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n*Paul Carrizzo&nbsp;\u2013 backing vocals\n{{Col-2}}\n;Production team\n*[[Kenny Laguna]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Record producer|producer]] on all tracks\n*[[Ric Browde]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer on tracks 2, 4-6, 8-11\n*[[Desmond Child]]&nbsp;\u2013 producer on tracks 1 and 3\n*[[Thom Panunzio]]&nbsp;\u2013 associate producer; [[audio engineer|engineer]]; [[Audio mixing (recorded music)|mixer]]\n*Jay Healy&nbsp;\u2013 engineer; mixer on track 5\n*Arthur Payson&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n*James A. Ball&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n*John Aiosa&nbsp;\u2013 engineer\n*Andrew Spigleman&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*David Cook&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Rich Travali&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Roger Talkov&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Scott Forman&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Teddy Trewhella&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*Thom Cadley&nbsp;\u2013 assistant engineer\n*[[Bob Ludwig]]&nbsp;\u2013 [[Audio mastering|mastering]] at [[Masterdisk]], New York\n{{col-end}}\n\n==Charts==\n{| class=\"wikitable sortable plainrowheaders\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|-\n! scope=\"col\"| Chart (1988)\n! scope=\"col\"| Peak<br/>position\n|-\n{{album chart|Canada|48|chartid=8728|rowheader=true|accessdate=April 15, 20